<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack     08-28 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth Man Arrested in Racial Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sixth man was arrested and charged Monday in
connection with the shooting death of a 16-year-old black youth who
police said was attacked by a bat-wielding gang of whites in
Brooklyn.
   Joseph Serrano, 20, surrendered to detectives and was charged
with first-degree assault, first-degree riot, aggravated harassment,
menacing and civil rights violations, said Officer Edward Feeney, a
police spokesman.
   In the neighborhood of Bensonhurst, meanwhile, where Yusef
Hawkins was shot to death Wednesday night, there were signs that
tempers were cooling off following two days of racial confrontations.
   About a dozen blacks led about 150 white residents on a short
walk through the streets where the killing occurred. Dozens of
people, angry over a third day of demonstrations in their
neighborhood, stood facing the demonstrators but were quieter and
less confrontational than residents of the predominantly white
community had been Saturday and Sunday.
   Before the start of the march, seven Catholic priests gathered on
a street corner and led about 75 Bensonhurst residents in prayer.
   The Rev. Arthur Minichello, a local pastor, said they were
praying for the family of the victim.
   ``This is the community of Bensonhurst, not the idiots that are
down the block,'' said 26-year-old James Tancredi.
   Police are also investigating whether a seventh man who could be
a suspect in the shooting on Wednesday may have fled to Italy, The
New York Times reported in its Tuesday editions.
   Detectives, however, still believe that 18-year-old Joseph Fama,
whose parents were born in Italy and who holds dual American and
Italian citizenship, remains in the United States, the newspaper
said.
   Fama was identified by a witness as the triggerman in the attack.
   In a related development Monday, a 22-year-old construction
worker was freed on bail after pleading innocent to charges he tried
to intimidate the woman who authorities believe may have
precipitated the attack by befriending the black youths.
   Cosmo Camia of Brooklyn, was arrested Saturday after he twice
drove by the home of Gina Feliciano and allegedly yelled threats.
Camia, charged with two felony counts of intimidating a witness and
two counts of harassment, both violations, faces up to four years in
prison on each of the intimidation charges.
   Apart from Serrano, Kenneth Mondello, 18, Pasquale Raucci, 19,
Charles Stressler, 21, Steven Curreri, 18, and James Patino, 24,
were charged in the attack. The five men were freed on bail over the
weekend.
</TEXT>
