<FIRST>r p PM-Pepper'sSeat     08-28 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper's Seat,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Birthplace More Important Than Issues In House Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivalries between Hispanics and other Americans have
crowded out issues in the tight, emotion-charged race for the U.S.
House seat left vacant by the death of Democratic Rep. Claude Pepper.
   Voting Tuesday is expected to be by ethnic, more than party,
lines, with Hispanics rallying around a Havana-born woman trying to
become the first Cuban-American in Congress, and most non-Latin
whites and blacks turning out for a Brooklyn-born, Jewish attorney.
That scenario, indicated in polling, would result in a photo-finish
race.
   While Pepper, a national advocate for the elderly and poor who
died May 30 at age 88, overwhelmed opponents for 27 years _ and drew
no opposition last year _ Tuesday's special election is the
culmination of one of the most bitter campaigns Florida has seen.
   Attorney Gerald Richman, making his first run for elective
office, defied political pundits and his own party's local hierarchy
by winning the Democratic nomination by a landslide in an Aug. 15
runoff.
   GOP nominee Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a state senator, put together a
well-organized, well-funded campaign featuring appearances by
President Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle.
   The president's son, Jeb Bush, is her campaign chairman and the
Republican Party is trying to add to its momentum in Florida and
increase its 10-8 majority in the congressional delegation.
   However, Richman charged charged from Democratic dark horse to
running neck-and-neck with Ms. Ros-Lehtinen in a campaign in which
he repeatedly said ``this is an American seat.'' He called Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen a right-wing extremist.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen said Richman was running a campaign of racism
and bigotry and she refused to debate him during their two-week
campaign.
   Richman, whose thin, inexperienced campaign staff was beefed up
by national party help after his nomination, said his theme has been
``for all the people,'' and that the ``American seat'' comment means
voters shouldn't choose by place of birth.
   It was Republican national leader Lee Atwater who set the tone by
saying the party wanted to elect a Cuban-American, Richman says.
   He calls the bigotry charges ``a phony issue. ... My opponent has
cleverly fanned the flames and used it as an excuse not to debate.''
   Adding to the ethnic heat was an Aug. 20 comment by the Rev.
Thomas Ferguson, chairman of the black Republican caucus, as he
toured churches with Ms. Ros-Lehtinen. He said ``Mr. Richman does
not believe in God like we do.''
   And in the campaign's final weekend, a Spanish-language flier
went out to Hispanics in the 18th District, reading:
   ``We want Mr. Gerald Richman to understand one thing: `We, too,
are Americans.' No, we weren't born in Brooklyn, New York, like him.
No, we don't speak English the same way he does.''
   Jeff Eller, spokesman for Richman, called the flier ``bald
hypocrisy.''
   Overall, they have similar views on most issues, but they differ
sharply on some emotional issues, such as:
   _Abortion: Ms. Ros-Lehtinen favors more restrictions, Richman
favors more choice. With polls indicating most voters are
pro-choice, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen says abortion is not a congressional
issue.
   _Orlando Bosch: Ms. Ros-Lehtinen has argued for freedom for the
anti-Castro militant considered a hero by many Cuban exiles. Richman
says Bosch, called a terrorist by U.S. officials, should be deported
to a third country.
   _Prayer in schools: Ms. Ros-Lehtinen favors a constitutional
amendment allowing voluntary prayer; Richman is opposed. She also
wants a constitutional amendment to outlaw flag burning, which
Richman opposes.
   _Official English: Ms. Ros-Lehtinen fought in the Legislature to
block implementation of an official English amendment passed by
voters. Richman said he would support making English the nation's
official language.
   While Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, wife of U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen,
campaigns as tough on crime, Richman has tried to turn her
opposition to gun control into proof she is weak on crime, saying
she favors allowing criminals easy access to guns.
</TEXT>
