<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock singer and songwriter Don Henley
thinks of himself as a socially motivated citizen who happens to be
in the rock 'n' roll business.
   ``I read novels, political biographies _ there's plenty of news
everywhere,'' he said in a recent interview from Boston. ``There's a
lot of news but not much analysis.''
   Henley, 42, formerly of the Eagles, began a solo career in 1982.
   His current album, ``The End of the Innocence,'' looks critically
at greed and corruption in America.
   ``It's about trying to reconcile the way things ought to be with
the way things are,'' Henley said. ``It's about trying to grow up.''
