<TEXT>
   James Meredith, the first black student to
attend the University of Mississippi, is moving to San Diego after
five years in Cincinnati.
   Meredith, 56, would not disclose his plans. He came to Cincinnati
in 1984 as a visiting professor at the University of Cincinnati's
African-American Studies Department.
   Meredith later criticized the school, which did not renew his
one-year contract, for not graduating enough black athletes.
University officials said at least 51 black athletes had graduated
since 1964.
   Meredith lost a bid for a seat on the Cincinnati Board of
Education in 1985 and ran an unsuccessful campaign for the state
board of education.
   He spent recent years in various trades including tree farming
and financial counseling.
   ``I have no complaints,'' Meredith said at a going away party
Sunday. ``Everything I came here to do, I accomplished.''
