<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-28 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three love-stuck couples took a break during
the Great American Kiss-Off to rest their jaws and make wedding vows.
   They started kissing for the money, but showed it was really for
love Saturday in the contest at a furniture store parking lot.
   The six were among six couples still contesting the $10,000 grand
prize Sunday after going at it for 18 straight 12-hours days.
   Pronounced husband and wife, the three couples began perhaps the
longest post-nuptial kisses in history.
   ``Here they go again,'' said one woman, shaking her head.
   The idea for the parking-lot wedding was hatched last week when
Lloyd Gubler, 23, and Laura Sue Bradley, 25 realized they would have
to cancel their wedding plans to take part in the Kiss-Off.
   ``At first, I thought, `Getting married in a parking lot? I don't
know,''' said Laura.
   The two couples who joined them were John Castle, 20, and Crystal
Larribas, 18; and Jason Knapp, 20, and Menette McVey, 19.
   The three couples saved up five-minute break periods allowed in
the contest so they could have an hour for their weddings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEMING, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-month-old mallard known as It's Miller
Time waddled off with the title of the world's fastest duck at the
Great American Duck Race.
   ``Finally,'' said trainer Gary Miller of Anthony, N.M. ``It's
been a long time coming, with so many second and third places. It's
a great feeling to win.''
   Miller, who has entered ducks eight-straight years, said he was
nervous during the early heats Saturday.
   ``But I calmed down and so did the duck and we did it,'' he said.
   His duck covered the 16-foot track at the Deming Duck Downs on
the lawn of the Luna County Courthouse in 1.42 seconds, winning by a
bill in a photo finish over several hundred other contestants. The
time was well off the record of 1.23 seconds by Oliver South two
years ago.
   Miller, who took home about $3,000 in prizes, said he trained his
ducks only nine days but had them on a special high-protein diet.
   An estimated crowd of 25,000 attended the weekend events, which
included the race, a tortilla toss, a chili cookoff and a best
dressed duck contest.
</TEXT>
