<FIRST>r a PM-Newsman-Drugs     08-28 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newsman-Drugs,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York City Anchor Recounts Battle With Drugs, Booze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   WCBS-TV newsman Jim Jensen says he was able to
give up his cocaine habit quickly, but the torturous withdrawal to
break his addiction to Valium pushed him to the point of considering
suicide.
   ``It was a monumental depression,'' the 62-year-old Jensen said
in this week's People magazine. ``You feel as though there's no
future left, you might as well die.''
   WCBS and family members persuaded him to enter the depression
unit at St. Mary's hospital in Minneapolis shortly after his 25th
anniversary party at the CBS affiliate in February.
   The depression was caused by kicking a 4{-year addiction to
Valium, which a doctor prescribed for a sleep disorder, Jensen said.
   ``There was a bridge over the Mississippi _ I thought about
that,'' he said. ``I never actively did anything, but the thoughts
cross your mind.''
   Jensen said he was bothered by losing his anchor spot, but has
been back at work since June as a senior correspondent.
   He said he takes an antidepressant drug every day, and hopes to
be off it in a few months. He sees a psychiatrist once a week and
attends daily Alcoholics Anonymous meetings. Jensen said he
celebrated one year of sobriety Aug. 2.
   ``People on the street, they pat me on the back,'' he said.
``It's wonderful. They're all pulling for me. I can't let them
down.''
</TEXT>
