<FIRST>r a PM-DrugPoll     08-28 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Poll,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Half Back Military Involvement vs Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half the American public favors deploying U.S.
troops against drug dealers overseas, although most believe drug
traffickers would try to retaliate violently, a poll has found.
   Fifty-three percent of the 600 adults in the Gallup poll for
Newsweek magazine said they would favor sending troops to fight or
arrest drug traffickers in Colombia or other major drug exporting
centers.
   Thirty-four percent opposed and 13 percent were not sure, the
magazine reported Sunday.
   At the same time, 64 percent said they believed the drug cartels
would retaliate with ``increased violence against Americans'' if
more foreign drug traffickers were brought to this country for
prosecution.
   Nineteen percent did not expect retaliation and 17 percent were
unsure.
   The poll found 85 percent support penalties against casual users
of illegal drugs, such as the temporary suspension of a driver's
license.
   Gallup conducted the poll by telephone Thursday and Friday. The
results have a 5-point margin of sampling error.
</TEXT>
