<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Party     08-28 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Party,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chuck Berry Helps Scientists Celebrate Voyager-Neptune Encounter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Voyager-Neptune, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a tape recording of his voice floated
past Neptune, rock 'n' roll legend Chuck Berry laid down an earthy
beat for dancing scientists at a Voyager bash outside the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
   ``Go, Voyager, go!'' Berry sang as he belted out a slightly
modified version of his classic ``Johnny B. Goode.'' A recording of
that song was among the cultural and historical items aboard aboard
Voyager 2, 2.76 billion miles from Earth.
   Sunday night's celebration, attended by 1,500 scientists,
engineers and their families, was part of a special program
sponsored by The Planetary Society and televised on Turner
Broadcasting System in the United States, Asahi Broadcasting in
Japan and on state television in the Soviet Union, said astronomer
Carl Sagan, who was host of the party.
   Voyager 2 achieved its close encounter with Neptune on Thursday
night and flew past the moon Triton on Friday, capping its historic
exploration of the outer solar system.
   In case some alien civilization ever stumbles upon Voyager 2 or
its twin, Voyager 1, the space probes each carry a 12-inch copper
record containing greetings in 60 languages and a variety of sounds
from Earth, including ``Johnny B. Goode.''
   ``I could never be gratified more than being part of that,''
Berry said after the concert, where many normally somber scientists
dancing to the beat.
   Sagan, a Cornell University astronomer who helped popularize
space science with his ``Cosmos'' TV series, ended the celebration
by saying, ``I'm going to go get some sleep, or maybe I'll do a
little dancing.''
</TEXT>
