<DOCNO> AP890828-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MexicanBobsledders     08-28 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexican Bobsledders,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Still Trying to `Break the Ice'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an uphill climb, they concede, but members of
the Mexican Olympic bobsled team say they still expect someday to
become real competitors in the winter sport.
   That goal comes despite the fact the Tames brothers finished 36th
and 37th at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary. And it comes
despite the fact they still have no sled, little money and are
hundreds of miles from the nearest snow.
   The brothers are seriously preparing for another run at breaking
into bobsledding respectability, said Eduardo Tames. They are
raising money for a November training trip to Calgary and hope to
travel to Europe in 1990 for much-needed competition.
   And what's more, Tames said, the team is recruiting.
   ``We're trying to find Mexicans who play college football, who
have the leg strength to get faster starts,'' he said Sunday. ``We
want to have 10 to 12 guys on our team next time.''
   Tames said he and brothers Jorge, Adrian and Roberto, who are
from Guadalajara and work at a Dallas restaurant, plan to go to
several Mexican cities for the recruiting. They would like to take
several new recruits to Calgary for the November practice runs.
   ``We'll have to let them try the sleds,'' he said. ``Sometimes,
they don't like that.''
   For the time being, Tames and his brothers are working out every
morning in Dallas, going out early to beat the searing Texas heat.
Snow is the furthest thing from their minds, he said, as they push
and ride a wheeled cart across a large parking lot to get down their
timing and strengthen their bodies.
   ``We need to be more explosive, to push the sled faster at the
beginning,'' he said.
   They would like to buy their own sled, but that seems like an
idle dream because even used sleds go for $10,000 to $20,000.
   For now, they are simply doing well to afford $1,000 weekly just
to rent a sled during their Canadian training trip and meet the $16
fee they must pay track operators for each practice run.
   Mexican officials were pleased with the team's finish at Calgary
and have already given them permission to represent the financially
struggling country again if the brothers can find their own funding
for the 1992 games.
   Wearing red and white donated uniforms, the brothers finished
ahead of Portugal, a Japanese team, one from the Virgin Islands and
a U.S. entry that abandoned its last run.
   ``We didn't finish last in 1988 so that was pretty good for us,''
Tames said. ``We definitely want to improve that performance.''
   Improvement will be a costly endeavor, and a medal is an
unthinkable goal, but Tames says nothing can beat the thrill he and
his brothers find in bobsledding.
   ``It's really different from anything I've ever tried before,''
he said, adding that no amusement park roller coaster can even come
close.
   ``The only way you can tell if you're going to like it is to try
the sled. It's really scary. It's really fast until your reflexes
and eyes adjust to the speed you're running.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
