<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--PlaneMishap     08-28 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Plane Mishap,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hydraulic Problems Force Jetliner Back to Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines Boeing 767 with 215 people aboard
was forced to return to Stapleton International Airport after
takeoff when it experienced hydraulic trouble in its landing gear,
authorities said.
   No one was hurt in Sunday night's incident.
   The hydraulic problems were in the left main landing gear, said
Stapleton spokesman Jack McGuire. He said he assumed from the
uneventful return of the plane that the gear must have stayed down
after the takeoff.
   McGuire did not know what time the plane took off for New York,
but said it reported trouble eight minutes into the flight and was
reported back at the gate at 9:35 p.m. MDT.
   United Airlines spokesman Jack Ekey in Denver declined to comment.
   A passenger who spoke on condition of anonymity said the plane
took off at about 7 p.m. About 1{ hours into the flight, he said,
the pilot reported a problem, and later said it was leaking brake
fluid.
