<FIRST>r a PM-LesbianSlaying     08-28 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lesbian Slaying,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lesbian Alleges Spouse Abuse in Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with murdering her
lesbian lover is using the ``battered spouse syndrome'' as her
defense, authorities said.
   Defense lawyers for Annette Green, 30, planned to argue that she
killed her 32-year-old live-in lover, Ivonne Julio, because Ms.
Julio beat and humiliated her repeatedly during their 11-year
relationship.
   The trial was scheduled to begin today in Palm Beach County
Circuit Court.
   Ms. Green's defense is considered novel because the battered
spouse syndrome is usually ascribed to women who suffer repeated
beatings by male partners.
   ``This is a new issue,'' said New York University law Professor
Holly Maguigan, an expert on domestic violence. ``But it is not
surprising. ... The dynamics in a same-sex relationship are often
similar to those in a heterosexual relationship.''
   Ms. Green shot Ms. Julio with a bullet to the brain on Oct. 30,
1988, following a Halloween party and a fight in a trailer park in
unincorporated Palm Beach County, according to police.
   ``She would have killed me because she is very violent,'' Ms.
Green told police after the killing.
   Ms. Green told police that Ms. Julio had beaten her more than 100
times since 1977, when they became lovers. Ms. Julio, two years
older and 70 pounds heavier, used to strike Ms. Green without
warning, Ms. Green said.
   Police said Ms. Green admitted that she was not in immediate
danger when she shot Ms. Julio, who was kneeling in a closet.
   Assistant State Attorney Bob Johnson has asked the court to
exclude testimony on the battered spouse syndrome as it applies to
lesbians because of a lack of adequate research.
   Circuit Judge Tony Waddell has not ruled on the issue.
   Johnson said he will seek the death penalty if Ms. Green is
convicted.
   A doctor hired by the defense found evidence Ms. Green had
suffered ``multiple head injuries.'' Acquaintances said the couple
argued frequently and their arguments often dissolved into violence.
   Defense attorney William Lasley said Ms. Green did not leave Ms.
Julio out of concern for Ms. Julio's twin 14-year-old daughters.
   Lasley said Ms. Green ``adopted'' the teen-agers and acted as
their mother, protecting them from Ms. Julio.
</TEXT>
