<DOCNO> AP890828-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MansionSlayings     08-28 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mansion Slayings,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Believes Organized Crime Behind Killing of Video Exec and
Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives warned Jose Enrique
Menendez that criminals prey on the rich. But he kept the gates
unlocked at his $4 million Beverly Hills house, with its tennis
court and Mercedes-Benz outside.
   And that could have made it easy for mobsters to get him, his
sister said outside a memorial for the slain Hollywood executive.
   ``We think he made the mistake of buying a business that had been
used before by the Mafia, and we think he was trying to run it
straight,'' Marta Menendez-Cano of West Palm Beach, Fla., said
Friday.
   Her brother, Jose E. Menendez, was found shot to death the night
of Aug. 20 along with his 44-year-old wife, Kitty, in their
Spanish-style mansion.
   About all police would say was that nothing had been ruled out.
   The Cuban-born Menendez, 45, once headed RCA-Ariola Records as
well as the U.S. rental car operations for the Hertz Corp.
   He was chief executive officer and chairman of the board of Live
Entertainment Inc., an affiliate of Carolco Pictures Inc. in the
video and music distribution business, and had been praised for
improving the company's performance.
   Two of the three companies operated by Live Entertainment had
been linked to organized crime before Live Entertainment bought
them. Live Entertainment acting President Roger R. Smith has
vehemently rejected suggestions that the deaths may have a mob link.
   Ms. Menendez-Cano and former Lt. Gov. Mike Curb, a friend for
nearly a decade, described Menendez as absolutely honest, although
an extremely aggressive businessman.
   ``Sometimes he had to tell people things they didn't want to
hear,'' Curb said. ``But he was a wonderful guy, an absolutely
outstanding person. I just can't believe something like this could
happen.''
   Curb and Ms. Menendez-Cano spoke outside the memorial service at
the Directors Guild of America in Hollywood, where 400 people
listened to eulogies by the Menendezes sons, Eric, 18, and Lyle, 22.
   Ms. Menendez-Cano said her brother had tried to keep the video
business clean.
   ``The first thing he did was to get rid of the porno business,''
she said. ``Because of his success, he probably was stepping on many
shoes, which some people didn't like.''
   International Video Entertainment, which Live Entertainment
purchased in 1986, had been owned by Noel C. Bloom. Bloom was
identified in a California attorney general's report on organized
crime that year as a major distributor of X-rated movies and a
former associate of the late Michael Zaffarano of the Bonanno
organized-crime family.
   Peter Hoffman, Carolco's president and chief executive, said
International Video Entertainment itself was never involved in
pornography.
   The other company with a crime-linked past was BeckZack Corp.,
which owns the 81-store Strawberries audio and home-video retailing
chain in the Northeast. Live Entertainment completed its acquisition
of BeckZack this June.
   BeckZack's principal shareholder, Morris Levy, was convicted in
May 1988 of conspiring to extort payments from a record wholesaler.
He remains free pending an appeal of his conviction.
   An FBI affidavit filed in federal court in New York in connection
with an investigation of Levy quoted an unidentified informant as
saying that a faction of the Genovese crime family owned an interest
in the Strawberries chain. The documents called Levy ``a lucrative
source of cash and property'' for Genovese leaders.
   Andrew Nichols, the Boston lawyer who represented Levy in the
sale of Strawberries to Live Entertainment for about $40.5 million,
said he is certain the company had no crime connections at the time
of the sale.
   And Live Entertainment officials said they even checked with
federal organized crime investigators, who said they were unaware of
any such links to Strawberries.
   Ms. Menendez-Cano said her brother had big plans to expand. ``He
said he would be controlling the East Coast video business, through
his careful planning, in the next couple of years.''
   She said her brother refused to listen when she warned him about
leaving the house unlocked.
   ``We told him that there were burglars, criminals in the
neighborhood,'' she said.
   Menendez and his wife had been looking to the future, building an
8,000-square-foot dream house above Los Angeles.
   Then their sons found their bullet-riddled bodies.
   Menendez would want his business associates and friends to keep
up the fight, his younger son told the mourners.
   Eric Menendez recalled how his father kept a portrait of the
slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. in the house, and
adopted as his motto King's declaration of hope _ ``I have a dream.''
</TEXT>
