<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0554EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Election     08-28 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Election,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberal Democrat-Backed Candidate Wins Closely Watched Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the first mayoral election since the
scandal-tainted Liberal Democratic Party lost its dominance in the
upper house of Parliament, a candidate backed by the conservative
party has defeated a divided opposition.
   The vote Sunday in Kyoto, 90 miles west of Tokyo, was considered
an indication of how the conservative governing party will fare in
upcoming national balloting.
   Tomoyuki Tanabe, 64, defeated Communist Party candidate Manpei
Kimura by 321 votes, the Kyoto Election Committee said.
   In July, the Liberal Democrats lost a majority in the upper house
of Parliament for the first time in 34 years. Their poor election
showing was attributed to an unpopular sales tax, and
influence-peddling and sex scandals involving party members.
   Elections for the more powerful lower house, which appoints the
prime minister, are due by next summer and political analysts said
the governing party may have a fight on its hands.
   All nine candidates in Sunday's election called for abolition of
the 3 percent sales tax imposed April 1.
   Kyoto is considered symbolically important as Japan's ancient
capital and as a district that in the late 1970s swung from nearly
three decades of mostly Communist local government to a Liberal
Democratic-led coalition.
   Tanabe, an independent candidate endorsed by the Liberal
Democrats, won the race with 148,836 votes. Kimura, 65, received
148,515 votes, the Election Committee said.
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu said he was relieved by Sunday's
victory.
   It was the first mayoral election since the Kaifu administration
was inaugurated on Aug. 9.
   Kaifu replaced Sousuke Uno, who held office for just 69 days
before stepping down amid accusations he had paid mistresses.
</TEXT>
