<HEAD>Thunderstorms in the Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dumped heavy rain and hail today on Kansas and
Missouri, and fog covered parts of the Ohio Valley.
   Kansas City, Mo., was hit by severe storms just after midnight,
drenching the city with over an inch of rain in 20 minutes. Storms
whipped winds up to 70 mph at St. Joseph.
   Baseball-sized hail fell near Belleville, Kan., and 35 mph winds
knocked over power lines at Hesston.
   Floods briefly closed parts of Interstate 70 in Kansas City and
near Independence, Mo., Sunday night.
   A tavern in Princeton, Mo., was flattened when a 60-foot brick
wall blew over on it.
   From 1 to 2 inches of rain fell in less than an hour early today
across much of eastern Kansas and northwest Missouri, with 2.2
inches falling in 45 minutes at Cottonwood Falls, Kan.
   Two to 4 inches of rain fell in portions of North Dakota on
Sunday afternoon and evening.
   Showers were scattered across portions of the East Coast states
this morning. Dense fog developed over portions of the southern
Appalachians and the Ohio Valley.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 1.88 inches at Topeka, Kan., and 1.29 inches at Columbia,
Mo.
   Today's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms extending from
the Rockies across most of the Great Plains and the upper half of
the Mississippi Valley to Michigan, with the most numerous storms
over northern Missouri, Iowa, Wisconsin and northern Illinois.
Showers also were expected over the central Gulf Coast and south
Atlantic states and the Tennessee Valley, with a few showers in
Maine.
   Highs were expected in the upper 60s and 70s along the Pacific
Coast across the Northern Rockies, in the Dakotas and upper
Mississippi Valley to northern Michigan, and across much of New
England; near 100 over the lower Mississippi Valley, the southern
Plains and interior valleys of California, from 100 to 105 in the
desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 60 showery; Atlanta 76 foggy; Boston 62
partly cloudy; Buffalo 63 fair; Charleston, S.C. 77 partly cloudy;
Chattanooga 73 foggy; Cincinnati 74 foggy; Cleveland 63 fair;
Detroit 67 foggy; Hatteras 74 fair; Key West 84 partly cloudy;
Knoxville 73 foggy; Macon 74 foggy; Miami 81 showery; New York 68
cloudy; Philadelphia 67 cloudy; Pittsburgh 66 fair; Portland, Maine
57 cloudy; Richmond 67 foggy; Tampa 76 foggy; Washington, D.C. 74
foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 59 partly cloudy; Chicago 71 partly cloudy;
Denver 64 fair; Des Moines 71 cloudy; Fort Worth 81 fair;
Indianapolis 74 foggy; Kansas City 67 showery; Little Rock 78 fair;
Louisville 75 foggy; Memphis 80 fair; Nashville 74 foggy; New
Orleans 77 foggy; North Platte 66 foggy; Oklahoma City 76 fair;
Omaha 70 cloudy; Rapid City 57 fair; St. Louis 75 cloudy;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 69 cloudy; Sault Ste. Marie 56 foggy; San
Antonio 81 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 62 partly cloudy; Anchorage 54 rain; Boise 57
fair; Casper 54 fair; Fairbanks 62 cloudy; Great Falls 49 partly
cloudy; Honolulu 78 fair; Las Vegas 79 fair; Los Angeles 62 foggy;
Medford 64 fair; Pendleton 62 fair; Phoenix 88 fair; Portland, Ore.
59 fair; Reno 65 fair; Salt Lake City 64 fair; San Diego 66 cloudy;
San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 57 fair; Spokane 55 fair.
   _International: Mexico City 59 cloudy; Acapulco 75 cloudy; San
Juan 77 fair.
