<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     08-28 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Force Open Shops as Sinhalese Strike Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops forced open shops in the capital
and its suburbs today, the first day of a weeklong strike to protest
alleged killings of Sinhalese militants and to demand the withdrawal
of Indian soldiers.
   Heavily armed soldiers in combat gear drove around Colombo
warning shop owners to open and troops broke the locks of shops
whose owners refused. Most subsequently opened their establishments
but some said they did because they feared the military.
   Few buses rolled through the capital and soldiers were posted at
nearly every corner, witnesses said.
   Troops also prevented cameramen from taking pictures of the
military actions and at least two photographers had their film rolls
exposed by the military.
   No clashes or other violence were immediately reported. But
military officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said 235 suspected Sinhalese radicals had been rounded up since
Sunday in central and southern Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese heartland.
   Inspector General of Police Ernest Perera also ordered all police
on alert after intelligence reports were received that said
Sinhalese extremists planned to attack police stations during the
strike, military officials said.
   The strike was called by National Workers Action Front, the trade
union wing of the People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese
group waging a violent 2-year-old campaign against the
Sinhalese-dominated government.
   Sinhalese radicals oppose the government's peace plan granting
limited autonomy to Tamils in the north and east. Indian troops were
invited to the island in July 1987 to help enforce the initiative
but the government now wants them out. India says a quick withdrawal
could lead to further violence.
   Posters put up in Colombo by the militants demanded that
residents stay indoors and not open for business. Counter-posters,
believed to have been put up by pro-government groups, said anyone
who heeded the strike call would be treated as a traitor.
   At least 5,000 people have been killed in the campaign by
Sinhalese ultranationalists. Human rights organizations and
opposition politicans say many of the victims have been suspected
radicals shot after capture by security forces. In past weeks,
military officials have reported scores of unidentified bodies
turning up in various parts of the island every day.
   Another 11,000 people have died in the Tamil insurrection that
began in 1983 in northeastern Sri Lanka.
   Sinhalese, who are mainly Buddhist and make up 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, dominate the government and military.
Tamils, who are mainly Hindu and comprise about 18 percent of the
island's population, say they are discriminated against by the
ethnic majority in jobs, education and use of the Sinhala language.
   India, the dominant military power in the region, moved in troops
because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel
cause. But the soldiers soon began fighting the rebels it once
supported after a major Tamil militia rejected the peace plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
