<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans     08-28 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Issue Plagues Lutherans But Compromise Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lutherans worked on a compromise approach
to abortion, an issue that in the past divided the three
denominations that merged last year to form the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America.
   A motion was submitted Sunday at the church's eight-day
legislative assembly, which ends Wednesday, asking individuals ``to
act on their Christian convictions'' while the church makes a
long-range study.
   The motion, by Louise Shoemaker of Philadelphia, was to supplant
a resolutions committee proposal calling simply for a church study,
and for people to use prior church guidance.
   The Lutheran Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and
the Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches merged into the
5.3-million member church on Jan. 1, 1988. The three denominations
had taken varying positions on abortion.
   The substitute motion, which reportedly satisfied a women's
caucus that had sought church action to oppose restrictions on
abortion, said church advocacy should involve appealing for ``free
access to services for individuals'' and ``work for justice,
especially with and for the poor.''
   Meanwhile, anti-abortion pickets showed up outside the O'Hare
Exposition Center where the new church's first policy-making
assembly is being held with signs reading:
   ``ELCA: It's Your Baby Now,'' ``Abortion Stops A Beating Heart''
and ``Lutheran General, Stop Killing.''
   The pickets said they were mostly from a group that for two years
has been picketing Lutheran General Hospital in nearby Park Ridge,
Ill., which performs abortions.
   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, the church's president, said in a
letter that the hospital does not provide abortion on demand. He
also was quoted as saying the hospital aborts only fetuses so
seriously abnormal they would die before or at birth.
   Meanwhile, the assembly delayed action on whether to set a
deadline for its pension board to sell off stock in companies doing
business in South Africa.
   The board has $1.6 billion in assets, $84.9 million invested in
companies operating in South Africa. It says it is gradually
reducing the holdings but must do so gradually to be financially
prudent.
   One group, Pension Members for Justice, is pressing for a
deadline of Sept. 1, 1991, to get rid of the holdings.
   Several denominations _ including the United Church of Christ,
the Episcopal Church, the Church of the Brethren and the Quakers _
have decided to sell all stock in companies operating in South
Africa.
   The disinvestment campaign's aim is to push South Africa to end
its system of racial separation and domination of 28 million blacks
by 5 million whites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
