<FIRST>u i PM-Pakistan-Plane     08-28 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Plane,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Hampers Search for Missing Plane With 54 Aboard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor weather in the rugged Korakoram
Mountains stalled search efforts today for a Pakistani airliner that
disappeared three days ago with 54 people aboard.
   ``Today the weather is very bad. We haven't been able to operate
any flights in the area,'' said A.M. Sarooqi, a spokesman for
Pakistan International Airlines.
   Two British trekkers who reported sighting a low-flying aircraft
Friday near 26,606-foot Nanga Parbat, or Naked Mountain, were to
lead a five-man ground search this morning but low clouds and heavy
rains hampered the expedition.
   Sarooqi said the group was on standby in the northern mountain
village of Gilgit waiting for the weather to clear. Helicopters plan
to drop them on a glacier 16,000 feet up the mountain.
   Military and civilian aircraft have been flying over the area's
peaks and valleys since the twin-engine Fokker 27 Friendship
disappeared on a flight from Gilgit to Islamabad, 175 miles to the
south.
   The 27-year-old propeller plane was carrying 49 passengers,
including two American nationals and five crew members.
   The pilot made a routine radio contact seven minutes into the
45-minute flight to the Pakistani capital. That was the last
contact, Sarooqi said.
   Sarooqi said no signals have been picked up from the plane. It
was equipped with an emergency locater transmitter that had to be
activitated manually, he said.
   Four aircraft _ a Fokker 27, a DC-3 and two military C-130s _
have crashed in the area since 1963.
</TEXT>
