<HEAD>Two Palestinians Die in Troop Clashes; Collaborator Reported Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians died today of gunshot wounds
suffered in clashes with Israeli forces and West Bank Arabs began a
general strike to protest the deportations of five activists a day
earlier.
   The deaths raised to 12 the number of Palestinians killed in
clashes the past week, in contrast to 10 people who died in
confrontations in the previous three weeks.
   Also today, 60-year-old Rajeb Al Kassas died of injuries suffered
three days earlier when he was beaten by masked youths who accused
him of collaborating with Israeli authorities, Arab reports said.
The army said it was checking the report.
   The army's chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, has blamed the
rising violence on a decision by Yasser Arafat's mainstream PLO
faction Fatah early this month urging armed struggle against Israel.
   The Israeli daily Haaretz said, however, that the upturn in
violence also resulted from a new army policy of raiding remote
villages in the West Bank to arrest uprising activists.
   A total of 98 Palestinians have been reported slain by fellow
Arabs as alleged collaborators during the revolt.
   One of the deaths today came after masked youths blocked a main
road the night before in Beit Safafa, a village within Jerusalem,
and pelted police with stones, said police spokesman Uzi Sandori.
   Police first fired tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse the
protesters but then opened fire with live ammunition, wounding a
21-year-old demonstrator who later died, Sandori added.
   Officials at Mukassed Hospital identified the youth as Bassel
Khaled Suleiman and said he died of two gunshot wounds in the chest.
   The second fatality was Ali Mahmoud Shaban, 20, of the Jebaliya
refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip, who died of wounds suffered
Friday, the army said.
   The army said Shaban was masked with an Arab scarf when he was
shot while interfering with army operations. The Jerusalem Post
daily said the youth was going from door to door collecting
Israel-issued identity cards.
   The latest fatalities increased the number of Palestinians killed
by Israelis during the 20-month-old uprising to 552. Thirty-eight
Israelis also have been slain.
   The general strike called by masked activists in Nablus and the
towns of Ramallah and El-Bireh was to protest Sunday's deportations
of five Palestinians accused of being ringleaders of the uprising.
   Since the rebellion began on Dec. 8, 1987, a total of 60
Palestinians have been expelled, most of them to Lebanon.
   In Jerusalem, Jewish settlement leader Rabbi Moshe Levinger
pleaded innocent today to charges of manslaughter for allegedly
shooting and killing a Palestinian shopkeeper in the West Bank city
of Hebron last September 30.
   Levinger, at the opening of his trial, admitted firing several
shots in the air, claiming it was in self-defense against a stoning
attack on his car.
