<HEAD>British Daily Hits at Cardinal over Auschwitz Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mass circulation British newspaper today accused
Poland's Roman Catholic Church leader of anti-Semitism in the
controversy about a convent at Auschwitz death camp.
   The Daily Mirror said Cardinal Jozef Glemp's stand must have had
the backing of Pope John Paul II.
   ``The cardinal has tapped into the deep vein of anti-Semitism
which has existed in his country for a thousand years. He would not
have done so without the knowledge of the pope, himself a Pole,''
today's editorial said.
   The tabloid sells 3 million copies a day and supports the
socialist opposition Labor Party.
   On Saturday, Glemp urged Jews worldwide to stop being anti-Polish
in objecting to the existence of a Catholic convent at Auschwitz,
the German concentration camp established in Poland mainly to
exterminate Jews.
   ``If there would be no `anti-Polonism,' there will be no
anti-Semitism in our country,'' Glemp said.
   The Daily Mirror commented: ``The butchers were German Nazis and
their renegade allies, but when Cardinal Glemp spoke warmly of the
improving relations with Poland's old enemies, Germany and Russia,
he used dangerously inflammatory language against the Jews.
   ``He tried to justify his own shameless bad faith in tearing up a
solemn agreement that a Carmelite convent would be removed from
Auschwitz, a place which the Holocaust made holy to Jews.
   ``The Polish Catholic Church had given its word that the nuns
would be moved by last February. Cardinal Glemp broke it without a
qualm. And now that the Jews insist that he keeps the promise, he
accuses them of violating Poland's sovereignty.
   ``In the name of God, what does he hope to gain by fanning the
embers of hate?'' the editorial asked.
