<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     08-28 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Re-occupy Island After Riot By Vietnamese Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today re-occupied an outlying island
after a riot by Vietnamese boat people during which 23 policemen
were injured, police reported.
   About 250 officers landed without incident by helicopter and by
boat on Tai A Chau island, where about 5,000 Vietnamese boat people
are housed, a police statement said. Police searched the island for
any hidden weapons.
   About 50 policemen withdrew from the island to nearby police
launches Sunday night after some 1,000 Vietnamese began hurling
stones following a dispute over the distribution of rice. None of
the policemen was seriously injured.
   Police said some of the Vietnamese were armed with metal bars and
other sharpened objects.
   Forty rounds of tear gas were fired by police during the
violence, police said. It was the first time tear gas had been used
to stop unrest among Vietnamese who fled here seeking a better life.
   The Vietnamese boat people have been put on the island until they
can be inoculated and processed into detention centers to await
screening.
   Under a policy adopted in June 1988, Vietnamese boat people will
be granted refugee status and resettled overseas only if they can
prove they fled political persecution in Vietnam. Otherwise, they
would be considered illegal immigrants and face repatriation.
   About 55,000 Vietnamese are staying in Hong Kong. Two-thirds of
them are kept in prison-like centers, waiting to be screened.
   Earlier this month, Vietnamese battled each other with iron bars,
stones and sharpened objects at the Whitehead Detention Center.
Seventeen people were injured.
</TEXT>
