<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0465 08-28 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Questioned About Links to Colombian Drug Lords</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with today's developments. Pick
up 12th pvs, `He said...' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Israeli officer was questioned by
police today about allegations he trained private militias for
Colombian drug lords, and claimed he did no more than other former
Israeli officers working in the region.
   Retired Lt. Col. Yair Klein told reporters at police headquarters
in the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva he believed he was innocent of
any wrongdoing.
   ``If I did break the law, a lot of other people did,'' he said.
   Israeli newspapers have said Klein was the officer seen in an NBC
film showing the training of death squads for the Medellin drug
cartel in Colombia. He has denied he trained squads for Colombian
drug dealers.
   On Sunday, Klein said he would name high-ranking officers,
including one now sitting in Israel's Parliament, who were involved
in training operations in Latin America. But today he continued to
refuse to make any names public.
   Police launched an inquiry Sunday into possible involvement of
Israelis with Colombian assassination squads.
   Yehoshua Caspi, head of the investigations unit, said police
would examine ``all aspects of Israelis suspected of selling
military services and know-how without Defense Ministry permission
to unofficial groups in Colombia.'' He said the Defense Ministry
requested the probe.
   The possible involvement of Klein and other Israelis with the
Medellin drug cartel drew a renewed defense today from Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   ``I know our officers. I cannot believe that they have been
involved in such crimes,'' Shamir said.
   He said the government was not responsible for its citizens'
actions overseas but that it would prosecute those who broke laws.
``We have to do what we can. ... I am concerned with everything that
is doing harm to our image,'' he said.
   Reports from Colombia said four Israelis were involved in
training assassins for drug smugglers in Colombia along with U.S.,
British and South African mercenaries.
   Klein returned to Israel from Miami on Friday after Israeli
newspapers and television identified him in the NBC film on drug
cartel militias.
   He said that last year he helped train banana growers and
ranchers in Colombia's rural countryside to fight guerrillas.
   He said he was paid $40,000 for two monthlong weapons training
courses he conducted with three other retired Israeli officers and
said all of his dealings in Colombia ``were according to the law.''
   He said his security company, Spearhead, ended its training
program last year and his last visit to Colombia was four months ago.
   His company was denied a Defense Ministry permit to export
weapons or arms technology, but he said the permit was unnecessary
because ``you don't need a permit to work with civilian
organizations.''
   The Yediot Ahronot daily said Klein was paid $800,000 to train
hit squads for the Medellin drug cartel. The newspaper alleged that
Klein was recruited last year by cartel leaders to train ranchers
and paramilitary troops.
   Yediot said Klein was introduced to the drug barons by an Israeli
businessman, identified only as ``Shoshani.''
   Klein confirmed that a man named Shoshani helped him make
contacts and received 10 percent of his fees.
   Yediot said Colombia's secret service sent a report to Israel
four months ago on Israeli mercenaries in Colombia, but the claims
were ignored.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Israel received no official
report from Colombia, but began investigating allegations in the
Colombian press passed along by the Israeli Embassy in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
