<FIRST>r a PM-Congressman-Prostitute 1stLd-Writethru a0496 08-28 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressman-Prostitute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank: No Objection to Ethics Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after the 12th, ``I don't think,'' to update
with Gobie helping police in arrest. Pick up 13th graf pvs, `After publicly
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank says he would not stand in
the way of a congressional investigation into his relationship with
a male prostitute.
   ``If people think an inquest is appropriate, I have no objection
to that at all,'' Frank said Sunday after attending a parade in Fall
River.
   Democrats and Republicans may request a formal investigation when
Congress reconvenes early next month. The House code of conduct
calls for members to act ``at all times in a manner which shall
reflect creditably on the House.''
   Frank says he was ``victimized'' in his relationship with a male
prostitute who may have run a sex ring out of his apartment, and
predicted voters will not hold the incident against him.
   Despite Republican calls for his resignation, polls published
over the weekend showed Frank's constituents still strongly support
him.
   One poll found Frank's constituents by a 2-1 margin said he
deserved re-election, and more than 65 percent in another poll did
not think Frank should resign.
   Frank received spirited support Sunday as he marched in the Fall
River parade, three days after admitting to the relationship with a
male prostitute.
   The parade was part of an event named ``Fall River Celebrates
America'' that drew some 100,000 people over the weekend.
   While there were a few muffled boos, most of the crowd cheered
Frank as the Democratic congressman moved through the parade route.
   Frank, 49, acknowledged on Friday he had once paid for sex with a
male prostitute, then hired the man, Steve Gobie, to do household
chores and run errands.
   Frank said he fired Gobie when he became suspicious that the man
was selling sex from Frank's Capitol Hill apartment.
   ``I don't think I'm going to be heavily penalized by the voters
for being suckered by a guy I was trying to help,'' Frank said on
Friday.
   In a related development, Gobie said he helped police in
Alexandria, Va. on Friday arrest a former Senate aide who allegedly
tried to arrange a sexual encounter with a 13-year-old girl.
Alexandria police Cpl. John Avery confirmed Gobie's claim today.
   The Washington Times and the Washington Post reported today that
the man was charged with solicitation to commit indecent liberties
involving a minor.
   Gobie told both newspapers no actual child was ever involved.
``It was something we made up,'' he told The Times.
   The Times identified the man as John E. Ashford, 39, who has done
consulting work for several Democratic governors and Sen. Richard H.
Bryan, D-Nev. He is a former aide to Sen. Thomas Eagleton, D-Mo.
   Ashford declined comment. His attorney, Rawles Jones, said
Ashford would plead innocent.
   After publicly acknowledging his homosexuality in May 1987, Frank
won election to his fifth term in 1988 with 70 percent of the vote
in the state's 4th District, which encompasses some Boston suburbs
and parts of southeastern Massachusetts.
   A poll of 400 registered voters in Frank's district conducted
Friday night for The Boston Globe and WBZ-TV showed 65.3 percent did
not think Frank should resign.
   The Boston Herald and WCVB-TV polled 300 of Frank's constituents,
who by nearly a 2-1 margin said Frank deserved re-election.
   Both polls carry a margin of error of plus-or-minus 5 percent.
</TEXT>
