<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     08-28 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Session Opens to Pursue Elusive Cambodian Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final session of an international peace
conference on Cambodia opened today in the French capital with no
agreement as yet on any of the major issues dividing the
Vietnam-backed Cambodian government from three resistance factions.
   Foreign ministers attending the opening sessions of the monthlong
conference established working committees on reaching cease-fire,
achieving a power-sharing agreement, repatriating refugees and
monitoring the complete withdrawal of 26,000 Vietnamese troops by
Sept. 27.
   But nearly three weeks of committee meetings, which has involved
19 countries and the United Nations, yielded so little progress that
U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker announced Friday he would not
return to Paris for the meeting today through Wednesday.
   The United States accused Vietnam and its government in Phnom
Penh, led by Prime Minister Hun Sen, of inflexibility toward the
conditions for peace set out by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, leader of
the resistance, who enjoys strong U.S. support.
   China's official Xinhua news agency reported over the weekend
that Foreign Minister Qian Qichen would attend the closing
ministerial session only ``if the four committees of the conference
can succeed in producing agreements.''
   China sponsors the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three
resistance movements fighting the Cambodian government. The Khmer
Rouge, whose genocidal rule between 1975 and 1978 cost a million
lives, have been at the center of the deadlock.
   Sihanouk's resistence coalition has insisted that the Khmer Rouge
be given a role in a transitional government that would rule between
the troop pullout and elections, which Hun Sen has said he would
like to hold within three months of the withdrawal.
   But Hun Sen rejects including the Khmer Rouge and says they must
be ``eliminated'' politically and militarily.
   ``The Khmer Rouge remain the principle obstacle. They don't
believe in a political solution,'' said Hun Sen's deputy foreign
minister, Sok An.
   The Khmer Rouge are militarily the strongest of the resistence
factions and are the most feared by the government and Cambodian
population.
   Surprise last-minute concessions were possible, but not likely.
   Thailand, which has thousands of Cambodian refugees in camps
along its border and is the supply route from China to the Khmer
Rouge, has predicted no ``global'' accord will be signed and that
another international meeting will be necessary.
   Indian officials have said the problems existing after nearly two
decades of fighting ``cannot be settled in one month.''
   There remained hope among some delegates that the conference
could result in a partial accord.
   ``It does not appear likely the conference will achieve its
objectives,'' said a Western delegate several days before the
conference reconvened.
   But, the delegate added, the conference is less a failure than
``a stage through which one has to pass.''
</TEXT>
