<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BloodStrike     08-28 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blood Strike,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Union Strikes Blood Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest blood center in the country was down
to less than a day's supply when a planned four-day strike by more
than 400 union workers began today, a spokesman said.
   The New York Blood Center, which handles 2,000 pints per day, or
nearly all of the blood that the area's 250 hospitals use, planned
to resupply from outside the area.
   Hospital and union officials said most hospitals have put off
elective surgery.
   Sixty-five of the affected hospitals are in central and northern
New Jersey and are supplied by New Jersey Blood Services of New
Brunswick, a branch of the New York Blood Center, said spokesman
Michael Scahill.
   ``We're trying to source as much blood as we can from different
parts of the country. Any Red Cross center that has blood has been
contacted,'' Scahill said.
   A picket line was established by the 50 to 75 employees at the
New Brunswick center, according to Scahill. Pickets also marched
outside the New York Blood Center in Manhattan.
   ``Everybody is out and we are accusing management of allowing no
negotiations over the weekend, absolutely none,'' said Edward Kay,
an executive vice president for Local 1199 of the Drug, Hospital and
Health Care Employees Union.
   No negotiations were planned until workers are back at their
jobs, Scahill said.
   Besides calling around the country to locate blood, medically
qualified management employees were taking blood from donors,
according to Scahill. Those without medical training were doing
clerical work.
   The not-for-profit organization usually has a four-to-five-day
supply of blood, but because of the strike and the time of year, it
was down to less than a day's worth, Scahill said.
   ``It's the traditional shortage period, the pre-Labor Day period.
... We're used to shortfalls in the system, but this adds a real
crunch to it,'' he said.
   The union said the strike was called because of a management
attempt to cut pension contributions by 50 percent.
   The labor union announced last week that it would walk out on the
blood center today for four days and offered to set up weekend talks
to avert the job action, according to Kay.
</TEXT>
