<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     08-28 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extremists Threaten Pope If He Visits Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An underground extremist faction today
threatened to kill Pope John Paul II if he comes to Lebanon on a
peace mission.
   The wording of the threat by the Organization for the Defense of
the Oppressed suggested it was made by Shiite Moslem zealots.
   A newspaper in Iran, a sponsor of Moslem Shiite extremism in
Lebanon, said Sunday the pope should stay out of Lebanon, but it did
not make an overt threat.
   It was the second time in four days that the previously unknown
Organization for the Defense of the Oppressed has made a statement.
   Delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut, the statement said:
``To his holiness Pope John Paul II: We address our words to him,
wishing that he writes his will before he comes to Beirut.''
   ``The organization emphasizes that his holiness the Pope will be
one of the victims of the criminal war our beloved homeland Lebanon
is living through,'' the statement said.
   Other Moslem groups have said that a Lebanese peace mission by
the Roman Catholic leader would really be intended to boost the
Christian side in the country's 14-year-old civil war.
   However, a senior Shiite cleric, Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, was quoted Sunday as saying he would welcome the pope and
``give him full security guarantees'' to visit Moslem west Beirut.
   The Vatican said it is studying the possibility of a visit to
Lebanon, but no date has been set.
   In its statement, the extremist group also said ``it will arrange
a reception for the Pope of Rome similar to our reception of the
Israeli invaders and the forces of (former President) Reagan and the
`loving mother' (France) in 1982 and 1983.''
   That last paragraph referred to twin suicide truck bombings on
Oct. 23, 1983 that killed 241 American servicemen and 58 Frenchmen.
The attacks prompted withdrawal of an international peacekeeping
force from Lebanon.
   France, which ruled Lebanon from 1918 to 1943, often is referred
to as the the Christians' ``loving mother,'' mainly because it
helped forge a national covenant that gave the Christians key
government posts.
   The French have now sent a six-ship flotilla to the Eastern
Mediterranean off Lebanon, saying the forces may be needed to
evacuate French nationals from Lebanon.
   Last week, the Organization for the Defense of the Oppressed
issued a statement threatening to attack any French vessel that
approaches the Lebanese coast.
   Today's developments came amid renewed clashes between Christian
army units and Syrian troops allied with Moslem militias. Police
reported no casualties in the sporadic clashes.
   By police count, 792 have been killed and 2,247 wounded in the
5-month-old confrontation, the latest round of the civil war.
   On the diplomatic front, a French envoy was reported in Damascus,
Syria, waiting to begin talks on a French peace plan, while a Soviet
envoy discussed peace proposals for Lebanon with Iraqi officials.
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas said the envoy would be
pressing for a cease-fire with an embargo on arms deliveries to the
warring factions, political reform, and withdrawal of Syrian and
Israeli forces from Lebanon.
   The proposed troop withdrawal is similar to a Soviet proposal
outlined Sunday by Arab diplomats.
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon with an estimated
40,000 troops in the country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate. Israel has maintained a self-declared security zone in
south Lebanon since withdrawing most of its invasion forces in 1985.
   Moslem radio stations today criticized the French proposal. The
Voice of the Nation, the most popular station in Moslem west Beirut,
said: ``Dumas' plan ... lays all the blame for the crisis on Syria,
with whom most of the Moslem majority is aligned.''
</TEXT>
