<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     08-28 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Activists to Go on Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young Hungarians arrested in
anti-government protests last week will go on trial Tuesday on
charges of disrupting public order, a judge said today.
   Prague riot police dispersed thousands of demonstrators Aug. 21,
the 21st anniversary of the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed
attempts to liberalize Communism in Czechoslovakia.
   State news media said 370 people were detained in last week's
protests, including 50 foreigners.
   The two Hungarians, who belong to the FIDESZ independent
Hungarian youth group, have been identified as Gyoergy Kerenyi and
Tamas Deutsch.
   Plainclothes police seized the two activists as they took part in
a protest, and charges of violating public order were pressed by a
Prague prosecutor Saturday.
   Prague District Judge Jan Belohlavek said they will go on trial
in District Court on Tuesday. They face up to six months in jail or
a fine of $2,000.
   Hungary has protested the holding of the two Hungarians and said
it would guarantee their appearance in court if they are set free.
   Relations between Hungary and Czechoslovakia, which are Warsaw
Pact allies, worsened after Hungarian television carried recent
interviews with Alexander Dubcek, who led the 1968 Czechoslovak
reforms, and with dissident Vaclav Havel.
</TEXT>
