<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyTrial     08-28 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsley Tax Evasion Jury Deliberating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors began a third day of deliberations today
in the trial of Leona Helmsley, the ``queen'' of expensive New York
hotels who is charged with evading $1.2 million in taxes.
   The jurors spent 15 hours deliberating over the weekend.
   The jury, which has been sequestered since closing arguments
began Wednesday, deliberated seven hours Sunday and had met more
than eight hours Saturday.
   Two hours into deliberations Sunday, they sent out a note
requesting documents relating to a Helmsley-controlled partnership
that owned three of the Helmsley hotels in Manhattan.
   The partnership, Realesco Equities Corp., is named in two sets of
charges _ aiding in the filing of false corporate tax returns and
mail fraud _ against Mrs. Helmsley and her two co-defendants, former
aides Frank Turco and Joseph Licari.
   Mrs. Helmsley's 80-year-old husband, Harry, also was indicted but
was severed from the trial because he was found to be mentally
incompetent.
   The jury also asked for a 1985 memo which Turco had forwarded to
Licari and on which he had written, ``Please deep six after
reading.''
   The document was a progress report on renovations at the
Helmsleys' Connecticut estate, Dunnellen Hall.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is accused of evading $1.2 million in federal
taxes by charging personal expenses, including renovations at
Dunnellen Hall, to her businesses. She is charged with 41 counts in
a 47-count indictment.
   A second note requested rereading of testimony concerning
Licari's involvement in the alleged phony billing scheme, a list of
exhibit numbers and documents dealing with the payments by another
Helmsley company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
