<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--EmergencyLanding     08-28 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Emergency Landing,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Makes Emergency Landing in School Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane carrying two people made an
emergency landing on the grounds of a middle school this morning,
but no one was injured, officials said.
   The plane landed at about 8 a.m. on a grassy athletic field
adjacent to the Sharpstown Middle School in southwest Houston, said
Houston Independent School District spokesman Larry Yawn. He said
the engine had failed.
   Today was the first day of work for teachers, but students won't
return to school until next week.
   The vintage plane's pilot and passenger, his wife, were not
injured in the landing, Yawn said. He said the couple had taken off
from the Clear Lake section of Houston, about 20 miles southeast of
the school.
   The area where the plane landed is about the size of a football
field and is used for physical education activities and football
practice.
</TEXT>
