<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0478 08-28 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0478,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Planes Flying Over Shiite Base Prompt False Reports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Hezbollah denying Israeli
raid; police confirming Hezbollah toll in earlier raid. Pick up 10th graf
pvs, `Ain Abu-Suar...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli jets roared over a stronghold of
Shiite Moslem forces in east Lebanon today, touching off false radio
reports of a bombing raid.
   The Voice of Lebanon, the most popular Christian radio station in
east Beirut, and Voice of the Nation, the main broadcaster in the
Moslem sector, were among those to report a raid on Lebanon's Bekaa
valley.
   However, Hezbollah issued a statement saying there was no such
raid, and the Israeli army also denied launching an attack.
   ``There hasn't been any air raid today,'' said a police
spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations.
   The spokesman said supersonic jets broke the sound barrier in
reconnaissance runs over the village of Janta and the ancient city
of Baalbek, drawing heavy anti-aircraft fire from Hezbollah's
positions.
   The sonic booms apparently prompted the reports that the Israelis
bombed Janta, 43 miles southeast of Beirut.
   An Israeli army spokeswoman, who could not be identified under
standing military rules, described the report as ``disinformation.''
   An earlier Hezbollah statement today said nine people were killed
and 27 wounded in the Israeli air attack Sunday on a party base in
south Lebanon's village of Ain Abu-Suar.
   The statement said the victims included 15 students wounded when
their school was hit in the attack.
   Police, who had earlier put the toll at three guerrillas killed
and nine wounded, today confirmed Hezbollah's toll.
   Ain Abu-Suar is 40 miles southeast of Beirut near the northern
edge of Israel's self-designated ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Sunday's attack was Israel's ninth on Lebanon this year. It
apparently was in retaliation for an Aug. 9 suicide car bomb attack
by a Hezbollah activist in the security zone.
   Five Israeli soldiers and an militiamen of the Israel-backed
South Lebanon Army were wounded.
   Hezbollah said the bombing was to avenge the kidnapping of a
Shiite Moslem cleric, Sheik Abdul-Karim Obeid, by Israeli commandos
south Lebanon on July 28.
   Israel justified the kidnapping by saying it wanted to trade
Obeid for two soldiers and an airman captured in Lebanon in 1986 and
believed held by Hezbollah.
   It has offered to swap Obeid and other captive Shiites for the
three Israelis and 16 Western hostages, including eight Americans,
most of whom are believed held by groups linked to Hezbollah. The
fundamentalists have rejected the offer.
   Longest held of the hostages in Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was taken nearly 4{
years ago.
   Israel carved out the security zone, which is 6-10 miles deep,
when its withdrew most of its army from Lebanon in mid-1985
following a three-year occupation.
</TEXT>
