<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cuba-DrugTrial     08-28 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Drug Trial,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Asks 20 Years For Disgraced Interior Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban prosecutors at a trial stemming from
their country's drug scandal asked that a former interior minister
be given 20 years in prison for corruption, the island's official
news agency said today.
   Closing arguments in the military trial of Division Gen. Jose
Abrantes Fernandez and six other officials, including the former
vice interior minister and the former head of customs, were made
late Sunday, Prensa Latina said in a dispatch monitored in Mexico
City.
   It did not say when a verdict was expected.
   The trial stems from a drug scandal that has shaken the nation,
belied President Fidel Casto's vision of Communist rectitude, and
sent four officers to the firing squad. One of those killed was a
highly decorated war hero.
   Abrantes was fired as interior minister in June, when 12 military
officials from his ministry and two from the army were charged with
drug smuggling and other crimes. The ones who escaped execution
received sentences of up to 30 years.
   In addition to requesting the 20-year sentence, prosecutors also
told the military tribunal Sunday that Abrantes should be demoted to
private, Prensa Latina said.
   The prosecution said Abrantes fumbled a drug-trafficking
investigation so badly that his mistakes appeared deliberate, but it
said the evidence did not support a charge of treason, Prensa Latina
said.
   It also said he and his co-defendants used their posts to enrich
themselves, according to the agency.
   Abrantes was charged with abusing power, neglecting his duties
and stealing from the government, Prensa Latina said.
   The chief prosecutor said Abrantes was so consumed with ``dollar
fever'' that he traded in Cuban pesos on the black market for his
own profit.
   The prosecution also asked the tribunal to sentence the former
vice interior minister, Division Gen. Pascual Martinez Gil, to 15
years in prison and to demote him to private for abuse of power and
stealing from the government.
   It requested a 13-year sentence for bribery and abuse of power
for Lt. Col. Oscar Carreno Gomez, former head of customs.
   Sentences ranging from 8-12 years were requested for the rest of
the defendants. The charges were similar.
</TEXT>
