<FIRST>r a AM-Voyager-Berry     08-28 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voyager-Berry,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Go, Voyager, Go!' Sings Chuck Berry, Whose Voice is on Voyager</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Voyager-Neptune, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If alien creatures ever discover Voyager
2 as it speeds toward the stars, they will find it carries a
recording of Earth's sounds, including rock 'n' roll legend Chuck
Berry's ``Johnny B. Goode.''
   ``I could never be gratified more than being part of that,''
Berry said Sunday night after he belted out his classic song for a
crowd of 1,500 at a party outside NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Berry changed the words a bit, replacing ``Go, Johnny, go!'' with
``Go, Voyager, go!''
   The party _ sponsored by The Planetary Society and televised in
the United States, Japan and Soviet Union _ was a celebration of
Voyager 2's flight past Neptune, the fourth and final planet it
explored during a 12-year trek through the solar system.
   Voyager 2 and its twin, Voyager 1, each carry a 12-inch copper
record containing greetings in 60 languages and a variety of sounds
from Earth in case some extraterrestrial civilization ever stumbles
upon one of the space probes.
   Berry is the only rock artist on the record.
   Cornell University astronomer Carl Sagan, who devised the Voyager
record and was the emcee at Sunday's party, ended the celebration by
saying, ``I'm going to go get some sleep, or maybe I'll do a little
dancing.''
   Meanwhile, Voyager's photographic imaging team partied at a home
in Pasadena, toasting Voyager's success at Neptune. ``We couldn't
have asked for a more cooperative planet,'' said Voyager project
scientist Edward Stone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
