<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 08-28 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0546,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian President Denies Justice Minister Has Quit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORECTS sprelling of de Greiff in 2nd graf; inserts 2 grafs
after 7th graf, Popadiuk said, with details on Colombian official's schedule
in Washington; adds 6 grafs with other announcements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Colombia has denied
reports that his justice minister has resigned from fear of death
threats from drug lords, a White House spokesman said today.
   The minister, Monica de Greiff, is in Washington meeting with
officials of the State and Justice departments about efforts to
break the drug cartels in the South American nation and extradite
those wanted by American prosecutors, spokesman Roman Popadiuk said.
   ``As I understand it, our contacts through the (U.S.) embassy
with President (Virgilio) Barco indicate that President Barco has
denied that she has resigned,'' said Popadiuk.
   Asked if the 32-year-old minister has discussed with U.S.
officials the possibility of asylum, the White House official said,
``I do not know of any such discussions.'
   ``President Barco has assured us that there is no truth to the
stories as far as we know in terms of a resignation. ... President
Barco's words are good enough for me,'' said Popadiuk.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Sunday he knew of no
request for political asylum from Mrs. de Greiff, but he said it
``would not be surprising'' in light of the drug lords' violence.
   Popadiuk said Mrs. de Greiff was in Washington ``discussing such
issues as the extradition process.'' Asked if she was still acting
in her official capacity, he replied, ``Absolutely, just as
originally planned.''
   Meanwhile, U.S. officials in Washington said there were tentative
plans for Mrs. de Greiff to meet later today with senior State
Department officials, including Undersecretary of State Robert
Kimmitt.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they had
heard unconfirmed reports that the Colombian minister's 3-year-old
son, who accompanied her from Bogota, was the target of a death
threat. They said her place of residence while in Washington aas
being kept secret for security reasons.
   The White House announced Friday that President Bush is sending
$65 million in emergency aid to Colombia for the drug fight. It
includes $5 million to protect judges and other Colombian justice
officials threatened by the drug trafficers, who have warned they
will kill 20 judges for each drug trafficker extradited to the
United States.
   Bush was asked as he teed off for golf this morning if he has
approved any covert action to fight the Colombian drug lords. He
replied: ``If I discussed covert action it wouldn't be covert. I
don't discuss that kind of thing at all.''
   He cautioned reporters that his words should not be interpreted
as a ``yes or a no or a confirm or a deny.''
   Asked if he was concerned that drug-fighting efforts might be
undermined by resignations of Colombian officials, he said, ``I'm
not concerned about anything. It's my vacation. That's what you're
supposed to do on vacation is relax.''
   On Tuesday, Bush is to huddle with Thornburgh, drug policy
director William J. Bennett and other top administration officials
at the president's compound here to discuss the drug strategy he
will unveil Sept. 5.
   Meanwhile, the president had another frustrating fishing trip
this morning, failing to catch a fish for the 13th day of his 20-day
vacation.
   Bush engaged in what he called a sports ``quintathalon'' on
Sunday: jogging, tennis, horsheshoes, softball and fishing.
   A double in softball allowed him to boast of his hitting prowess,
but he was still looking for his first fish.
   He and wife Barbara also squeezed in a pair of church services _
one abbreviated _ with visiting evangelist Billy Graham and his wife
Ruth.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and his family arrive
Wednesday for an overnight visit, and on Friday Bush will make a
brief trip back to the White House to meet Japan's new prime
minister, Toshiki Kaifu.
   In other matters, the vacation White House announced today that:
   _Bush formally asked Congress for a 3.6 percent pay raise for
federal civilian workers effective in January 1990, as previously
agreed to in budget negotiations.
   The president noted in a letter to leaders of Congress that pay
advisers had recommended a 28.6 percent raise for the civil
servants, but said that was out of the question. The administration
originally suggested a 2 percent raise.
   _Bush warned South Korea that he may bar fish imports if it does
not reach an agreement with the United States on driftnet fishing in
the next 30 days.
   _The National Teacher of the Year, Mary V. Bicouvaris of Bethel
High School in Hampton, Va., was named to the Commission on
President Scholars, succeeding a former top teacher, Tennessee's
Terry Weeks.
   _Bush will appoint Craig I. Fields to the new National Commission
on Superconductivity. Fields, 43, is director of the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency in Arlington, Va.
</TEXT>
