<FIRST>u i PM-India-Killings     08-28 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Killings,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Gunmen Raid Train, Kill at Least 22 Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Sikh gunmen raided a passenger
train in Punjab state and massacred at least 22 Hindu passengers, a
senior police official said today.
   At least 30 others were wounded in the attack on the
Suratgarh-to-Bhatinda train late Sunday, said K.P.S. Gill, director
general of police in the northern state.
   But the English-language Tribune newspaper in the state capital,
Chandigarh, said 70 people had been killed and 150 wounded.
   Gill said 12 Sikh militants, armed with automatic rifles, stopped
the train, stormed three of its five cars, and separated the Hindu
passengers from the Sikhs before opening fire on the Hindus.
   The attack occurred at Qabarwala in Fridkot district. The area is
85 miles south of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar and about 25 miles
from the Pakistan border.
   Gill said the train, carrying 450 people, had four armed security
guards to protect passengers from such an attack. He said the
attackers fled before the guards could intervene.
   Sikh radicals have been fighting for an independent nation in
Punjab since 1982. They say they suffer discrimination at the hands
of India's Hindu majority.
   Hindus make up 82 percent of India's 880 million people, and
Sikhs account for 2 percent. However, they are in a slight majority
in Punjab.
   At least 1,224 deaths this year have been blamed on Sikh radicals
in Punjab.
   In a similar attack in August 1988, Sikh radicals raided a train
and killed 11 Hindus.
</TEXT>
