<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Farmers 1stLd-Writethru a0559 08-28 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Farmers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0559,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Farmers Protest Government Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to DELETE reference to tractors.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 farmers from the
breadbasket province of Vojvodina on Monday rallied in front of the
federal parliament to demand higher selling prices for their produce.
   The farmers are angry about the government's attempts to control
runaway inflation by forcing food prices down.
   At Monday's rally in a driving rain, farmers demanded that
state-controlled food prices cover the cost of production.
   ``It is cows which should be milked, not peasants,'' said one
sign. ``After paying taxes, the peasant has only his underpants,''
read another.
   Farmers in Yugoslavia's largest republic of Serbia, of which
Vojvodina is a part, objected to a recent government decision to
flood the market with cheap flour, wheat, sugar and other foods from
federal stockpiles to try to halt constant price rises on those
items.
   Agriculture Minister Stevo Mirjanic said Aug. 9 that past
governments were to blame for the poor state of Yugoslav
agriculture, and he promised higher guaranteed prices for farm
products. The Tanjug news agency said the government planned to
review agricultural problems Oct. 5.
   The protest had been intended to draw farmers from all over
Yugoslavia, but the rally fell victim to the divisive disputes among
the country's six constituent republics. Farmers from Croatia and
Slovenia pulled out because they saw the protest as a Serbian move
to rattle the federal government of Ante Markovic, a Croat under
fierce attack from Serbian politicians.
</TEXT>
