<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Word is out that Elizabeth Taylor has written her
memoirs, but publication details are still under wraps.
   ``Miss Taylor has in fact completed a manuscript which chronicles
her life, but there are no immediate plans for its release,''
according to a statement from Miss Taylor's publicist, Chen Sam &amp;
Associates.
   The publicist owned up to the manuscript after C. David Heymann,
author of a best-selling biography of Jacqueline Onassis, said he
soon would begin a biography of Miss Taylor. ``She might cooperate.
She hasn't given me a no yet,'' Heymann said.
   But Miss Taylor's publicist said the actress had never spoken
with Heymann ``nor does she have any plans to collaborate with him.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The singing Jacksons, minus superstar brother
Michael, returned to their old homestead, 2300 Jackson St., the
namesake of their new album.
   It was the first time in 18 years brothers Jackie, Tito, Jermaine
and Randy had appeared as a group in Gary, where they began singing
25 years ago.
   ``This is where it started,'' Jackie Jackson told a crowd outside
the homestead after an appearance Saturday at a local shopping
center.
   The Jacksons knew early on what they wanted out of life, said
Gladys Bufkin Johnson, the retired principal of a school they once
attended.
   ``The teachers used to talk about Michael's refusal to learn his
numbers _ addition and subtraction _ because he said his manager was
going to take care of that,'' she said. ``He was even thinking of
success them.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donny Osmond autographed one of his early
albums for a woman who said she waited 15 years for the moment, but
the singer said he's trying to shed the image of the teen-ager who
sang ``Puppy Love.''
   Osmond, 31, who has hit the charts again, said he hopes people
``wake up to the realization that 15 years have gone by'' since he
was a teen idol.
   But diehard fans like Rally Castellanos, 23, at Sunday's benefit
concert are still a thrill, Osmond said.
   ``They bring back a lot of memories that are really great to
me,'' he said. ``All the traveling I did, when you talk to people
like Rally, it all starts to come back.''
   Ms. Castellanos described the moment as ``an 8-year-old girl's
dream coming true'' after receiving a hug from Osmond.
   ``I know he's trying to change his image, and I can appreciate
that,'' she said, ``but my heart will always belong to the old
Donny.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stacy Keach, appearing here in ``The King and I,''
is driving against the odds in a loaner program that puts stars in a
borrowed Cadillac.
   Two of the cars landed in the repair shop and another was stolen.
   ``Thank goodness no one has been hurt,'' said Cadillac dealer
Alice DeSanders, who persists in loaning cars to visiting stars of
the Dallas Summer Musicals. ``But maybe it's a good thing the 1990
Cadillacs have air bags as standard equipment.''
   The bad luck started when Debbie Reynolds, who starred in ``The
Unsinkable Molly Brown,'' was driving her loaner and was hit by a
truck. She was given another vehicle, which was stolen from the
music hall's parking lot.
   During the run of ``Godspell,'' star Adrian Zmed was driving one
of Ms. DeSanders' Cadillacs when it was sideswiped by a boat being
towed on a freeway.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BUTTE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The von Trapp family portrayed in the movie
``The Sound of Music'' has the hills of Montana alive with the sound
of angry sportsmen.
   The von Trapps recently bought the 50,000-acre Snowcrest Ranch,
which contains several private roads that connect public roads to
the Beaverhead National Forest, popular with hunters and fishermen.
   Johannes von Trapp, president of the family company, agreed to
leave several roads open. But he has hunters and fishermen seething
over the one he closed.
   ``They closed a road that's been open for 60 years,'' said Bill
Endy of Whitehall, a sportsman who said he has hired a lawyer.
   Von Trapp said in a statement that he wanted ``to be a good
neighbor to the people who hunt in the Beaverhead National Forest.''
   ``I also want to be a good land steward,'' von Trapp said. ``I
hope those who cross the Snowcrest Ranch on these roads will respect
that.''
