<FIRST>r a PM-LouisianaPrisons 1stLd-Writethru a0407 08-28 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Prisons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Warden Resigns Under Fire; Judge Criticizes Prisons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT that warden resigned, sted was
fired, and to DELETE erronious reference to judge ordering corruption investigation;
SUBS 9th graf, `As a ..., to CORRECT number of prisoners to 16,000 sted
18,000; SUBS 10th graf, `Gov. Buddy ..., to clarify that judge criticized
Legislature for not doing enough; SUBS 14th graf, `Two days ..., to add
that Smith is interim warden; SUBS 15th graf, `Butler, a ..., to clarify
that Butler never said conditions were bad. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rash of slayings, suicides and escapes
at the state penitentiary has led to the resignation of the warden
and once again focused negative attention on the Louisiana prison
system.
   Earlier this year, legislators spoke optimistically of ending
federal intervention in the prisons, begun in 1975 as a result of a
lawsuit that claimed inmates were living in squalor. But the
possibility of renewed state control seems remote now.
   Instead, U.S. District Judge Frank Polozola has demanded
step-by-step plans to move convicts out of parish jails. In
addition, he has dressed down prison officials who had criticized
his actions.
   ``Believe me, I truly don't want to be warden at any
institution,'' Polozola said at the hearing. ``I really didn't want
to go to law school to be a warden.''
   The state penitentiary at Angola has been racked by allegations
of drug dealing, lax security and low employee morale.
   The maximum security prison houses 4,800 inmates on its
18,000-acre site along the Mississippi. Because of court rulings,
the number of inmates is about the prison's intended capacity.
   In the 1950s when inmates were forced to work long hours in the
fields and housed in substandard cells, Angola was declared ``the
worst prison in America'' by one study. Conditions there contributed
to the 1971 lawsuit that led to the federal takeover.
   A 500-inmate cellblock at Angola was built several years ago but
hasn't opened because the state lacks funds to pay more guards.
   As a result of the manpower shortage at Angola and other
Louisiana prisons, 4,000 of the 16,000 inmates the state is
responsible for are being held by sheriffs in parish jails.
Officials in Orleans and Jefferson parishes have been forced to
release some accused criminals before trial because of a lack of
space.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer recently authorized $5 million to $8 million to
open the addition at Angola, and to step up construction of a new
prison in Winn Parish. Polozola, unmoved by the state's continuing
budget squeeze, has criticized the Legislature for not doing enough
to head off the problem.
   ``If the state can't do it, I will. That's not a threat. That's a
promise,'' Polozola said.
   On June 21, Polozola declared a state of emergency following four
fatal stabbings, four suicides and 11 escapes over 14 months at
Angola, and appointed former warden Ross Maggio to oversee a special
investigation.
   Maggio's Aug. 21 report said Angola was understaffed, that guards
were not properly trained to use firearms, and that prison officials
were not searching visitors or guards for drugs. He accused the
administration of lax management, saying it had not even filed
criminal charges against seven recaptured escapees.
   Two days later, Roemer asked Warden Hilton Butler to retire.
Larry Smith was appointed interim warden, becoming the
penitentiary's first black warden.
   Butler, a career corrections employee who ran the prison for 2{
years, has said the accusations against him were exaggerated, and
that conditions at the prison were similar under Maggio, his
predecessor.
   Roemer also ordered state police to re-open an investigation that
stemmed from a scandal involving former Pardon Board Chairman Howard
Marsellus Jr.
   Marsellus, who served under former Gov. Edwin Edwards, was
convicted of accepting money for pardon recommendations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
