<FIRST>u a PM-HelicopterSearch 1stLd-Writethru a0581 08-28 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Search, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0581,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Apparently Crashes With Shooting Suspect Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with crash confirmed, two bodies
found, criminal investigation under way; and to CORRECT first name of sheriff's
sergeant to Kenneth sted Kennedy. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Bob Zinkgraf...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical helicopter crashed in northern
Idaho while taking an injured criminal suspect to a hospital,
killing at least two persons, authorities said today.
   There were indications that the man, wounded in a Canadian border
shootout, scuffled with the helicopter's three-person crew before
the craft disappeared Sunday evening, and authorities said they were
treating the crash as a crime.
   Rescuers found two bodies in the wreckage of the helicopter where
it crashed in a mountainous region and were looking for the other
two people, said Kootenai County, Idaho, Sheriff's Sgt. Kenneth
Sopher. The helicopter had been en route to Sacred Heart Medical
Center in Spokane.
   ``The circumstances of the mishap ... definitely indicate that
it's not an aircraft accident,'' said Pete Mangum, an air safety
inspector with the National Transportation Safety Board in Seattle.
``The Kootenai County Sheriff's Office is investigating the incident
as a criminal activity other than an aircraft accident.''
   He declined to specify what evidence led authorities to believe a
crime had caused the crash, but a man who was monitoring radio
messages Sunday evening said the crew apparently radioed shortly
before the crash that they were having trouble with the wounded
suspect.
   The helicopter, an Aerospatiale Astar, also carried its pilot, a
nurse and a respiratory therapist, according to Marilyn Thordarson,
a spokeswoman for the hospital.
   The wreckage was spotted at about 10 a.m. near Spirit Mountain,
about two miles south of Blanchard Lake near the Washington-Idaho
border, Sopher saod.
   The copter was believed to be one of two that were dispatched to
Bonners Ferry, Idaho, to pick up two people wounded in the shooting,
which occurred after a man wanted by the Royal Canadian Mounted
Police forced his way into the United States from Canada at gunpoint.
   One helicopter picked up a wounded 71-year-old man and returned
to Spokane safely. The second copter left Bonners Ferry about 9:30
p.m. and disappeared about a half-hour later.
   Bob Zinkgraf, a resident of Colbert, about 15 miles north of
Spokane, said he was listening to a radio scanner when he overheard
what he believed was a report of a scuffle aboard the helicopter
shortly before 10 p.m.
   ``They reported they were having problems with the suspect,'' he
said. ``A couple of minutes minutes later, they reported they were
in a scuffle with the suspect.''
   Zinkgraf said he heard the hospital reporting that it had lost
contact with the helicopter a short time later, at about 10 p.m.
   Ms. Thordarson said she knew of no reports of difficulty from the
helicopter crew, only that it made a routine patient status report
shortly before radio contact became garbled and then was lost
altogether.
   Identities of those on board were not immediately released, but
authorities said the patient aboard the missing helicopter was
apparently the man sought by police for questioning about an
incident at the U.S. Customs Station at Eastport, Idaho.
   The border incident began Sunday about 7:30 p.m., during the
search of a vehicle of a man entering the U.S. from Canada, said
Cherise Miles, a U.S. Customs spokeswoman in Chicago.
   During a ``secondary'' inspection, the man pulled a gun and
disarmed Port Director Joe Hancock, then fled south on U.S Highway
95, said Ms. Miles. Hancock was not injured, she said.
   A short time later, a man approached the home of an elderly
couple about a mile south of the crossing station and forced his way
in, she said. A woman fled the house and called police, who later
found two wounded men, Ms. Miles said.
   She wouldn't give the name of the elderly couple, but the
hospital identified the injured man in the helicopter that arrived
safely as Bob McGlocklin, 71. He was reported in satisfactory
condition with gunshot wounds in his arm and back.
</TEXT>
