<FIRST>r w AM-US-Palestinians     08-28 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Palestinians,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Opposes PLO Membership In World Tourism Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department flatly opposed on Monday
any form of membership by the Palestine Liberation Organization in a
world tourism group as contrary to international law and the cause
of peace.
   It was not clear, however, that U.S. opposition would derail the
move under discussion at a meeting of the World Tourism Organization
in Paris since the United States does not have veto power.
   On the other hand, the Bush administration could discourage the
move if it chose to withhold financial support. The United States,
which covers 4 percent to 5 percent of the organization's budget, is
contributing $330,000 this year.
   The PLO, with which the administration is discussing Mideast
peace prospects, applied for membership on July 7 for ``Palestine.''
All Arab countries recognize Yasser Arafat's groups as the sole,
legitimiate representative of Palestinian Arabs and many other
countries have permitted the PLO to open quasi-embassies.
   The United States enhanced PLO prestige last December by opening
a dialogue that the Bush administration has continued despite an
evident lack of progress in promoting Arab-Israeli negotiations. On
the other hand, all U.S. administrations, as a matter of policy,
have been opposed to establishment of a Palestinian state on land
held by Israel.
   Asked about the PLO's latest push for acceptance, State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher declared: ``The U.S. is opposed
to admitting the PLO, or, quote, Palestine, unquote, to the World
Tourism Organization. In our view, the self-declared state of
Palestine, which we do not recognize, does not meet the generally
accepted criteria under international law for statehood, and thus
does not qualify for membership in international organizations.''
   ``Nor,'' Boucher said, ``do we believe that bestowing legitimacy
upon the self-proclaimed, quote, state, would advance the efforts to
promote peace in the Middle East. We're convinced that the final
status of the occupied territories can be determined only through
negotiations, not through unilateral acts that prejudge the outcome
of such negotiations. The declaration of Palestinian statehood was
such a unilateral act.''
   Boucher said the administration had made its views known to the
World Tourism Organization and ``we are consulting closely with
like-minded friends on how best to block these PLO efforts, which we
will continue to oppose vigorously.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
