<FIRST>u w PM-Thornburgh-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 08-28 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0567,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Official Meets with Thornburgh</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top four grafs new to UPDATE with de Grieff arrival for Justice
Department meeting; picks up 3rd graf pvs, White House. Deletes outtdated
material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian Justice Minister Monica de Greiff
came to the Justice Department under tight security today for a
meeting with Attorney General Dick Thornburgh about the war against
her country's drug lords.
   Mrs. de Greiff arrived in an unmarked official car that drove
into the Justice Department's underground parking garage. The
32-year-old jurist was in Washington for meetings with Bush
administration officials about fighting the war against the
Colombian cocaine cartel.
   There were also tentative plans for her to meet with State
Department officials later in the day, according to U.S. officials.
   Administration officials denied reports that Mrs. de Greiff had
resigned in the face of death threats from the leaders of the
Medellin cocaine cartel.
   White House spokesman Roman Papadiuk said the president of
Colombia, Virgilio Barco, has denied reports that Mrs. de Greiff had
resigned in the face of death threats from drug lords, and his
``words are good enough for me.''
   Papadiuk, speaking to reporters in Kennebunkport, Maine, where
President Bush is vacationing, said Mrs. de Greiff planned to
discuss efforts to break the drug cartels in Colombia with officials
of the State and Justice departments and extraditing drug lords
wanted by U.S. authorities to this country.
   U.S. officials said there were tentative plans for Mrs. de Greiff
to have an afternoon meeting with senior State Department officials,
including Undersecretary of State Robert Kimmitt.
   The time and place were not disclosed.
   U.S. officials said they had heard unconfirmed reports that Mrs.
de Greiff's 3-year-old son, who accompanied her here from Bogota,
was the target of a death threat.
   According to the officials, who asked not to be identified, Mrs.
de Greiff's place of residence during her stay here was being kept
secret for security reasons.
   Thornburgh said Sunday on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' that efforts
to extradite Eduardo Martinez Romero, the most prominent alleged
Colombian drug figure arrested in recent government sweeps against
the cartel, are proceeding and ``we expect to have him delivered to
U.S. authorities this week.''
   Martinez reputedly is involved in the Colombian cartel's money
laundering operation, but was not one of a dozen Colombian drug
traffickers included in a U.S. ``most wanted'' list sent to Colombia
last week.
   The three men at the top of the U.S. list are Pablo Escobar,
Jorge Ochoa and Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha. All have evaded the
government crackdown and are believed to be in hiding.
   Thornburgh also said unconfirmed sightings of some of Colombia's
drug cartel kingpins have been reported, but he suggested there is
little to indicate any of them will be captured soon.
   ``As in most fugitive situations, there are sightings of these
figures, but they're very clever, they're well financed,''
Thornburgh said.
   Meanwhile, William Bennett, President Bush's drug czar, said the
Colombian drug operation has been severely disrupted even if the top
kingpins have eluded capture.
   ``These guys need to feel the heat,'' Bennett said on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press'' interview show.
   President Bush last week announced plans for a $64 million
military aid package to Colombia that ncludes the use of U.S.
military advisers and equipment.
</TEXT>
