<DOCNO> AP890828-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     08-28 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki to Present Government in September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki met with
coalition leaders Monday about forming the East bloc's first
non-communist government, but a Solidarity deputy said a new Cabinet
could not be presented until September.
   Also Monday, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said he plans to
appeal to workers for a moratorium on strikes to give the new
government time to solve Poland's pressing problems.
   ``There are no major obstacles or difficulties in forming the
government, only there is a certain inevitable slow process,'' said
Bronislaw Geremek, the Solidarity parliamentary floor leader.
   Mazowiecki, elected the first non-communist government leader in
the East bloc in more than 40 years on Thursday, had said he would
like to present the government to the Sejm by the end of August.
   ``The prime minister did not realize this inevitable slowness
when he gave the date of Aug. 31, and he cannot keep that promise.
We think the government could be presented to the Sejm before Sept.
10,'' Geremek said.
   Geremek and other members of the Solidarity parliamentary group
met with Mazowiecki for two hours Monday. The prime minister also
received separately the parliamentary and party leaders of the
Democratic and Peasant Parties.
   The independent Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper said Monday that Walesa
would issue a statement in the coming days about the need for strike
moratorium of at least a six months.
   Walesa has said that labor peace and Western aid are necessary to
help reverse Poland's economic decline and provide a favorable
climate for the new government.
   Asked in Gdansk on Monday when the moratorium request would be
issued, Walesa replied: ``We should do it together with the
appointment of the (whole) government.''
   ``We have the biggest chance ever to make the Poland of our
dreams. We can go in this direction but we cannot do it if we are
going to suffer economic losses,'' he said.
   Walesa will appeal to workers not to strike and said Solidarity
would help them in the meantime to negotiate with management, Gazeta
Wyborcza said.
   Pay disputes have broken out on an almost daily basis in the
country in the past six months, but most of the work stoppages have
been brief.
   Workers are frustrated by soaring inflation, empty shelves and
stores with poor quality goods, as well as by the lack of visible
economic improvements since Solidarity was legalized in April after
a seven-year ban and Poland's freest elections in more than four
decades were held in June.
   Geremek said the parliamentary group discussed its relationship
with the prime minister, the government's economic program and the
distribution of ministries.
   Drafting an economic plan is the most difficult problem the
government faces, he said.
   ``A sketch of the economic program emerged during the electoral
campaign. Now is not the time to define the direction of the
program, but to define the strategy, in particular a choice between
a step-by-step approach and a big bang,'' he said.
   ``We have the impression now that a policy of radical (economic)
change is necessary. ... From the start this government must see the
need to give some signs of improvement in the short term,'' he said.
   Geremek said the improvement must concern supplying goods to
major cities and that the government must also find a way to stop
inflation, which has reached three digits.
   The Communist Party has been promised the key ministries of
defense and the interior which control the army and the police, and
Geremek indicated that the communists may be asked to take an
economic ministry as well.
   ``To give them the ministries of the interior and the army and no
economic ministry would be a big mistake. They would have all the
power and no responsibility,'' he said.
   The Solidarity group also told Mazowiecki it was important to
diminish the Communist Party's monopoly over mass media,
particularly radio and television.
   Until now, state radio and television were administered by a
state-run committee whose chairman held the rank of minister.
Geremek suggested the new head of radio and television could be
someone who is not a member of the government.
   ``There is no place in the government for a minister of
information,'' he said.
   As part of the agreements that led to Solidarity's legalization
and the election, the indpendent movement was granted permission to
publish a daily and weekly newspaper. It also has limited access to
state TV and radio.
</TEXT>
