<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Refugees     08-28 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Refugees,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Catch Chinese Posing as Vietnamese Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese authorities said Monday they detained two
Chinese refugees posing as Vietnamese boat people and launched a new
policy of refusing Vietnamese who flee their homeland for economic
reasons.
   Refugees from political persecution still will be accepted under
the policy that began Monday, said Yoichiro Mizukami of the Justice
Ministry's Immigration Bureau.
   He said the decision to start the screening was made after the
two Chinese were discovered and detained for illegal entry.
   Other Asian countries have adopted similar screening policies for
Vietnamese boat people, but Japan so far had taken in all boat
people.
   The Justice Ministry said in a statement that immigration
authorities discovered the two Chinese among 107 Vietnamese boat
people who arrived in southwestern Japan in a wooden boat May 29.
   It said the two Chinese, both from Fujian province in
southeastern China, had pretended to be boat people in hopes of
becoming permament residents of Japan or at least finding work.
   Landing permission for the pair was retracted and they were taken
into custody, it added. A ministry official, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said Japan would deport them to their homeland but
declined to discuss details.
   The ministry also said remarks by the two Chinese led authorities
to believe many Chinese or Chinese-Vietnamese were included among
arriving boat people.
   Earlier, a Justice Ministry official said merchants in southern
China were helping many Vietnamese refugees travel by boat to Japan.
   Also Monday, another wooden vessel with 203 Vietnamese refugees
was found heading for Japan, an official of Japan's coast guard
said. The Justice Ministry said they would face screening under the
new policy.
   So far this year, 1,909 Vietnamese have arrived in Japan,
compared with 219 boat people in all of 1988, according to Justice
Ministry figures.
   Many refugees have said they came to Japan for a better economic
life, Ministry officials reported.
</TEXT>
