<FIRST>u a AM-Bush     08-28 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Declines To Comment On Covert Action in Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, on the eve of a drug
policy strategy session with top advisers, was noncommittal Monday
on the possibility of using covert military actions to help Colombia
fight drug lords.
   Bush was briefed on the Colombia situation at his seaside
vacation home by national security adviser Brent Scowcroft as the
South American nation's justice minister met with administration
officials in Washington. This came a day after reports surfaced that
the minister, Monica de Greiff, had resigned in the face of death
threats from drug traffickers.
   President Virgilio Barco informed U.S. officials that Ms. de
Greiff, was not resigning, White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said.
   As he teed off for golf, the vacationing Bush was asked about a
Newsweek report that he was considering sending covert military
teams into Colombia to assist Barco's crackdown
   ``If I discussed covert action it wouldn't be covert. I don't
discuss that kind of thing at all,'' he replied.
   Bush cautioned that his reply should not be interpreted as a
``yes or a no or a confirm or a deny.''
   Popadiuk told reporters in response to a question about covert
operations: ``Obviously we are very concenrned about he Colombian
drug situation. .. but in terms of specific actions we may or may
not be undertaking, we just don't comment on any covert activities
that may or may not be undertaken.''
   Another administration official said that Bush would like to use
U.S. military teams and special forces to help Barco. But the
president's hands are tied by Barco's own statements that he does
not want such assistance, said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The Colombians are sensitive to the appearance of a heavy-handed
U.S. presence in their country, an image the Latin countries try to
avoid, the official said.
   Bush on Tuesday was to meet here with Attorney Gen. Dick
Thornburgh, Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney, Assistant Secretary of
State Lawrence Eagleburger, CIA Director William Webster and drug
policy coordinator William Bennett.
   They were to help put the final touches on a national drug
strategy that Bush is to announce in a nationally broadcast White
House address Sept. 5.
   Popadiuk said that Ms. de Grieff was in Washington to discuss
efforts to break the drug cartels in Colombia and extradite to the
United States suspected traffickers.
   Asked if the 32-year-old minister discussed wanting asylum,
Popadiuk said, ``I do not know of any such discussions.'
   Bush later told reporters that it was ``too hypothetical'' to say
what advice he would give Ms. De Grieff about asylum.
   Thornburgh said Sunday he knew of no request for political asylum
from Ms. De Greiff, but said it ``would not be surprising'' in light
of the drug lords' violence.
   The officials, all speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
had heard unconfirmed reports that the Colombian minister's
3-year-old son, who accompanied her from Bogota, was the target of a
death threat.
   The White House announced Friday that Bush was sending $65
million in emergency aid to Colombia for the drug fight. It includes
$5 million to protect judges and other Colombian justice officials
threatened by the drug traffickers, who have warned they will kill
20 judges for each drug trafficker extradited to the United States.
   On another subject, the vacation White House announced Monday
that Bush formally asked Congress for a 3.6 percent pay raise for
federal civilian workers effective in January 1990, as previously
agreed to in budget negotiations.
   The president rejected pay advisers' recommendation of a 28.6
percent raise for the civil servants. Bush also warned South Korea
that he may bar fish imports if it does not reach an agreement with
the United States on driftnet fishing in the next 30 days.
</TEXT>
