<FIRST>r i AM-Chess     08-28 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portisch Moves up to Share Third Place in Chess World Cup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SKELLEFTEA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lajos Portisch of Hungary moved up to
share third place in the Chess World Cup on Monday after the
completion of the adjourned games.
   With four rounds remaining, world chess champion Garri Kasparov
and the former titleholder Anatoly Karpov, both Soviets, are tied
for first place with seven points out of a possible 11.
   Portisch defeated Valery Salov of the Soviet Union in a marathon
91-move battle when play resumed in their adjourned game from the
10th round.
   After a 30-minute break, Salov returned to complete his
unfinished 11th round game with British Grandmaster John Nunn. Their
game was agreed drawn on the 74th move.
   Portisch, Yasser Seirawan of the United States and British
Grandmaster Nigel Short are all tied for third with 6{ points.
   The World Cup is a series of six tournaments featuring the
world's top 25 grandmasters and a total prize fund of $1.2 million.
The 12th round is scheduled for Tuesday, and the final round will be
played Saturday.
   Widely regarded as the second most important chess event after
the individual world championship cycle, this final part of the
World Cup is the third strongest tournament ever held.
   Karpov, who held the world title for 10 years before losing it to
Kasparov in 1985, needs to win all four of his final games to catch
his countryman in the series.
   Since 1981, Kasparov has won or tied for first in every
tournament he has played.
</TEXT>
