<FIRST>r a AM-Congressman-Prostitute     08-28 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressman-Prostitute,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Grateful for Constituent Response; Professor Asks for Sodomy
Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank said Monday that reaction
among friends and constituents to his relationship with a male
prostitute has been ``more generous than I really had any right to
expect.''
   Opponents kept up their criticism, however, and a law professor
asked prosecutors Monday to file felony sodomy charges against the
five-term Democrat from Massachusetts.
   On Friday, Frank confirmed details of a newspaper account of his
paying the man for sex once and then hiring him as a personal
assistant, believing he could help reform him. He said he fired the
man when he suspected he was selling sex from Frank's apartment.
   Frank said he did not believe he or anyone else in such a
situation should be prosecuted.
   ``I felt that they were poor judgments, and that if they
victimized anybody, they victimized me,'' he said. ``That is, I
never felt I was hurting anybody except myself.''
   Two polls published over the weekend showed that voters in the
state's 4th District still strongly supported Frank.
   Frank, 49, made two public appearances in Fall River over the
weekend where a few muffled ``boos'' were overwhelmed by applause
and cheers.
   ``I guess it means people think I've done a good job in the past.
It's nice to have that. I work hard at my job,'' he said. ``I'm
touched because right now, obviously, I'm chagrined and angry at
myself as I rethink all this.
   ``People are being nicer to me than I'm ready to be to myself
right now.''
   Alexander Tennant, executive director of the state Republican
Party, called on Frank to resign for apparently violating the law
and predicted that voter opinion will change once the GOP makes it
clear Frank not only hired a male prostitute but also wrote letters
on the man's behalf to his probation officer.
   ``The Democrats are arguing this is a personal matter. We are
arguing that there is a very serious public matter,'' Tennant said.
He and other Republicans are asking for an House ethics
investigation, to which Frank said he had no objection.
   George Washington law Professor John Banzhaf said ``many people
don't think Frank confessed to a crime. He has.''
   Banzhaf said he asked U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens of the District
of Columbia to also investigate other charges related to
prostitution, including running a bawdy house and soliciting for
prostitution.
   ``What Banzhaf is saying is that every gay person in Washington,
D.C., who is not totally abstinent is a criminal,'' said Frank.
   ``In a lot of districts, if two people who are not married have
any kind of sex they're breaking the law. And in some states if
married people have a certain kind of sex they're breaking the law
and ... I have always thought that was a mistake.''
   Felony sodomy in the District of Columbia carries up to 10 years
in prison. The other charges carry lesser penalties, said Banzhaf,
who teaches public interest law and has filed suits in a number of
corruption cases involving federal officials.
   Frank said he hired the male prostitute, Steve Gobie, to run
errands and do chores, hoping to help Gobie give up prostitution and
drugs. Frank said that two years ago he fired Gobie, who turns 33 on
Monday, because he suspected Gobie was selling sex out of the
congressman's apartment when he wasn't home.
</TEXT>
