<DOCNO> AP890828-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1924EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StrikeStruggles     08-28 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strike Struggles,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Strike Suffocating Mining Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTWOOD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decent pair of shoes is as hard to find
as a patch of flat land in this coal mining community now that the
last clothing store has shut its doors.
   The strike against the Pittston Coal Group is slowly suffocating
Dickenson County, where nearly a third of the striking United Mine
Workers live.
   The county had been in an economic downturn for more than four
years when the strike began April 5. Since then, the county has lost
coal tax revenue, the school budget has been cut deeply and
businesses have been hurt by the lack of buying power.
   The county's unemployment rate for July, announced Monday, was
9.2 percent, second-highest in the state.
   ``It's really put a strain on the community as a whole,'' said
Henry Vanover, the county administrator.
   But the loyalty of its people to the union remains as deep as the
black veins that provide the county's lifeblood.
   ``You can go into any town and find widespread community support
for the union and the union's position,'' Commonwealth's Attorney
Gerald Gray said.
   Carrol Deckard, for example, said she donates 10 percent of the
sales at her craft and novelty store in Clintwood, The Odd Shop, to
the union.
   ``This is a coal mining town. It's all we've got,'' she said.
``The union brought decent wages here where people used to work for
$1 an hour. If the union doesn't get a contract, we're gone. We've
already lost three stores.''
   The geography that makes Dickenson County rich in coal and lured
miners from Scotland and Ireland a century ago also makes it
dependent on the mineral.
   The rugged county is surrounded by large mountain ranges. The
county needs to upgrade its roads and its water and sewer systems to
compete for industry, Gray said.
   But the government can barely make ends meet now and may have to
borrow before the end of the fiscal year to provide essential
services, Vanover said.
   To show both the isolation of the area and the closeness of its
people, Gray noted that 95 percent of the people living in the
county are descendants of the original settlers.
   Pittston owns about 70 percent of the surface land and 95 percent
of the underground reserves, Gray said. ``In essence, they are the
landlords and we are the tenants,'' he said.
   Although Pittston denies it is trying to do away with collective
bargaining, the residents and business owners believe for the most
part that the company is trying to break the union. That is making
the stakes of the strike higher than any previous labor dispute and
drawing the community together.
   Most of the replacement workers are from out of state. When local
residents cross over, Gray said, it splits families.
   Denny Boggs pointed to a trailer next to his service station and
said the woman who lives there disowned her father when he went to
work for Pittston.
   ``People who have been friends all their lives are being
separated, kids who grew up together,'' Harold Willis added as he
paid Boggs for his gas.
   Pittston's replacement workers are digging 40 percent less coal
than normal, which means a 40 percent reduction in coal severance
taxes. Vanover estimated that the county has lost $200,000 in
anticipated severance tax revenue and will continue to lose about
$60,000 each month the strike goes on.
   The schools open next week with their budget for the year cut
$400,000.
   ``It doesn't look very good for us, even to maintain present
standards,'' Assistant Superintendent Gerald Triplett said. The
county has cut four teaching positions, and more reductions are
possible, he said.
   There is no indication the strike involving Pittston's 1,695
union employees in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky will end
soon.
   Real estate and personal property taxes counted on in the county
budget are due Dec. 5, and many striking miners may not be able to
pay them, Gray said.
   Several stores have gone bankrupt. The striking miners are making
$200 a week in strike pay compared with $500 a week before they
walked out, which means they have only enough to cover groceries and
monthly bills.
   ``The loss of revenue is a strain, but the worst part is the
effect on people, their spirits, the longer it goes,'' Vanover said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
