<FIRST>r w AM-CanadianPork     08-28 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canadian Pork,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duty On Canadian Pork Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Trade Commission cleared the
way for a duty on imports of subsidized Canadian pork, ruling Monday
that the shipments have hurt American meatpackers.
   However, Canada is contesting the duty before a two-nation panel
set up by the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement and could appeal the
commission's 3-2 ruling.
   The Commerce Department imposed the 3-cent-per-pound duty in
July, but the commission was required to find that American
producers were being injured by the Canadian subsidy.
   Canadian pork imports ``present a real and imminent threat to the
domestic industry,'' said Commissioner David B. Rohr.
   ``Today's decision is a victory for U.S. pork producers and fair
trade,'' said Don Gingerich, president of the National Pork
Producers Council. ``The countervailing duty should send a clear
signal to the Canadian pork industry to curb its excess production.''
   Imports of Canadian pork products have increased by more than 52
percent since 1984, according to the producers group.
   The duty applies to shipments of subsidized fresh, chilled and
frozen pork from Canada. The Commerce Department imposed the duty
after determining that Canadian payment programs amount to a subsidy
on pork. The revenue was put into escrow until the commission ruled.
   Canadian pork representatives petitioned last week for the
appeals panel to review the Commerce Department's decision, and the
Canadian government expressed disappointment with the commission's
decision Monday.
   ``We do not agree with this ruling,'' said Canadian Agriculture
Minister Don Mazankowski. ``In our view, the Canadian industry had
made a compelling case before the commission for a no-injury finding
in this investigation.''
   Commission Chairman Anne Brunsdale, who voted against the
commission's finding, said she did not think the Canadian subsidy
was a significant threat to U.S. meatpackers.
   She said Canadian pork imports amounted to just 0.4 percent of
U.S. production.
   Rep. Tim Johnson, D-S.D., wrote President Bush Monday urging him
to raise the issue of pork imports when he meets Wednesday with
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   ``Truckloads of subsidized Canadian pork products are being
dumped over the border, where they unfairly undercut producers from
South Dakota and other states,'' Johnson said.
</TEXT>
