<FIRST>u a AM-BushRdp     08-28 0976</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Rdp,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Gorbachev; Remains Silent on Colombian Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 14th graf, bgng, The Doles xxx to CORRECT Hussein to Hassan;
INSERTS 24th graf, bgng, Walt Riker ... etc., to UPDATE with statement
by Dole spokesman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday praised
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev for being ``extraordinarily
understanding'' of the changes taking place in Eastern Europe and
expressed hope that change can continue peacefully both outside the
Soviet Union and within it.
   The president also said it wil take ``a lot more money'' than his
$119 million aid package to help Poland rebuild its economy, but
said that political and economic reforms must come first.
   Bush said that once reforms take hold in Poland, more aid will be
forthcoming from the international financial institutions that help
developing countries.
   The president spoke with reporters on the lawn outside his
oceanfront home after getting a firsthand report from Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., on their just-completed visit to Poland and their talks with
the country's new leaders.
   Asked whether the Soviet Communist Party's criticism of the
Baltic nationalism movement might be a prelude to a crackdown, the
president said, ``I hope not.''
   Gorbachev has told officials of the Lithuanian Communist Party
that the Baltic republic has gone too far in its drive for
independence, an activist said Monday.
   In Vilnius, Lithuania, Romaldus Ozolus, a member of the governing
council, or Sejm, of the Sajudis grassroots movement, said he and
four colleagues met with Lithuanian Communist Party chief Algirdas
Brazauskas after Gorbachev called the Lithuanian party leader on
Friday and Sunday to express his concern.
   Bush said, ``I think that Mr. Gorbachev's reaction to the changes
in Poland were extraordinarily understanding and certainly not
militant in any way, and I hope that would be the tone as the rapid
change that's taking place in Eastern Europe goes forward, not just
in Poland, but in other countries as well.''
   ``I must say the way Mr. Gorbachev has handled this and reacted
to it has been very positive,'' the president said.
   ``Let's hope that change continues to take place peacefully, and
not only outside the Soviet Union, but in it. ... We want to see
perestroika succeed,'' he said.
   Bush said that if Solidarity leader Lech Walesa visits the United
States later this year, ``I certainly will'' meet with him.
   On another topic, Bush declined to say what advice he would give
Colombian Minister of Justice Monica de Greiff if she seeks asylum
in the United States. ``It's too hypothetical for me to answer that
question,'' he said.
   The Doles made a detour here on their way home from Europe after
visiting Morocco, Armenia, Poland and The Netherlands. They brought
Bush a letter from Walesa, as well as their own letter outlining the
urgency of the appeals they heard for help from Polish leaders,
including new Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowecki and President Wojiech
Jaruzelski, the former Communist Party chief.
   The Doles also brought Bush greetings from Morocco's King Hassan,
who has been in the midst of efforts to end the strife in Lebanon.
   Mrs. Dole said of Poland, ``It was incredible and it was really
awesome to be there at this particular time in the history of
Poland.''
   She said the Poles appreciate the help Bush has already
proferred. ``They're seeking more foreign investment and hoping that
our banks will establish branches in Poland. ... And they're
concerned about food. They feel that some change there within the
short term is important because the shelves are empty and they need
more food,'' Mrs. Dole said.
   Her husband, the Kansas senator, said Polish leaders all
``indicated some urgency'' and one ``used the word `emergency.' ''
   ``We came away with the feeling that maybe the time is not great.
Maybe it's 60 days, maybe it's three months. Walesa said yesterday
maybe it's six months to a year, the people need to see a change,''
the senator said.
   He added, ``They don't want to be a welfare client. They want
investments. They want banks. They want opportunities. And it's
going to take a while to change that system after 45 years ... to a
market economy.''
   Asked if he felt $119 million was enough, Bush said, ``I think to
satisfy all the requirements of Poland, it could take a lot more
money than that. But it's also got to take political reform. It's
got to take economic reform so that when they talk about investment
and privatization, something really happens.''
   ``And once those reforms are in place and on forward, then you
will find that your multilateral financial institutions will be in a
much better place to help,'' said Bush, who added that he hopes that
support will build in Congress for those lending institutions.
   Mrs. Dole said her department will dispatch a team to help Poland
on such matters as job training and unemployment insurance once the
new government selects a labor minister.
   The Doles made the sidetrip here via a Marine helicopter after
landing at Pease Air Force Base in neighboring New Hampshire on
their way home to Washington. They were joined by Rep. Bob McEwen,
R-Ohio, and his wife, Liz, who visited Poland separately and picked
up with the Doles in The Netherlands.
   Walt Riker, the senator's aide, said the Doles called Bush on
Sunday to request the meeting because of their own sense of urgency.
``There's a limited window of opportunity now in Poland,'' Riker
said.
   Dole said the devastation in Armenia from last December's
earthquake was ``heart-rending,'' and he said 700,000 people are
still homeless from the disaster that killed 35,000 to 50,000
Armenians.
   Bush, meantime, went fishing, but failed to catch anything,
keeping intact a bad streak that began Aug. 16, the first day of his
vacation.
</TEXT>
