<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Alsop 1stLd-Writethru a0598 08-28 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Alsop, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0598,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Columnist Joseph Alsop Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 8th graf, During World xxx to elaborate on Alsop's war
record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Alsop, a political columnist for 37
years, died Monday at his Georgetown home here. He was 78.
   Alsop's health had been declining for several months, said
Patricia Alsop, wife of his late brother, Stewart. His death was
attributed to lung cancer, anemia and emphysema, Mrs. Alsop said.
   The Alsop brothers, who began as New Deal liberals in the spirit
of their cousin Franklin Delano Roosevelt but became more
conservative in later years, wrote a political column syndicated by
the now-defunct New York Herald Tribune.
   Alsop started his career as a newsman at the Herald Tribune after
graduating from Harvard University in 1932. Five years later, he
began writing a political column for the North American Newspaper
Alliance. He wrote his first books, ``The 168 Days'' and ``Men
Around the President,'' in 1938.
   He wrote several other books, including ``We Accuse'' with
brother Stewart.
   Alsop wrote a column for the Herald Tribune with his brother from
1946-1958, at which time his brother joined The Saturday Evening
Post. Joseph Alsop continued the column alone, first for The
Washington Post and later for The Los Angeles Times Syndicate. He
also contributed articles for magazines, including The New Yorker.
   He retired from daily and weekly writing in 1974, the year
Stewart died, but continued to write books and articles.
   He was commissioned as a lieutenant in the Navy in 1940. He
resigned the commission in August 1941 and joined the American
Volunteer Air Group as an aide to Gen. Claire Chennault of the
Flying Tigers. Alsop was captured by the Japanese in Hong Kong in
December 1941 and held prisoner until he was exchanged in June 1942.
Later he served as chief of the Lend Lease Mission to China and in
1943 went to China as a captain in the Army Air Forces.
   In retirement, he became known for his Asian art collection and
was invited to lecture at the National Gallery of Art as part of the
Andrew W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts in 1977.
   Alsop, whose 17-year marriage to Susan Mary Alsop ended in 1978,
had no children.
   The Avon, Conn., native leaves two stepchildren, William S.
Patten of Camden, Maine, and Anne Milliken of Salt Lake City; a
brother, John deKoven Alsop of Old Lyme, Conn.; and a sister,
Corinne Chubb of Chester, N.J.
   A funeral service is planned for 11 a.m. Thursday at St. John's
Episcopal Church at Lafayette Square in Washington. Family members
also are planning to hold a memorial service in September. A date
has not been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890828-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-PayRaise     08-28 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Pay Raise,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Proposes 3.6 Percent Raise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday recommended
to Congress a 3.6 percent pay raise for federal employees,
formalizing an agareement worked out last spring.
   The raise, agreed upon by congressional leaders and the
administration, would be effective in January 1990.
   A letter containing the formal recommendation from Bush to House
Speaker Thomas Foley was released by the travelling White House
accompanying Bush on his vacation in Kennebunkport.
   Bush wrote that the government's pay advisory commission had
concluded a pay raise of 28.6 percent would be consistent with
current provisions requiring federal government pay to be comparable
with private-sector pay.
   However, Bush noted he has the power to alter the comparability
rules in the case of national emergency or economic conditions
affecting the general welfare.
   He said that 28.6 percent raise would be unacceptable because of
``adverse budgetary and economic effects.''
   Initially, Bush had proposed a 2 percent federal pay increase in
his 1990 budget request.
   In addition, Bush has previously recommended pay increases of up
to 25 percent for some top level federal executives, although
legislation pending in the House would freeze that pay and that of
judges.
   ``We feel there is a better alternative'' to the House proposal,
White House spokesman Steve Hart said Monday in reference to the
president's pay increase propoals for senior executives and judges.
</TEXT>
