<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Mosque     08-28 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Mosque,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Mayor and Moslem Leader Sign Pace to Build Mosque</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Charvieu-Chavagneux and the head
of the local Moslem community signed a pact Monday aimed at easing
religious tension caused by the city bulldozing a mosque.
   Mayor Gerard Dezempte and Abdelhag Benyaya, president of the
Islamic Cultural Association, said they ``condemned any act of
violence against people and property as well as statements urging
the communities to confront each other.''
   A joint statement said the two agreed the town will have a new
mosque.
   Dezempte campaigned for re-election last spring saying he opposed
granting a permit to build a new mosque because it would attract
more Moslems to the community.
   Charview-Chavagneux, a town of 8,000 people about 20 miles east
of Lyon, became a national focus for religious tension when the
building used as a Mosque by 800 Moslems was knocked down on Aug. 16.
   The battering began just after early morning prayers, and one of
those inside was slightly injured.
   Dezempte said the bulldozer was supposed to knock down a
different wing of the building, not the one used as a mosque.
   The following day several city properties were set ablaze and
suffered minor damage.
   Benyaya said Monday he will pursue charges he filed accusing the
mayor of violating Moslems' religious freedom by destroying the
mosque, but will stop holding Friday prayers in front of City Hall
as a protest.
   Dezempte said he will not withdraw his criminal charges of arson
against unknown perpetrators for the fires on city property.
   France has about 3 million Moslems, many immigrants or children
of North African immigrants, in a population of 55 million. Islam is
the country's second-largest religion after Roman Catholicism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
