<DOCNO> AP890828-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Wallenberg     08-28 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Wallenberg,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Looking for Missing Swedish Diplomat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet activist Andrei Sakharov visited
labor camps in search of Raoul Wallenberg this year but found no
trace of the Swedish diplomat missing since 1945, Svenska Dagbladet
newspaper said Monday.
   A Swedish Foreign Ministry official confirmed the Soviet human
rights activist recently elected a legislator was pursuing
Wallenberg's fate. He also said the ministry has released previously
classified documents to the newspaper.
   Svenska Dagbladet quoted documents as relating that Sakharov
heard of another long-term prisoner in the Soviet Union who, the
paper concluded, may have been confused with Wallenberg.
   The Swedish diplomat is credited with rescuing tens of thousands
of Hungarian Jews from Nazi extermination before he was arrested in
1945 by Soviet troops entering Budapest.
   Soviet officials say files discovered in 1957 show Wallenberg
died of natural causes in prison 10 years earlier. But other
prisoners reported seeing Wallenberg long after he allegedly died.
He would be 77 years old now.
   Vollrath Tham, the Foreign Ministry official in charge of
Wallenberg's case, confirmed Sakharov had visited labor camps to
seek word of the missing man. Sakharov's last communication was in
March, he said.
   Tham declined to disclose further information. He said
``substantial parts'' of the Wallenberg file remain classified and
were withheld from Svenska Dagbladet.
   The paper said it examined more than 6,000 pages of documents.
   It reported a December conversation between Sakharov and Andrs
Wijkman, head of the Swedish Red Cross.
   Sakharov told Wijkman that, acting on information from a Swedish
source, he and his wife Yelena Bonner searched for Wallenberg at two
labor camps near Torzhok, 125 miles northwest of Moscow, but found
no trace of him.
   The Nobel Peace Prize winner also reported learning about a
recently released prisoner called Einar Marcus who helped save Jews
in Czechoslovakia from Nazi deportation.
   Marcus, who apparently is of Swedish descent, had told a friend
of Sakharov about his wartime service and that, like Wallenberg, he
was arrested at the end of the war.
   The paper concluded that if the story is correct, several people
who reported seeing a Swedish diplomat in prison may have met
Marcus, not Wallenberg.
   Sakharov suggested Sweden send an envoy to talk to Marcus, who
now lives in Syktyvkar, 600 miles northeast of Moscow.
   On Sunday, Soviet television broadcast a report on Wallenberg for
the first time and appealed to anyone who had any information on him
to step forward.
   The broadcast was the latest sign of glasnost, or openness, on
the case which Soviet authorities had tried to bury for years.
   No reason was ever given for Wallenberg's arrest, but it is
assumed he was mistaken for a spy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
