<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia-Kosovo     08-28 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Kosovo Leader, 14 Others Charged with Counterrevolutionary
Acts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  The former Communist Party chief in
Kosovo province, Azem Vllasi, and 14 other ethnic Albanians were
charged with counterrevolutionary activities in ethnic unrest there,
Tanjug said Monday.
   If convicted, the 15 could be sentenced to death.
   The state news agency said Vllasi and the others were accused of
trying to destroy fraternity and unity of peoples and nationalities.
   The accused ``created danger for the life of people ... caused
grave violence, imperiled the security and economic strength of the
country, which amounted to posing a counterrevolutionary threat to
the social system,'' Tanjug quoted the indictment as saying .
   Spasoje Zamfirovic, the prosecutor in the town of Titova
Mitrovica, said all 15 organized and supported mass protest meetings
and demonstrations of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo in November.
   They also orchestrated a strike by 1,300 miners in a lead and
zinc mine last February, he was quoted as saying.
   At least 23 demonstrators and two policemen were killed in spring
riots in Kosovo after ethnic Albanian miners staged a weeklong
sit-in at the mine to protest constitutional changes giving the
republic of Serbia greater control over Kosovo, an autonomous
province.
   Vllasi was arrested shortly after he talked to the miners. His
lawyers say he tried to persuade them to leave, but his accusers say
he was conspiring with ethnic Albanian separatists who want the
province to become a republic.
   Ethnic Albanians comprise nearly 90 percent of the 1.7-million
people of Kosovo, where Slavs claim they are being harassed by
Albanians.
   The accused are being held at Titova Mitrovica, 130 miles south
of Belgrade.
   Zamfirovic told Tanjug the trial will be held within two months.
</TEXT>
