<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-28 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Cause Flooding in Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms pushed streams over their banks and flooded streets
in the Midwest and produced walnut-sized hail in North Dakota on
Monday.
   Strong thunderstorms developed in hot, humid air across northern
Missouri into central Illinois and central Indiana. Rainfall totals
in Indiana included more than 3 inches in Frankfort, nearly 2}
inches in Antioch and 1\ inches in 15 minutes in Sheridan.
   Heavy rains prompted the closure of state Highway 28 in Clinton
County, Ind., and knocked out power in Lafayette, Ind.
   Thunderstorms rumbled across eastern North Dakota ahead of a cold
front Monday morning. Walnut-size hail fell from a severe
thunderstorm near Cooperstown, N.D.
   Thunderstorms also extended along the Gulf Coast, Florida and the
southern Atlantic Coast, with nearly two inches of rain recorded in
Pensacola, Fla. Showers and thunderstorms were scattered in central
Arkansas, New Mexico, the Texas Panhandle and southwest Kansas.
   Hot and very humid weather was common again Monday afternoon
throughout much of the south central and southeast portions of the
nation. Temperatures were in the 90s from Florida and the South
Carolina coast across the Gulf Coast and the lower Mississippi
valley into the southern Plains.
   Temperatures were in the 90s, but with low humidity, across the
desert Southwest.
   The coolest readings were in the northern Rockies, where
temperatures were in the 50s or 60s. Temperatures also were in the
60s along the Pacific coast and from North Dakota into upper
Michigan.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., and Arcata, Calif., to 101 degrees at
Palm Springs, Calif., and Beeville, Texas. The low in the nation
Monday morning was 30 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   On Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms are expected from the
eastern half of the Gulf Coast region and Florida to much of the
Atlantic Coast states, as well as from the central Appalachians
across the Great Lakes region, the Ohio Valley, the lower
Mississippi Valley, much of Kansas and the Texas Panhandle into
southeast New Mexico.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 80s across much of
the nation. Highs in the 70s were forecast from Washington state
across the northern Rockies, the northern Plains, the upper
Mississippi Valley and the northern half of the Great Lakes into New
England, as well as along the Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures in the 90s were expected throughout the southern and
central Plateau, the interior valleys of California, and from the
middle and southern Atlantic Coast and Florida across the Gulf
Coast, the western half of the Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi
Valley into the southern Plains. High temperatures were forecast to
climb between 100 and 110 degrees over the desert Southwest and near
the big bend of the Rio Grande Valley in Texas.
</TEXT>
