<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Colombia     08-28 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Colombia,0856</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Investigate Officer Suspected of Training Drug Ring Killers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday questioned two former Israeli
military officers about reports they trained gunmen for Colombian
cocaine bosses. One said the civilians he trained may have later
been hired by drug lords.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said Monday on Army Radio that
Israel will make every effort to prevent Israelis from working as
mercenaries in Latin America, declaring: ``We will do everything in
our power to enforce the law and prevent all aid by Israelis to the
drug cartel.''
   Lt. Col. Yair Klein said in an interview shortly before being
questioned by police that ``the force we trained was so strong that
the drug dealers wanted them for their own, and with the money they
have they probably succeeded.''
   Klein, a former paratrooper who once headed an elite anti-terror
squad, said he regretted getting involved in Colombia even though at
the time he believed he was only training farmers to defend their
cattle against marauding guerrillas.
   ``If I had known who these people were and where they ended up I
wouldn't have done it,'' said Klein.
   Also questioned was reserve Lt. Col. Amatzia Shueli, a former
commando who worked with Klein as a shooting instructor in Colombia.
   Police went to Klein's farmhouse after questioning him for nine
hours and confiscated documents, Israel Radio said.
   Klein and Shueli were asked to leave their passports with police,
it added.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Israel will fully investigate
the affair but added, ``I know our officers, and I cannot believe
that they have been involved in such crimes.''
   In Tel Aviv, Klein said he was no more guilty than other Israelis
who trained paramilitary groups in Latin America.
   ``If I did break the law, a lot of other people did,'' Klein said
on Army Radio as he walked into the criminal affairs division of the
Petah Tikva police station near Tel Aviv.
   Israeli sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, estimated
dozens of former officers were involved in training non-government
groups.
   Klein said on Sunday he would name high-ranking officers and a
member of Parliament who were involved in training paramilitary
forces in Latin America. He declined to identify them Monday.
   Yehoshua Saguy, a former chief of military intelligence and now a
parliament member of the right-wing Likud bloc, said on Israel radio
he visited Colombia in 1986 as a representative of an electronics
firm. He said he met with the defense minister but concluded no
deals.
   The newspaper Yediot Ahronot quoted former Maj. Gen. Rahamim
Zeevi as saying he visited Colombia several times on business, but
always had government authorization. Zeevi, who now represents the
Moledet Party in Parliament, once was Klein's commander.
   Klein said he and three other retired Israeli officers held two
three-week weapons courses for civilians starting in April 1988. He
said his Hod Hahanit (Spearhead) company trained groups of 30
farmers and ranchers to defend themselves from guerrillas.
   Hod Hahanit said Israeli Defense Ministry authorization was not
required because he was training civilians.
   Klein said the Colombian army initially encouraged his work, but
that he shut down and fled the country shortly after trying to set
up a third course.
   ``For the third course we saw something was going wrong,'' he
said. ``We were no longer getting ammunition from the army and
officers stopped visiting our training camp.''
   He said he was paid $20,000 a course and each instructor received
$2,000.
   Klein retired from the army in 1978 and founded Hod Hahanit in
1985 after operating a restaurant and then a gas station.
   ``There are officers like me who at the height of their abilities
leave the army and settle on a low-paying pension,'' Klein said.
``Out of frustration with the civilian market they go back to doing
what they do best.''
   Yediot Ahronot said two Israelis were arrested in Miami in June
for trying to ship weapons to Colombia intended to kill the leader
of the Medellin drug cartel.
   U.S. customs authorities identified one as David Candiotti, 27.
They said he reputedly worked for the rival Cali drug cartel and was
involved in a conspiracy to detonate an explosives-packed drone over
the hideout of Medellin cartel leader Pablo Escobar Gavaria.
   In Bogota, Colombian Defense Minister Gen. Oscar Botero Restrepo
said in a statement Monday that training there by Israeli
mercenaries was illegal.
   The Bogota newspaper El Tiempo quoted Klein as saying in an
interview that he ignored an Israeli Embassy warning that he may
have been training drug traffickers last year, believing he was
dealing with legitimate ranchers.
   The ranchers also hired mercenaries from South Africa, Zimbabwe,
Ireland and the United States, Klein was quoted as saying.
   Klein's training was reportedly done near Puerto Boyaca.
   Puerto Boyaca, 100 miles north of Bogota, is an area where drug
traffickers have steadily bought up land and where anyone resisting
their efforts has been murdered.
</TEXT>
