<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Riley     08-28 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Riley,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>8-Year-Old Cancer Victim Dies After Getting Wish To Join Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRMONT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old cancer victim who died three
days after realizing his dream of becoming a soldier was buried in
his camouflage fatigues Monday.
   Chris Riley, inducted into the Army as a ``special soldier'' by
recruiting officials, died Sunday night in the arms of his father,
Robert Riley, at his Fairmont home, said his aunt, Sherrie Cottrill.
   ``Even though they knew it was coming, it was still hard to
take,'' Cottrill said. ``We knew it wouldn't be too long, maybe two
weeks or three, the doctor couldn't tell us for sure.''
   The youth had undergone surgery twice since November 1986 for a
brain tumor. Chemotherapy was stopped last month after the cancer
spread to his spine, leaving him in pain and too weak to walk, said
his mother, Gail Riley.
   The staff of Army's Fairmont recruiting office organized
Thursday's induction after a family friend suggested a visit from a
couple of soldiers might cheer Chris.
   Army Capt. Duane Hawn and 1st Sgt. Gary Johnson prepared an
enlistment certificate and Chris was sworn in as a special soldier.
Members of the Pittsburgh Recruiting Battalion sent a four-man color
guard and a stuffed bear wearing a camouflage suit.
   Chris, wearing a camouflage uniform with a black military police
armband and RILEY stitched above his right pocket, was given a
10-minute ride aboard a National Guard self-propelled howitzer a
couple of blocks from his home in northern West Virginia.
   That afternoon, Chris, riding on a stretcher, was taken up on a
flight aboard an Army Reserve Huey helicopter.
   ``He loved it,'' Cottrill said. ``In fact, (Saturday) he wanted
to go and buy a G.I. Joe toy `right now.'''
   Following services at Domico Funeral Home here, Chris was buried
at nearby Shinnston Masonic Cemetery in the same camouflage fatigues
he wore Thursday.
</TEXT>
