<FIRST>u i AM-SalzburgFestival 1stLd-Writethru a0623 08-28 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salzburg Festival, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salzburg Festival Gets New Director</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to ADD background on festival reforms. ADDS byline.
No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerard Mortier, director of the Brussels
Opera, was named artistic director of the Salzburg Festival on
Monday with a mandate to revamp a cultural showcase some critics say
is elitist and conservative.
   His appointment follows the July 16 death of Herbert von Karajan,
the longtime guiding spirit and conductor of the festival who died
of a heart attack at age 81.
   The board of the festival announced that Mortier, 46, will take
over at Salzburg on Oct. 1, 1991. But starting next month he will
help plan festival events to be held after 1991, the Austria Press
Agency reported.
   In another appointment, the board named Hans Landesmann, a music
manager in Vienna, as the festival's economic director.
   ``The festival has become an old museum, unaware of what's going
on in the world. We should give modern music and drama the place
they deserve,'' Landesmann said in an interview.
   For years, critics said tickets to the Salzburg Festival cost too
much, and that proceedings were too much under the sway of Karajan.
   Austrian cultural politicians now are trying to open the
69-year-old festival to new forms of art and invite a greater
variety of musicians.
   Under a plan outlined in June, the unpaid, honorary five-man
board of the festival will be replaced by a permanent, salaried
three-member board.
   ``We need new, forward-thinking people in the management, much
more aware of the contemporary scene,'' said Landesmann, who is to
draw up a reform program.
   Landesmann said he would like to include artists on a new board
to advise on projects.
   He said he would also like to see film and video galas and
exhibits during the festival.
   While not playing down the merits of Italian traditional operas
here every year, Landesmann proposes to include other composers,
such as Richard Strauss and Alban Berg.
   There is also talk among festival organizers of devoting the
2,600-seat Great Festival Hall to foreign classical opera and the
Little Festival Hall to Mozart productions.
   ``We want a repertoire consistent with the line of Mozart's
heritage, something specific, typical of Salzburg,'' Landesmann said.
   In an attempt to prevent the rise of another domineering figure
such as Karajan, he said, no permanent conductor will be named.
Invitations will go out to well-known figures such as Sir Georg
Solti, Riccardo Muti and Claudio Abbado, all of whom are present
this summer.
   ``Karajan was opposed to reforms. He was an old man and he didn't
like changes. He was opposed to seeing new people,'' Landesmann said.
   Five years ago, government auditors had urged festival organizers
to spend less.
   Press chief Hans Widrich said the festival runs an annual budget
of $27 million. State subsidies total $7.7 million and the rest
comes from ticket sales, radio and television rights.
   Salzburg pays some of the highest performer fees in Europe and
charges nearly twice the top ticket prices of other European
festivals _ up to $250 for the best seat at the opera.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890828-0154 </DOCNO>
