<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BoxOffice     08-28 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Box Office,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Uncle Buck' Continues to Lead Box Office; `Wired' Dead on Arrival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The controversy surrounding ``Wired'' didn't
help it at the box office, as John Belushi's cinematic life story
opened to miserable weekend business while ``Uncle Buck'' again held
down the top spot.
   ``Uncle Buck,'' a comedy starring John Candy as an obnoxious
relative sent to babysit two nieces and a nephew, collected $6.7
million to lead the charts for the second week in a row, according
to figures released Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.
   It was followed in second by ``Parenthood,'' the bittersweet
chronicle of family life featuring Steve Martin and Jason Robards,
which netted $6.4 million. The $43 million underwater adventure film
``The Abyss'' finished in third with receipts of $4.7 million.
   ``Wired,'' an unusual parable of drug addiction showing the late
Belushi revisiting his life after escaping from a coroner's body
bag, grossed just $681,000 while playing on 680 screens.
   With such a stunningly low per-screen average, ``Wired'' is
certain to disappear from theaters quickly and it likely will debut
in home video stores soon. The movie drew steeply negative reviews
and had difficulty finding a distributor partly due to its subject
matter.
   In fourth place after ``The Abyss'' was the romantic comedy
``When Harry Met Sally...,'' with Billy Crystal and Meg Ryan as
friends who become lovers, on ticket sales of $4.1 million. ``Lethal
Weapon 2,'' starring Mel Gibson and Danny Glover, was in fifth with
$3.3 million.
   The drooling dog-cop buddy picture ``Turner and Hooch'' finished
in sixth with a gross of $3 million. ``Casualties of War,'' which
opened poorly last weekend, fell to seventh with a gate of $2.9
million.
   Still showing in the charts after 10 weeks of release, ``Batman''
landed in eighth by collecting $2.6 million. Rounding out the Top 10
were ``The Package,'' debuting in ninth with $1.9 million in limited
release, and ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids'' with $1.7 million in 10th.
   In other box-office news, ``Little Monsters'' and ``The
Adventures of Milo and Otis'' opened weakly while ``Cookie'' did
fair business its first week out.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
