<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0596 08-28 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0596,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>French, Soviet Envoys Hold Cease-fire Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Scheer meeting Assad. Pickup
4th pvs, ``Syrian-backed ...'' ^By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French and Soviet envoys held talks Monday
with Iraqi and Syrian officials amid renewed international efforts
to stop the bloodshed in Lebanon, where nearly 800 people have been
killed in five months.
   Francois Scheer, secretary-general of the French Foreign
Ministry, met for four hours with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa. Syrian soldiers are battling Christian troops in Lebanon.
   ``Any solution in Lebanon must be a political one and no
political solution in Lebanon is possible without an effective
Syrian contribution,'' Scheer said after the meeting.``The French
position on Lebanon has not changed and our action is absolutely an
action of peace.''
   Later, the Frenchman met with Syrian President Hafez Assad at his
summer residence in the Mediterranean port of Lattakis and gave him
a message from French President Francois Mitterrand.
   Assad asked Scheer to deliver a reply to the French president,
said a Syrian official who refused to give details.
   Syrian-backed Moslem groups accuse France of supporting Lebanese
Christians and have threatened retaliation if a French naval task
force in the eastern Mediterranean intervenes in Lebanon, which
France governed until 1943.
   France says the flotilla is on a ``humanitarian'' mission, to
evacuate the 7,000 French citizens in Lebanon if necessary.
   Scheer's visit was the second to the Middle East this week by a
French envoy seeking a lasting truce in the battle that began March
8 between the Christian army units of Gen. Michel Aoun and a Moslem
alliance led by Syria's 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon.
   At least 790 people have been killed and more than 2,000 wounded
in the fighting. All but 150,000 of Beirut's 1.5 million residents
have fled the city.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France announced Sunday that
Scheer will confer with a three-member Arab League committee trying
to implement a cease-fire and end the 14-year-old civil war.
   The committee members _ King Hassan II of Morocco, King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia and President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria _ agreed at
an Arab summit in May to try to arrange peace in Lebanon by November.
   Syrian soldiers arrived in Lebanon under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate in 1976, a year after the beginning of the
sectarian civil war in which at least 150,000 people have been
killed.
   Scheer said Monday: ``We also support other efforts, namely by
the Soviet Union, and we wish very much that the mission of the Arab
tripartite committee, which has our full support, resumes as quickly
as possible.''
   A three-step peace plan outlined by Dumas calls for a cease-fire,
no more arms deliveries to the warring factions, political reform in
Lebanon and withdrawal of Syrian and Israeli forces from the
country, with Syrian departure from Beirut as the first step.
   Israel maintains a south Lebanon ``security zone'' just north of
its border.
   Gennady Tarasov, head of the Middle East desk at the Soviet
Foreign Ministry, was in Baghdad on Monday to meet with Tariq Aziz,
the Iraqi foreign minister. Tarasov has visited Jordan, Syria and
Lebanon for consultations on how to end the fighting.
   Iraq, an enemy of Syria, has been the main arms supplier to Aoun.
Syria is the Soviet Union's main Arab ally, but the Kremlin also
maintains relations with Iraq.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Tarasov gave Aziz a letter
from President Mikhail S. Gorbachev for Iraq's president, Saddam
Hussein.
   Foreign ministers of the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council on
Monday began a two-day meeting in Jidda, Saudi Arabia, with an
appeal to all factions in Lebanon to help the Arab League peace
effort. Member nations are Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi
Arabia and The United Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
