<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Scandal 1stLd-Writethru a0641 08-28 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Interior Minister Faces 20-year Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th pvs, `Castro fired...' to CORRECT that 10 sted eight
officials serving prison terms; Pickup 8th, `Prosecutors said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former interior minister may get 20 years
in the Cuban drug and corruption scandal and six ministry officials
face prison terms ranging up to 15 years, Fidel Castro's government
said Monday.
   Prosecutors requested the sentences Sunday after four days of
testimony to a military tribunal, the official Cuban news agency
Prensa Latina reported from Havana. It did not say when verdicts and
sentences were expected.
   Ministry officials for whom prosecutors asked sentences of 8 to
15 years include the former vice interior minister and the former
head of customs, the agency said.
   Gen. Jose Abrantes Fernandez, the former interior minister, and
his co-defendants were accused of using their posts to enrich
themselves.
   Prensa Latina said prosecutors asked that Abrantes and at least
four other defendants be reduced in rank to private and that all
their illegal gains be confiscated. It quoted a report Monday in
Granma, the official newspaper of the Cuban Communist Party.
   The trial is the latest chapter in a scandal that has resulted in
the executions of four officers, including a highly decorated
general who had been with Castro since guerrilla days more than 30
years ago.
   Castro fired Abrantes as interior minister in June, when 12
military officers from the ministry and two from the army were
charged with drug smuggling and other crimes. All were convicted and
the 10 not executed are serving prison terms of up to 30 years.
   Prosecutors said Abrantes fumbled the drug-smuggling
investigation so badly that his mistakes appeared deliberate, but
that the evidence did not support a charge of treason, Prensa Latina
reported.
   Abrantes knew as early as February that officials of his ministry
were involved in drug trafficking but did nothing about it, the
prosecution said.
   According to Prensa Latina, Castro personally ordered Abrantes to
investigate after persistent reports that tons of Colombian cocaine
and Jamaican marijuana were moving through Cuba to the United States.
   Abrantes was charged with abusing power, neglecting his duties
and stealing from the government, the agency said.
   It said prosecutors asked the tribunal to send the former vice
interior minister, Gen. Pascual Martinez Gil, to prison for 15 years
and requested a 13-year term for Lt. Col. Oscar Carreno Gomez, the
former customs chief.
   Abrantes, Carreno Gomez and four others are accused of taking
money from some of the officers arrested in June. Prensa Latina said
Abrantes allegedly accumulated millions of dollars in an illegal
fund.
   The prosecution said Abrantes had a long, close relationship with
Col. Antonio de la Guardia, one of the officers executed. In
addition to drug charges, those arrested in June were accused of
crimes ranging from diamond smuggling to black marketeering.
   Prensa Latina said Abrantes was accused of various illegal
financial dealings and diverting ministry funds and resources to
personal use.
   Felipe Aleman Cruz, the chief prosecutor, said Abrantes was so
consumed with ``dollar fever'' that he traded in Cuban pesos on the
black market for his own profit.
   Cuban media have given the corruption scandal an unusual amount
of coverage and Prensa Latina has sent dispatches around the world.
</TEXT>
