<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Contra     08-28 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Contra,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Director Returns; Says Armed Struggle Still An Option</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra rebel director returned from
six years' exile Monday saying he will join the political fight
against the leftist Sandinista government, but that armed struggle
remains an option.
   Roberto Ferrey is the second member of the Contra leadership to
return to Nicaragua in recent months. On arrival, he had to sign a
document saying he renounced armed struggle,
   ``I'm here to incorporate myself into the electoral process,''
Ferrey said, referring to general elections scheduled Feb. 25, 1990.
   Asked if this means he has given up armed struggle to fight the
government, Ferrey said: ``If the changes don't come about, it
(armed struggle) could still be an option.''
   President Daniel Ortega's government has signed regional accords
committing itself to democratic changes.
   In the latest accord, signed Aug. 7, the presidents of Nicaragua,
Honduras, El Salvador, Costa Rica and Guatemala agreed to dismantle
the Nicaraguan rebel force known as the Contras starting Sept. 5.
   The process, under the supervision of observers from the United
Nations and the Organization of American States, should be completed
Dec. 6.
   Most Contras, an estimated 10,000 with another 10,000 family
members, have been living in Honduras since their leaders and the
Sandinistas signed a temporary cease-fire in March 1988.
   Ferrey said ``there is no need to resign'' from the directorate
of the Miami-based Nicaraguan Resistance, an umbrella organization
of anti-Sandinista groups in exile.
   He arrived aboard a private flight from Guatemala City provided
by Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo.
   Alfredo Cesar was the first directorate member to return to
Nicaragua. he came home on June 11 and joined his old party, the
Social Democrats, but still has not said whether he has resigned
from the directorate.
</TEXT>
