<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Carnival     08-28 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Carnival,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Officers Hurt in Clashes at Notting Hill Carnival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said nine officers were hurt in
bottle-throwing clashes Monday night at Notting Hill Carnival,
marring an otherwise peaceful Carribbean celebration in which crime
was sharply down from previous years.
   Police reported 47 crimes in the Sunday and Monday event,
compared with 85 last year.
   But as the carnival drew to a close, some police were hit by
bottles and officers moved in to clear streets.
   ``A number of arrests have been made and there have been a few
minor injuries to the police,'' a police spokesman said.
   Deputy Assistant Commissioner Charles Rideout of Scotland Yard
later said nine officers were hurt, and the violence had spread to
other streets.
   ``This is a most unfortunate incident ... on a day we thought was
going to be one of the best carnival days ever,'' he said.
   Police estimated 300,000 people were on the streets of the
Notting Hill area of west London on Monday. On Sunday there were
200,000, about 15 to 20 percent fewer than in past years, they said.
   About 1,000 officers patrolled the carnival and 4,000 more were
on call, Rideout said.
   The carnival, held on the August bank holiday weekend, features
parades, colorful costumes, street performers and a jubilant
Afro-Caribbean atmosphere that has become a cultural focal point for
London's black community.
   Riots, muggings and other violence, including a fatal 1987
stabbing, have marred past carnivals _ billed as Europe's largest
street festival _ and led to calls for it to be banned.
   A new Carnival Enterprise Committee was formed this year to
organize the 24th annual event and to put the emphasis back on
traditional parades, dances and ethnic food stands.
</TEXT>
