<FIRST>r a AM-BangladeshiGirl 1stLd-Writethru a0597 08-28 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladeshi Girl, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede ABERDEEN, Wash.</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Agrees to Fight Deportation of Molested Bangladeshi Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with state saying it will fight deportation,
but girl cannot stay with foster parents, rally at capitol, other details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials Monday agreed to fight
deportation of a 9-year-old Bangladeshi girl who was molested by the
man who brought her to America, then taken from a foster home
because it wasn't ``culturally relevant.''
   Earlier, the girl's foster parents and more than 200 supporters
fighting her removal and possible deportation marched on the state
capitol, chanting and waving banners demanding help for the
youngster they call ``Kushi Bear.''
   The girl is one of several members of a Bangladeshi family that
Stefan Christopher, 52, brought to this country. A U.N. consultant,
he had married one of the girl's older sisters, separated from her
and married another sister, age 12. Over the years he brought family
members to work on his Oakville farm.
   Christopher is in jail awaiting sentencing Sept. 5 after pleading
guilty to taking indecent liberties with the girl and two other
children. Sheriff's department officials said he subjected them to
``physical and psychological torture.''
   After Monday's rally, the state Child Protective Services said it
would review the case and fight deportation. Spokeswoman Irene
Hopman said an education visa would be sought for Kushi, allowing
her to remain in the United States indefinitely.
   But Ms. Hopman insisted that the child could not remain with her
foster parents, chemical engineer Bob Martin and his wife, Betsy
Seidel, an English teacher.
   ``She is not adoptable. She had been raised a Moslem. That is her
family's religion,'' Ms. Hopman said. ``The girl's birth parents
want her educated and raised in the United States but their sect
does not believe in adoption and they have not relinquished their
rights.''
   Martin and Seidel wept when they were surrounded by supporters
after hearing the news. They had feared the state would allow Kushi
to be sent back to Bangladesh where she would be outcast because of
the sexual abuse.
   ``Kushi has a magic that touches everyone,'' Martin told the
rally. ``Betsy and I did everything we could within the system but
it wasn't enough. Removing Kushi was wrong, just wrong.''
   CPS workers took Khurshida ``Kushi'' Begum from the Martin-Seidel
home at Hoquiam near the Pacific Ocean last Friday, declaring it
wasn't ``culturally relevant.''
   The girl has been placed temporarily with her 19-year-old sister
Morshida here, whose marriage gave Kushi entry to the United States.
The girl faces deportation when her visa expires Sept. 5.
   If the placement with her sister doesn't work out, three Moslem
families have volunteered their homes, Ms. Hopman said.
   Morshida, mother of two children, has filed for divorce from
Christopher, 52, whom she married when she was 12.
   Supporters say if the child were returned to her remote village
she would face life as a social outcast because of her sexual abuse.
   Shah Asadullah, a Bangladeshi psychiatrist with Group Health
Medical Center in Seattle, wrote in a letter to CPS that if she is
deported she ``is likely to become completely outcast and walk the
streets to survive.''
   ``I am shocked by the sudden removal of the child,'' said lawyer
Janet Watson, who represents Martin and Seidel in their effort to
adopt the girl. ``I've never heard of a child being removed by the
state from an excellent home against the wishes of the child.''
   The girl said, ``I want to live with them, because they love me
and they're nice.''
   A 16-year-old cousin of Kushi's committed suicide last year after
being abused, leading to the sheriff's investigation and removal of
the children, the sheriff's office said.
   State officials said they have been unable to directly contact
the illiterate parents in Bangladesh. Three letters have not been
answered, said Ms. Hopman.
   She said efforts to reach them will be stepped up, and that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service will be asked to provide an
education visa, which would allow her to remain in the United States
until her education is completed.
   But Kushi's brother, Sultan, 21, who lives in Seattle, said in an
interview that Kushi's parents don't mind if their daughter stays
with Martin and Seidel.
   ``I write them and they say it's O.K. They don't know about this
adoption. This country is very hard. My parents can't understand,''
he said.
   ``They said it's OK if she happy. If she goes to school. They
poor. They don't have nothing. That's why it's OK.''
</TEXT>
