<DOCNO> AP890828-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HelicopterCrash     08-28 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed After Scuffle With Wounded Fugitive Aboard Medical Helicopter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wounded Canadian fugitive being airlifted
by a medical helicopter apparently tried to commandeer the aircraft
in flight, causing it to crash and killing him and the three-member
crew, authorities said Monday.
   The bodies of Robert L. Adams, 25, and the crew of the Heartflite
helicopter were found Monday on Larch Mountain 25 miles northeast of
Spokane, said Kootenai County sheriff's Sgt. Kenneth Sopher.
   The crew _ the pilot, a registered nurse and a respiratory
therapist _ reported that Adams was scuffling with them before the
Aerospatiale Astar from Sacred Heart Medical Center here crashed
around 10 p.m. Sunday.
   Adams apparently tried to enter the United States illegally near
a U.S. Customs station in Eastport, Idaho, on Sunday night, the
Boundary County Sheriff's Department said in a news release.
   The Bridgefield, Nova Scotia, man was wanted in Canada for
investigation of escape, sexual assault and auto theft charges.
   During a search of a vehicle at the Customs station, a man pulled
a weapon and disarmed Director Joe Hancock, agency spokeswoman
Cherise Miles said in Chicago. The man then fled south on U.S. 25.
The vehicle had been stolen.
   Adams forced his way into the nearby home of Bob McGlocklin, 71,
and briefly held the man hostage, the sheriff's department said. The
two men were wounded in an exchange of gunfire, but the sequence of
events was unclear.
   Two Heartflite helicopters were dispatched to Bonners Ferry,
Idaho, about 20 miles south of Eastport to pick up Adams and
McGlocklin.
   One picked up McGlocklin and returned to Spokane. The second
aircraft left Bonners Ferry at 9:26 p.m., and made a routine patient
report 30 minutes later, but was not heard from again, said Sacred
Heart spokeswoman Marilyn Thordarson.
   Bob Zinkgraf, who was listening with his wife to a radio scanner
at his Colbert, Wash., home 15 miles north of Spokane, said the crew
``reported they were having problems with the suspect.''
   ``A couple of minutes later, they reported they were in a scuffle
with the suspect. Then we heard the hospital trying to get in touch
with them. They reported they lost contact with the helicopter''
about 10 p.m., Zinkgraf said.
   Ms. Thordarson said the last report made no mention of any
difficulty, and that only static and background noises were heard
afterwards.
   The crash is being investigated as a crime rather than as an
accident, said air safety inspector Pete Mangum of the National
Transportation Safety Board's Seattle office.
   The spokeswoman identified the dead as pilot Pat Varaya, age
unknown, registered nurse Lyn Gould, 31, and respiratory therapist
Bob Siekerman, 36, all from the Spokane area.
   McGlocklin was in satisfactory condition at Sacred Heart with
gunshot wounds to his right arm and back, Ms. Thordarson said.
   The Bonner County Sheriff's office is investigating the accident,
as well as the Federal Aviation Administration, and the FBI has been
asked to join the probe, officials said.
</TEXT>
