<FIRST>r w AM-Avanti-AirBags 1stLd-Writethru a0640 08-28 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avanti-Air Bags, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avanti Convertibles Exempted From Passive Restraint Requirement</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adds 3 grafs comment from Nader group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avanti Automotive Corp. won a two-year reprieve
Monday from having to install air bags or motorized seat belts in
its convertibles.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said it
granted an exemption from passive restraint requirements because
complying would cause ``substantial economic hardship'' for the
struggling car company.
   Avanti's passive restraint exemption is the only one granted for
1990 model-year cars, NHTSA spokesman Tim Hurd said.
   The company's hard-top models still must comply with the passive
restraint requirement.
   In seeking the exemption, Avanti noted its importance to
Youngstown, Ohio, a once-thriving steel center now racked with high
unemployment.
   ``Avanti affords job opportunities to an economically depressed
area, its payroll approximately $250,000 a month. Other jobs have
been created by suppliers to Avanti,'' said the notice published in
the Federal Register.
   The company, which employs about 190 workers, was given $8
million worth of incentives to bring its plant to Youngstown.
   Avanti said it lost $2 million between June 1, 1988, and Nov. 30,
1988, the most recent financial statements made available to NHTSA.
   The company, which intends to produce about 200 convertibles a
year, had asked for a three-year exemption.
   NHTSA said it would consider extending the exemption, if
necessary, but wanted to take into account whether the company
follows through with interim plans to make a combination roll
bar-automatic seat belt, to be sold as optional equipment for the
convertibles, which sell for a base price of $47,982.
   ``It's just one of those decisions that is so dumb it speaks for
itself,'' said Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto
Safety. ``We feel that air bags are such an important life-saving
technology that there shouldn't be any exemptions from the
standard.''
   Ditlow, of the non-profit organization founded by consumer
advocate Ralph Nader, said the company should have been required to
buy air bag technology from another manufacturer.
   ``Avanti has known for five years now _ six years actually _ that
they have to meet the standard,'' he said. ``Consumers shouldn't buy
the car. There are other convertibles out there with air bags.''
</TEXT>
