<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LoveCanal     08-28 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Love Canal,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Eliminates Occidental Defense in Love Canal Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has eliminated one of
Occidental Chemical Corp.'s main defenses in a lawsuit over
liability for cleaning up the infamous Love Canal toxic dump,
according to a decision made public Monday.
   U.S. District Judge John Curtin, ruling in a lawsuit filed by the
state, rejected Occidental's claim that the company had relinquished
liability when it sold the Love Canal land to the Niagara Falls
school board.
   Occidental, owner of the former Hooker Chemical and Plastic Co.
that used Love Canal as a waste dump, contended it wasn't
responsible for the site after 1953, when it sold the land on which
a school was subsequently built.
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams said the ruling was ``a
great victory for the state.''
   ``It lays to rest Occidental's principal defense that selling the
landfill to a school district relieved the company of its
responsibility for the harmful health effects caused by Occidental's
dumping on the land,'' he said.
   Occidental actually ``palmed off what it knew to be an enormous
toxic waste site for $1,'' the attorney general said.
   Curtin, in a judgment dated Friday, also extended Occidental's
liability for the cost of cleaning up Love Canal to include
liability under the state's nuisance law. Last year, Curtin said the
company was liable under the federal Superfund law.
   Some estimates on the cost of cleaning up Love Canal, where
Occidental acknowledges that 20,000 tons of chemical wastes were
dumped in the 1940s and 1950s, exceed $250 million.
   New York state is one of several parties, including the federal
government and former area residents, suing Occidental over Love
Canal.
   ``We just received the court's decision late this afternoon and
have not yet had the chance to review it,'' said Occidental
spokesman John Stuart. ``However, given the court's previous summary
judgment ruling against Occidental in February 1988 on the question
of liability under Superfund, this decision is not completely
unexpected.''
   In 1978, Love Canal became synonymous with environmental disaster
when state officials ordered an evaculation of children and pregnant
women from the area because of leaking chemicals.
   President Carter designated the 10-block site as a federal
emergency area in 1978, and the federal Environmental Protection
Agency began a lawsuit against the company the following year.
   Other issues involving Occidental's liability and damages will
probably be the subject of future trials. Curtin has deliberated the
case for 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
