<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     08-28 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Die In Charter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private charter plane missed a runway and
crashed in a field while attempting an instrument landing in thick
fog early Monday, killing all five people on board.
   Three airplane mechanics for USAir Express-Henson Aviation Inc.
had chartered the Bayland Aviation flight from Salisbury, Md., to
Lynchburg where they planned to work on a passenger jet that was
having mechanical problems, USAir spokeswoman Susan Young said.
   The Piper 31 missed the runway by a quarter-mile and sheared
through trees in a wooded area before crashing in a corn field, said
police Cmdr. S.K. Newby.
   ``It was torn all to pieces,'' Newby said of the plane.
   The National Weather Service said the area was enshrouded in
patchy fog at the time, but it was unclear whether the fog
contributed to the crash.
   ``The plane was trying to attempt a visual approach and broke off
the approach,'' Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Fred
Farrar said. ``They then requested an instrument landing system
approach to the airport.''
   Bayland Aviation manager Dave Bush said National Transportation
Safety Board investigators would attempt to determine the cause of
the crash.
   The victims were identified as pilot Kenneth Forbes, 30, of
Salisbury; co-pilot William Bowen, 36, of Snow Hill, Md.; and
mechanics Dean A. Witmer, 35, Patrick G. Aragon, 32, and William J.
Neuman, 24, all of Salisbury.
   Forbes had been with Bayland for five years and had been flying
for the past year and a half, Bush said.
</TEXT>
