<FIRST>r a AM-Bus-TruckCrash     08-28 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus-Truck Crash,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Accordions into Rear of Truck; More than 40 Hurt, 10 Seriously</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greyhound bus heading cross-country
crashed into the rear of an equipment-laden truck on Interstate 10,
injuring all 44 aboard the bus and the truck's owner, at least 10
seriously, authorities said Monday.
   Several feet of the front of the bus ``just accordioned
backwards'' after the accident late Sunday night on a steep stretch
about four miles west of Benson, said Dr. Michael Gray, chief of
staff at Benson Hospital.
   ``I was awakened by a huge bang,'' said George Duran, 25, on his
way home to San Diego. ``People were just lying everywhere,
screaming and yelling. There was blood everywhere.''
   A paramedic said it took rescuers nearly an hour to free the
driver and two women from the crushed front of the bus.
   All passengers as well as the drivers of both vehicles were
evacuated by helicopter and ambulance to hospitals in Benson or
Tucson, authorities said.
   Many of the passengers had to be rescued through windows of the
bus, which lacks a rear emergency exit door, officials said.
   The bus was traveling at 60 to 65 mph when it plowed into a
18-wheel flatbed semi-trailer hauling large metal containers at
11:25 p.m., said Richard Pittman, a spokesman for the state
Department of Public Safety. The trucking rig was climbing uphill at
about 25 miles an hour toward Tucson.
   Among the hospitalized were Margo Romero, 21, of Houston, five or
six months pregnant, and her four small children, including a
2{-year-old son, Bill, who was in critical condition after surgery
for a skull fracture.
   Also hospitalized were Jerry Henson, 49, of Phoenix, the bus
driver, who suffered an amputated leg, and Maria Turrubiartes, 40,
of Santa Paula, Calif.
   DPS dispatcher Jerry Stiles said the bus had skidded about 250
feet, indicating Henson had tried to brake before the collision.
   Bruce Whitehouse, fire chief and paramedic of the small Corona de
Tucson fire department, said ``it was a gory scene'' as he arrived.
   ``People were yelling, `Help me! Help me!' A woman told me she
saw her baby go under four rows of seats,'' he said.
   Pittman said both drivers had been within legal limits and added
that the bus driver should have had about a three-fourths of a mile
line of sight of the truck ahead.
   But Pittman said investigators were waiting to talk to Henson to
determine whether he had attempted to change lanes before the
accident.
   He said it was unclear whether lights on the trailer had been in
operation, as required by law.
   The truck's driver, Ricky Middleton, 27, of Houston, told DPS
investigators he was making his first cross-country run at the time.
Investigators were checking to make certain that Middleton was
qualified to be driving the rig, Pittman said.
   Middleton was unhurt, but his father, James Middleton, 58, of
Houston, was listed in guarded condition at Tucson Medical Center.
The elder Middleton was thrown from the truck.
   Two military helicopters shuttled the most seriously injured
passengers from Benson Hospital or directly from the crash site to
trauma centers at Tucson Medical Center and University Medical
Center in Tucson.
   George Gravley, a spokesman for Greyhound Lines Inc. of Dallas,
said there were nine children under 12 among the 43 bus passengers.
Greyhound spokeswoman Liz Hale, also in Dallas, said the driver had
24 years of commercial driving experience, including 22 with buses.
   Gravley said the bus was on a transcontinental run from New York
to Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
