<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RunawayTrain     08-28 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Runaway Train,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Hearing Opens in Train, Pipeline Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A runaway train that careened off
its tracks into a row of houses, killing four people, was going
faster and had less braking capacity and more weight than indicated
in preliminary reports, federal officials said Monday.
   The derailment and a deadly explosion of an underground pipeline
that occurred 13 days later in the crash area are the subject of a
five-day National Transportation Safety Board inquiry. The hearing
began Monday.
   In addition to focusing on the train's mechanics, the hearing is
addressing the crew's response to the emergency. Local efforts to
determine the pipeline's safety after the derailment also were
examined.
   The Southern Pacific freight train, with 69 cars and six
locomotives, was traveling between 105 mph and 110 mph when it
derailed May 12, William Pugh, the NTSB investigator in charge, told
the hearing.
   Initial estimates of a train speed of 90 mph as it swooped down
from a mountain pass were discarded after a computer analysis of the
accident, said board chairman Lee Dickenson.
   The train crested the summit of Cajon Pass at 30 mph with
engineer Frank Holland believing the loaded train weighed 6,151 tons
and had full braking capability on at least four locomotives,
according to testimony by Holland and Pugh.
   But the accident investigation has found the weight of the train
was about 8,900 tons, and that possibly only two of the locomotive
had ``dynamic braking'' capability _ which Dickenson described as
akin to downshifting on a car to help slow it.
   The train could have been halted if it was at the weight Holland
used in his calculations, Dickenson said during a hearing break.
   Pugh said the weight for the cars, which were loaded with a
mineral called trona, had not been provided by the shipper, Lakes
Minerals Corp. In order to satisfy a computer requirement for
preparation of the weigh bills, the weight was estimated, he said.
   A routine test had indicated braking problems with one locomotive
and intermittent problems with another, Holland said. Two helper
locomotives were added to the train at Oban, before the Cajon Pass,
at Holland's request.
   But the engineer said he was not informed that one of the helper
units also lacked dynamic braking capability.
   The board also heard from witnesses to the May 25 gas explosion
that killed two people and injured 30 in a San Bernardino
neighborhood. A total of 17 homes were destroyed in the derailment
and explosion.
   James Knight, deputy chief of the San Bernardino Fire Department,
told the NTSB panel that he spoke with a representative of the
Calnev Pipe Line Co. after the train wreck, and recommended that the
entire line be unearthed and examined for possible damage. He also
recommended that the gas inside be removed, if possible, and
replaced with water.
   The line supplies 90 percent of Las Vegas' gas and nearly all the
jet fuel to George and Edwards air force bases.
   ``They said they planned to uncover the pipeline,'' Knight said.
   ``Did they?'' he was asked.
   ``No.''
   Knight, who said that Calnev had uncovered and examined only
three areas of the pipeline, added that he did not have the
jurisdiction to influence the company's actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890828-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Auschwitz-Furor     08-28 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz-Furor,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Newspaper, Leading Jews Attack Cardinal Glemp on Auschwitz
Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American Jewish leaders and a mass circulation British newspaper
assailed Cardinal Jozef Glemp of Poland on Monday for his weekend
remarks on the furor over a convent at Auschwitz death camp, calling
his comments anti-Semitic.
   The Daily Mirror paper said in an editorial that the Roman
Catholic prelate's stand must have had the backing of Pope John Paul
II.
   ``The cardinal has tapped into the deep vein of anti-Semitism
which has existed in his country for a thousand years. He would not
have done so without the knowledge of the pope, himself a Pole,'' it
said.
   Kalman Sultanik, vice president of the World Jewish Congress,
said in New York on Monday, ``Cardinal Glemp's grotesque and
hate-filled remarks have been strongly condemned by Solidarity and
revealed that an ugly vein of anti-Semitism runs through the Polish
church.''
   Glemp suggested in an address on Saturday to pilgrims at Jasna
Gora Monastery in Czestochowa, Poland, that Jews were being
anti-Polish in objecting to the existence of a Carmelite convent at
Auschwitz, site of a Nazi German death camp set up in Poland mainly
to exterminate Jews.
   He asked Jews worldwide to halt their objections, saying, ``If
there would be no `anti-Polonism,' there will be no anti-Semitism in
our country.''
   Glemp was responding to international criticism of the abrogation
by the church on Aug. 10 of a 1987 pledge to move the convent from
the camp perimeter. Many Jewish groups consider the convent an
intrusion at the site.
   A. James Rudin, chairman of interreligious affairs of the
American Jewish Committee, said in New York on Monday, ``We're in a
spiritual gridlock and the kind of rhetoric of Cardinal Glemp
doesn't help. He seems to be reviving some of the anti-Jewish
canards of the past.''
   Rudin said Glemp's comment ``raises the anger of many people and
feeds into the anti-Jewish stereotypes of some Polish people that we
thought we had overcome. I hope that won't be the final word from
Cardinal Glemp.''
   Rabbi Avi Weiss of the Riverdale section of New York City, one of
seven Jews who demonstrated on July 14 at the convent at Auschwitz,
said Glemp was quoted as saying, ``A squad of seven New York Jews
launched an attack against the convent, but did not kill the nuns or
destroy the convent only because they were stopped.''
   Weiss said Monday in New York, ``Glemp's statement is as close to
a blood libel as one can come. We're calling upon the Vatican to
discipline Cardinal Glemp.''
   The seven demonstrators were roughly dragged away by workmen at
the camp.
   Weiss said that Jacek Kuron, a leader of the Solidarity union in
Poland, told him, ``I feel very much ashamed as a Pole for what
happened to you.''
   The Daily Mirror said in its editorial: ``The butchers were
German Nazis and their renegade allies, but when Cardinal Glemp
spoke warmly of the improving relations with Poland's old enemies,
Germany and Russia, he used dangerously inflammatory language
against the Jews.
   ``He tried to justify his own shameless bad faith in tearing up a
solemn agreement that a Carmelite convent would be removed from
Auschwitz, a place which the Holocaust made holy to Jews.
   ``The Polish Catholic Church had given its word that the nuns
would be moved by last February. Cardinal Glemp broke it without a
qualm. And now that the Jews insist that he keeps the promise, he
accuses them of violating Poland's sovereignty.
   ``In the name of God, what does he hope to gain by fanning the
embers of hate?''
</TEXT>
