<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Anti-Semitism     08-28 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Anti-Semitism,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Complains of Increased Attacks on Jews Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auschwitz-Furor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel spoke on Monday of a growing wave of
anti-Semitic attacks abroad and urged foreign governments to fight
the trend as ``a shameful and disgusting phenomenon.''
   Cabinet Secretary Eliakim Rubinstein told foreign reporters at a
news conference the government was closely monitoring the attacks
and deeply concerned about them.
   Israel was founded as a Jewish homeland after the Nazi Holocaust
killed 6 million Jews.
   An official from the World Zionist Organization's Information
Department, Yochanan Manor, gave figues showing assaults motivated
by anti-Semitism on Jews rose worldwide from fewer than 200 annually
in the 1960s to more than 2,000 a year at the close of the 1980s.
   More than half the current attacks occur in the United States,
Manor said.
   In the last two years, arson attacks against Jewish targets and
attacks on synagogues in the United States and Europe doubled, he
said.
   Manor said most incidents involved anti-Jewish slogans or
swastikas painted on walls and arson attacks on synagogues.
   Rubinstein said he believed anti-Semitic attacks were increasing
because people were less aware of the repercussions of anti-Semitism
more than 40 years after the Holocaust.
   ``Anti-Semitism must be treated as a shameful and disgusting
phenomenon that has no place among civilized people and enlightened
countries,'' Rubinstein said.
   He noted the possible influence of the 20-month-old Palestinian
uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied territories, which has
marred Israel's image.
   ``The intefadeh,'' Rubinstein said, using the Arabic word for
uprising, ``may have been used as an excuse for serving as a basis
of anti-Israeli phenomena.''
</TEXT>
