<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 3rdLd-Writethru a0691 08-28 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0691,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Announces Arrest Of Drug Trade Financial Wizard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with drug store chain impounded;
Minor editing; Picks up 14th pvs, `The drug...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said Monday that it arrested a
financial wizard of the drug trade who is wanted in the United
States. He was seized at a ranch near Medellin along with 4.5 metric
tons of cocaine, it said.
   In an international appeal broadcast Monday, President Virgilio
Barco said survival of this South American nation of 30 million
people is at stake in the drug war.
   He said the war does not stop at Colombia's borders, and that
cocaine-users everywhere ``have created the largest, most vicious
criminal enterprise the world has ever known.''
   Also Monday, the U.S. ambassador in Bogota, Thomas McNamara, met
with the foreign minister, Julio Londono Paredes. No details of
their 20-minute meeting were immediately available.
   A Defense Ministry communique said the army kept up its pressure
on traffickers Monday, seizing 8.2 metric tons of marijuana in two
raids in the Caribbean coastal city of Barranquilla.
   The army's 11th Brigade in Medellin said in a communique that
Abraham Majuat _ identified as a top financial man for drug dealers
_ was detained last week. It said soldiers also found 4.5 metric
tons of cocaine, or about 9,120 pounds at the ranch.
   The communique said Majuat was wanted in the United States on
drug-related charges but gave no further details. The U.S. Embassy
in Colombia would not confirm or deny the army report.
   Medellin is hometown for the world's biggest drug organization
that reportedly is responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine sent by
air, sea and land to the United States.
   In Washington, Monica de Greiff, Colombia's justice minister who
has led a crackdown on cocaine barons, met with U.S. officials.
Barco's office denied reports she had resigned in fear of being
killed.
   Nationwide raids and dragnets began after the assassination on
Aug. 18 of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, an outspoken foe of the drug
trade and Colombia's leading presidential candidate.
   Police and soldiers have arrested more than 11,000 people and
seized hundreds of millions of dollars in property.
   The radio network Caracol reported on Monday officials impounded
17 branches of a drug store chain in Cordoba state allegedly
belonging to a top drug trafficker.
   Colombia has said drug traffickers wanted in the United States
would be extradited.
   Among those detained was Eduardo Martinez Romero, a reputed
finance manager for the Medellin cartel. He is wanted in the United
States in connection with a $1.2 billion money-laundering operation.
   Monday's meeting between U.S. envoy McNamara and Paredes was
thought to center on Martinez's extradition.
   Washington has pledged $65 million worth of helicopters and other
help.
   The drug traffickers have declared war on the government. They
have burned houses and set off bombs because of the crackdown, but
no new acts of terrorism were reported Monday.
   About 100 national policemen are being sent to Medellin, where
cocaine dealers bombed nine banks Sunday, that city's mayor said.
   Mayor Juan Gomez Martinez said in a statement Monday that 4,000
national police already were stationed in his northwestern city of 2
million, and ``we are going through a really difficult situation.''
   In his broadcast, Barco called Galan ``the latest of thousands of
Colombian martyrs who have given their lives in the fight against
drugs.''
   ``We may have borne the brunt of the violence, but it does not
stop at our borders.
   ``Those of you who depend on cocaine have created the largest,
most vicious criminal enterprise the world has ever known. What
might seem to be a matter of personal habit ... has thrown us all
into a war we did not ask for. Colombia's survival as the oldest
democracy in Latin America is now at risk, but so is the safety of
your streets.''
   Mrs. de Greiff was in Washington Monday in an official capacity
and conferring with U.S. officials.
   She met with Attorney General Dick Thornburgh about the anti-drug
war, arriving in an unmarked official car that drove into the
Justice Department's underground parking garage.
   The news agency Colprensa said Mrs de Greiff flew to Washington
on Thursday after a plan was uncovered to kill her.
   Bogota newspapers have published stories for days saying Mrs. de
Greiff, 32, would resign because of threats against her, her husband
and their 3-year-old child. She has been in the job less than two
months.
   A spokesman for Barco, Gabriel Gutierrez, told The Associated
Press that as of Monday afternoon Mrs. de Greiff had not resigned.
   Rumors of her resignation circulated after she said in a TV
interview last week: ``I wasn't prepared to work in times of war,
such as now.''
   Rodrigo Lara Bonilla, a predecessor of Mrs. de Greiff, was killed
by drug cartel assassins in 1984.
   Last week, the traffickers said they would kill 10 jurists for
every one of their number extradited.
</TEXT>
