<FIRST>r a AM-IndianCasinoBurned     08-28 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Casino Burned,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Gamblers Burn Down Casino on Indian Reservation, Witnesses Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOGANSBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob of angry anti-gamblers burned down
a casino scheduled to open on the St. Regis Mohawk Reservation,
Indian residents said Monday.
   The Lucky Knight casino was heavily damaged in the Sunday night
fire, which followed a confrontation between a group of Mohawks
opposed to the gambling parlors and a self-appointed reservation
security force.
   The confrontation also triggered a brief standoff between state
police and the security force, called the Warriors Society, on the
reservation straddling the U.S.-Canadian border in northern New York.
   Reservation residents said a group of gambling opponents came
together as a vigilante mob that burned the casino, which was
scheduled to open Tuesday and featured slot machines, craps tables
and other games.
   ``It was torched right there,'' said Alex Jacobs, a reporter and
program director for CKON-Radio, a public radio station.
   Franklin County fire investigators said Monday that arson is
suspected, but the blaze remains under investigation.
   Casino owner Victoria Adams said she had just left the building
when the mob stormed it and set the fire with Molotov cocktails. She
said the mob tried to burn other casinos on the reservation but were
fended off by armed guards.
   State police said the conflict involved ``upwards of 500''
people. The incident lasted about six hours.
   While state troopers set up roadblocks to reroute traffic around
the reservation, Warriors Society members, expecting state police to
intervene, set up their own armed checkpoints just inside the
reservation.
   After several tense hours, both sides relinquished their
respective strongholds along the perimeter of the reservation, which
was the site of a 10-day standoff between troopers and the warriors
after a gambling raid July 20 by state and federal authorities.
   Gambling is illegal in New York, and state officials have
contested the tribe's right to operate casinos. The Mohawks contend
they are not bound by state or federal gambling laws since they
consider their reservation a sovereign nation.
   Pro-gambling Mohawks voted this month to permit gambling on the
reservation, but anti-gambling Indians claim the vote was invalid.
   State police and tribal leaders reached an agreement this month
to resume patrols on the reservation, but the Warriors Society has
said they would allow troopers on their land only with advance
notice and escorts.
</TEXT>
