<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Tourism     08-28 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Tourism,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number of Foreign Visitors to China Plunges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of foreigners visiting China dropped
almost 50 percent in July, and tourism nearly dried up in the month
after the military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement,
according to the state tourism agency.
   The official China Daily on Tuesday quoted a State Tourism
Administration report as saying 80,000 foreign nationals visited
China in July, down 47.5 percent from the same month in 1988.
   Businessmen are included in the July visitor figure, which was up
11.3 percent from June.
   The report said China also received 4,700 overseas Chinese, down
30.2 percent from the previous year, and 1.69 million compatriots
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan, down 31.7 percent.
   China International Travel Service handled only 1,200 foreign
tourists, down 93.7 percent, China Travel Service received 41,100
tourists, down 58.2 percent and China Youth Travel Service received
only 900 people, down 91.9 percent.
   The report said tourism in Beijing, Shanghai and such tourist
spots as Hangzhou and Guilin was about 90 percent lower. There were
67.1 percent fewer tourists in Guangdong province, where Canton is
located.
   Most tourists have avoided China since martial law was imposed on
Beijing after the June 3-4 military attack on student-led
demonstrators in which hundreds, and perhaps thousands, of people
were killed.
   Luxury hotels are operating at less than 50 percent of capacity,
restaurants catering to Western tourists are empty, famous tourist
sites such as the Great Wall are deserted. Many of the hawkers who
sold souvenirs to foreign visitors have gone out of business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
