<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-USKilling     08-28 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US Killing,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filipino Communist Admits Killing U.S. Colonel, Military Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communist rebel has admitted taking
part in the April 21 shooting of U.S. Army Col. James Rowe, the
highest-ranking U.S. official to be killed in the 20-year-old
insurgency, the military said Monday.
   It announced that Juanito Itaas, 25, was arrested with a
companion Sunday evening in Davao City after intelligence reports
linked him to the death.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montanao, acting military chief of staff, said he
considered the Rowe case solved.
   It was the first time the military claimed to have arrested one
of the assassins. Police in June arrested a messenger for a
university newspaper in connection with the slaying but said later
he was not believed to have been among the actual assailants.
   Rowe, 51, of McAllen, Texas, a decorated Vietnam War veteran who
escaped after five years in a Viet Cong prison camp, was shot on his
way to work at the Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in Quezon
City. Communist rebels claimed responsibility.
   Itaas was flown on Monday to Manila from Davao City, 610 miles
south of the capital. Officials said he would be charged with murder.
   Itaas told reporters in Davao City he was part of a seven-man
rebel team that ambushed Rowe a few blocks from his office.
   He said he was summonded to Manila from Davao City a week before
the killing to attend a communist meeting on organizational
problems. After arriving, Itaas said he was ordered to take part in
an assassination but did not know the intended target.
   Itaas also said he did not know the real names of any of the
others involved in the killing. He said he was among four assailants
in one of two cars. Three other assailants were in a backup vehicle,
he added.
   Military officials said Itaas admitted taking part in three other
assassinations of police and military officers in Davao City area.
His companion, Angelito Moralla, 23, was held as a suspected member
of the rebel logistics command.
   Rowe was assigned to a unit that provides training and logistical
support to the Philippine armed forces. Rebels claim the
organization also assists the military clandestinely in
counterinsurgency operations.
</TEXT>
