<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 0756EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Brazil-Church Adv05   08-28 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Church, Adv 05,0944</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 5 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Brazil's Catholic Progressives Vow Political Fight for Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<UNK>By KEN SILVERSTEIN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>DUQUE DE CAXIAS, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The progressive wing of Brazil's
Roman Catholic Church has promised to keep fighting for political
change on behalf of the nation's impoverished multitudes, despite
Pope John Paul II's warnings that politics is not the business of
priests.
   ``In Latin America, religion has too often been utilized to
justify submission and domination,'' said Bishop Pedro Casaldaliga,
a leader of the progressive wing, which is the dominant faction in
the National Conference of Brazilian Bishops. ``It's necessary now
to stimulate the connection between faith and politics and work for
greater social justice.''
   Casaldaliga, who is Spanish-born, has received death threats for
defending Indians and landless peasants in his diocese in the
western state of Mato Grosso. He also has praised Nicaragua's
Sandinista government and leftist groups in El Salvador and
Guatemala.
   Last year, he received a letter from the Vatican criticizing his
pastoral work and placing restrictions on his visits to Central
America.
   But he said he would not be silenced.
   ``I can't accept the separation of life and politics,''
Casaldaliga said in an interview. ``To renounce my political
commitments would be equivalent to renouncing my faith.''
   Political involvement was the key message at a meeting of 2,000
delegates representing 100,000 ``Ecclesiastical Base Communities,''
church-sponsored social groups set up mainly in poor urban and rural
areas of Brazil.
   Among the delegates gathering in this poor, crime-ridden Rio de
Janeiro suburb were 95 of Brazil's 374 bishops, 135 priests, 100
nuns and 900 church workers. The others were community
representatives.
   The five-day meeting in July offered workshops on topics such as
``The Formation of Christians for Political Participation'' and
``Political Militance and the Deepening of Faith.''
   Casaldaliga described the meeting as ``especially important''
because it was held despite Vatican pressure on the Brazilian church.
   While the progressives remain dominant in the National Conference
of Brazilian Bishops, the church's main operational organization
here, it has become more centrist over the past few years, largely
as a result of the appointment of a number of conservative bishops
by the Vatican.
   Brazilians use the term ``progressives'' to describe what in
other parts of the world are called liberals.
   Brazilian church leaders were the most prominent critics of the
military government that ruled from 1964 to 1985 and have frequently
clashed with the civilian government that followed. The bishops
conference has accused the current administration of President Jose
Sarney of corruption and failure to implement a promised agrarian
reform program.
   The Brazilian church also has had several well publicized
disputes with the Vatican in recent years.
   The Rev. Leonardo Boff, Brazil's most prominent progressive
theologian, was ordered to maintain ``obedient silence'' for a year
in 1985. Early this year, Cardinal Paulo Evaristo Arns, another
progressive leader, had his Sao Paulo Archdiocese divided into five
smaller dioceses, seriously undermining his influence.
   But Carlos Alberto Libanio Christo, a Dominican friar who was
imprisoned for four years by Brazil's military government, said it
was essential for church leaders to continue to take stands on
social questions.
   ``Brazil finds itself in very difficult circumstances,'' he added
in an interview after the conference. ``For example, we have a
foreign debt of $112 billion, the highest in the developing world,
and will pay out $12 billion this year alone in interest on it.
Solutions to problems such as the debt are eminently political.
   ``The Vatican cannot be against politics. After all, the pope is
also a head of state.''
   Tomas Balduino, bishop of Goias, about 150 miles west of
Brasilia, the capital, in central Brazil, stressed the same theme.
   ``Politics is key because it concretizes the road to
liberation,'' he said told a reporter. ``We want liberation not only
in the realm of theology but in practice as well.''
   But Balduino, though admitting to past tensions between the
Brazilian church and the Vatican, said he saw no danger of a major
confrontation with Rome.
   ``The pope has benefited from our interchanges and so have we,''
he said.
   Bishop Adriano Hypolito of Nova Iguacu near Rio, who was briefly
kidnapped and tortured in 1976 by right-wing vigilantes because of
his criticism of the military government, said, ``All the church's
social work is political. We have the right to form people and that
formation has to be for the common good.''
   Hypolito was one of five Brazilian bishops to receive critical
letters from the Vatican last October. He did not want to discuss
the contents in an interview, but Brazilian press accounts have said
he had been sharply rebuked for ``opening paths for ideological
groups'' in his diocese.
   ``The letter was not really serious,'' he said. ``It was like a
note from a father to a son, reminding him to take care crossing the
street. I have no fears about the future.''
   Another sign the progressives intend to continue their political
activism came a week after the conference.
   Bishop Mauro Morelli, whose diocese was host to the conference,
endorsed the presidential campaign of Luis Inacio Lula da Silva of
the socialist Workers' Party in the Nov. 15 presidential elections,
although the pope has frequently insisted that church leaders stay
out of party politics.
   ``The Workers' Party was born out of the people's struggle and
has serious proposals,'' Morelli said in his endorsement. ``I don't
vote for friends but for ideologies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv For Tues PMs Sept. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
