<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, Sept. 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Sept. 5, the 248th day of 1989. There are 117
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Fifty years ago, on Sept. 5, 1939, the United States proclaimed
its neutrality in World War II.
   On this date:
   In 1698, Russia's Peter the Great imposed a tax on beards.
   In 1774, the first Continental Congress assembled in Philadelphia.
   In 1836, Sam Houston was elected president of the Republic of
Texas.
   In 1882, the nation's first Labor Day parade was held in New York.
   In 1905, the Treaty of Portsmouth ending the Russo-Japanese War
was signed in New Hampshire. President Theodore Roosevelt mediated
the settlement.
   In 1914, the First Battle of the Marne began during World War I.
   In 1945, Iva Toguri D'Aquino _ a Japanese-American suspected of
being radio broadcaster ``Tokyo Rose'' _ was arrested in Yokohama.
She served six years for treason, but was pardoned in 1977 by
President Gerald R. Ford.
   In 1957, ``On the Road,'' a novel by leading ``beat'' author Jack
Kerouac, was first published.
   In 1958, ``Doctor Zhivago,'' a novel by Russian author Boris
Pasternak, was published in the United States for the first time.
   In 1975, President Gerald R. Ford escaped an attempt on his life
when Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, a disciple of Charles Manson,
attempted to shoot the chief executive in Sacramento, Calif.
   In 1972, 11 Israeli athletes and five Arab guerrillas who had
taken them hostage were killed in a shootout with West German police
during the Summer Olympics in Munich.
   In 1977, West German industrialist Hanns-Martin Schleyer was
kidnapped in Cologne by members of the Baader-Meinhof gang. Schleyer
was later murdered by his captors.
   In 1977, seemingly in reverse order, the U.S. launched the
Voyager I spacecraft two weeks after launching its twin, Voyager II.
   In 1978, President Jimmy Carter welcomed Israeli Prime Minister
Menachem Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat to Camp David,
Md., for a summit that would result in the Camp David Middle East
peace accords.
   In 1986, 21 people were killed and dozens wounded after four
hijackers who had seized a Pan Am jumbo jet in Karachi, Pakistan,
began opening fire when the lights inside the plane failed.
   Ten years ago: Funeral services were held in London for Earl
Mountbatten of Burma, the British war hero killed in the bombing of
his private yacht by the Irish Republican Army on Aug. 27.
   Five years ago: The space shuttle Discovery completed its maiden
flight as it landed at Edwards Air Force Base in California.
   One year ago: On the campaign trail, Republican George Bush
continued to link his opponent with ``the liberal left,'' while
Democrat Michael Dukakis charged that under a GOP administration,
``the rich have become richer, the poor have gotten poorer.''
   Today's birthdays: Composer John Cage is 77. The president of the
Motion Picture Association of America, Jack Valenti, is 68. Former
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Paul Volcker is 62. Comedian-actor
Bob Newhart is 60. Senator John Danforth, R-Mo., is 53. Actor
William Devane is 50. Actress Raquel Welch is 49. ``Cathy''
cartoonist Cathy Guisewite is 39.
   Thought for today: ``An error is simply a failure to adjust
immediately from a preconception to an actuality.'' _ John Cage,
American composer (1912-).
</TEXT>
