<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Sept. 7, the 250th day of 1989. There are 115
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Sept. 7, 1825, the French hero of the American Revolution _
the Marquis de Lafayette _ bade farewell to President John Quincy
Adams at the White House at the conclusion of his tour of the United
States.
   On this date:
   In 1533, England's Queen Elizabeth I was born in Greenwich.
   In 1822, Brazil declared its independence from Portugal.
   In 1887, English poet Dame Edith Sitwell was born in Scarborough.
   In 1892, James J. Corbett knocked out John L. Sullivan in the
21st round to win the world heavyweight crown in New Orleans.
   In 1901, the Peace of Beijing ended the Boxer Rebellion in China.
   In 1936, rock legend Buddy Holly was born Charles Hardin Holley
in Lubbock, Texas.
   In 1940, Nazi Germany began its blitz on London during World War
II.
   In 1963, the National Professional Football Hall of Fame was
dedicated in Canton, Ohio.
   In 1969, 20 years ago, Senate Republican Everett M. Dirksen died
in Washington.
   In 1977, the Panama Canal treaties, calling for the U.S. to
eventually turn over control of the waterway to Panama, were signed
in Washington by President Jimmy Carter and General Omar Torrijos
Herrera.
   In 1977, convicted Watergate conspirator G. Gordon Liddy was
released from prison after more than four years behind bars.
   In 1986, Desmond Tutu was installed as the first black to lead
the Anglican Church in southern Africa.
   In 1987, Erich Honecker became the first East German head of
state to visit West Germany as he arrived in Bonn for a five-day
visit.
   Ten years ago: Anglican Bishop Robert Runcie was chosen to be the
102nd Archbishop of Canterbury, succeeding the Most Reverend Donald
Coggan. The Entertainment and Sports Programming Network made its
debut on cable television.
   Five years ago: The Labor Department reported that the nation's
unemployment rate in August 1984 remained at the July level of a
seasonally adjusted 7.4 percent of the work force.
   One year ago: Republican George Bush startled a friendly American
Legion audience in Louisville, Ky., by referring to Sept. 7 as Pearl
Harbor Day, which is actually Dec. 7.
   Today's birthdays: Heart surgeon Dr. Michael DeBakey is 81.
Producer-director Elia Kazan is 80. Actor Anthony Quayle is 76.
Senator Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, is 65. Actor John Philip Law is 52.
Actress Susan Blakely is 41. Actress Julie Kavner is 38.
   Thought for today: ``It is love, not reason, that is stronger
than death.'' _ Thomas Mann, German author (1875-1955).
