<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   08-28 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday Aug 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Early Start on Tax-Planning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you think they're rushing Christmas with those
catalogs before Labor Day, you should see the financial mail. It's
about taxes.
   That's right, federal income taxes. April 15 in August.
   But as much as that sounds like madness, there is some method in
it. Many taxpayers and the people who advise them have learned from
experience that it is never too soon to start arranging your affairs
to minimize the burden when it comes time to settle up with Uncle
Sam.
   ``The ideal would be to start in January,'' said William Brennan,
a specialist in the subject with the accounting firm of Ernst &amp;
Young.
   Tax planning _ some might call it finagling _ is often portrayed
as a shadowy activity practiced only by the rich at the expense of
the ordinary wage-earner.
   Note, for example, the court case this summer in which Leona
Helmsley, the New York hotelier accused of tax evasion, was quoted
by a witness as saying that ``only the little people'' pay taxes.
   Or consider the fuss over whether Malcolm Forbes, the magazine
publisher and bon vivant, might have been entitled to deduct some of
the expenses of his Morocco birthday extravaganza as a business
expense (he said he wouldn't anyway).
   The morals of the matter may depend on your personal viewpoint.
The law on this point, however, is pretty clear.
   It was settled long ago by the noted appeals court judge Learned
Hand, who decreed that everybody has a perfect right to take all
measures available within the law to minimize the taxes they owe.
   For most of the 1980s, the big tax planning problem has been
adjusting to some just-passed sweeping overhaul of the tax system.
This year, for a change, there isn't much that is drastically new.
   But there is a lot of uncertainty over changes that might be made
in the future.
   The betting among the experts is that sooner or later the low
basic income tax rates set by the 1986 tax reform law will be raised
again in some way.
   ``Before new tax laws became an annual event, sound tax strategy
generally called for deferring part of income and accelerating
certain expense items to shift some of the tax burden to the next
year,'' said analysts at Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. in the firm's
weekly publication The Outlook.
   ``Now the decision is less clear-cut. But despite prospects for
higher taxes to come, shifting income forward and expenses back is
still the best tax strategy in most cases.''
   This kind of maneuver can be as simple as stepping up charitable
contributions so that they are made before New Year's.
   ``It's easier to accelerate deductions than to defer income,''
observed the accounting firm Laventhol &amp; Horwath in a recent yearend
planning report.
   ``The reason is obvious: You control the money you pay out, but
not the money you take in.''
   Self-employed people have more flexibility in this regard. If
their checkbooks can stand the wait, they can simply delay sending
out bills to customers or clients so that the money won't be paid
until after 1990 has begun.
   One long-cherished deduction for many people continues to fade,
on its way to extinction by 1991. Consumer interest is 20 percent
deductible this year, and only 10 percent next.
   Says Standard &amp; Poor's: ``Many tax advisors now recommend either
paying off such loans early or consolidating them under a home
equity loan of up to $100,000, on which the interest is fully
deductible, regardless of how loan proceeds are used.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Aug 29</NOTE>
