<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Mexico-Labor Adv07   08-28 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Labor, Adv 07,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, Sept. 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Strike Accord Seen as Blow to Union Corruption in Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. assembly plants, back in operation
after winning a three-week labor dispute, have blazed the trail for
other companies to fight the extraordinary power labor unions hold
in Mexico, industry spokesmen say.
   A union power struggle that shut down 15 American plants known as
maquiladoras in the border city of Reynosa ended with labor and
government officials agreeing Aug. 18 to let the workers form a
union independent of the nationally powerful Mexican Workers
Federation whose local representative forced the workers to strike.
   ``It definitely means that companies can take a stand against
illegal activities and corruption and be successsul,'' said Don
King, manager for Reynosa's West Bend plant.
   ``We blazed a new trail.''
   The strike was settled after intervention of President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's government in Mexico City.
   Salinas has made clear he will not let unions stand in the way of
his goal of modernizing the Mexican economy and attracting more
foreign investors.
   ``The Salinas government has acted in a certain direction to
remove as much of the corruption as it possibly can,'' said Arnold
Kezsbom, president of the New York-based Service Manufacturing Corp.
whose Reynosa plant was closed in the strike.
   ``He doesn't want to have the negative publicity that occurred
out of this permeate throughout the world. The issue was the
expansion of the maquiladora industry in Mexico.''
   Maquiladoras, in which foreign-owned companies take advantage of
cheap Mexican labor to produce goods for sale in their own countries
or elsewhere, have become a top foreign income earner for Mexico.
   The industry, which generated $2.3 billion in foreign currency
last year, has grown by more than 70 percent since 1985 and employs
about 392,000 people, mainly along the U.S.-Mexican border.
   The strike cost an estimated $500,000 a day in lost production,
but plant managers said it was worth it because the outcome was
favorable to them.
   Although the plant workers indicated no great sympathy for a
walkout, they went on strike July 25 on the orders of Rafael
Morales, a local leader of the powerful Mexican Workers Federation.
   Strike flags were hoisted. Traditionally in Mexico, workers who
violate strike flags face severe consequences, including possible
physical harm, immediately or later.
   The plants, nevertheless, continued to pay the workers their
wages and benefits, averaging about $1.20 a hour, during the strike.
   Kezsbom said the American managers resisted Morales, who controls
most of the labor contracts at Reynosa's 27 other maquiladoras,
because they considered him corrupt.
   Morales forced companies to give him control of trucking
contracts, waste disposal and scrap resale, and to issue food
coupons good only at stores he controls. The coupons are part of the
employee benefit packages.
   The nearly 2,000 workers at the plants Morales shut down waited
for two weeks while plant managers and business leaders pleaded with
the federal government in Mexico City to step in.
   Then, frustrated by government inaction, about 900 workers ripped
down the strike flags, stormed back into their plants and went to
work.
   That same day Interior Secretary Fernando Gutierrez Barrios met
with industry leaders in Mexico City and promised the government
would intervene.
   Gov. Americo Villarreal of Tamaulipas summoned the managers to a
meeting in the state capital, Ciudad Victoria, the next day to work
out an accord giving the plant workers the right to form an
independent union.
   The agreement surprised those familiar with the strength of the
Mexican Workers Federation, the nation's largest labor organization
and a powerful sector of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party.
   Although the agreement stipulates that only workers from the
affected 15 plants can join the independent union, industry
spokesmen say it may open a new era of labor relations in Tamaulipas
and other Mexican states with maquiladora plants.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Sept. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
