<FIRST>s a BC-APN--RacehorseAcupuncture ADV10-1stAdd   08-28 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Racehorse Acupuncture, ADV 10-1st Add,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10</HEAD>
<TEXT>ELMONT: of life.''    Not that Cain is unrealistic.    ``Acupuncture
hasn't replaced anything we've already learned, just as surgery did not
replace anything we already learned. It just added another important piece
of the professional pie. I try and teach young vets not to become polarized
and use acupuncture for everything, but rather to use it in conjunction
with what we already know.''    Cain also concedes, in effect, that there
is something in acupuncture that just might be called a touch.    Some
argue flat out that it is an art _ or even voodoo _ but not science. 
  Cain agrees there is a certain art to it. He compares it to playing the
piano.    ``You can take lessons forever and practice forever, but most
people will never be able to write or compose like Mozart,'' he says. 
  According to horse trainers, Cain is the Mozart of Belmont.    Cain
says that when he first started, his Chinese instructors told him it would
take seven years to become a master acupuncturist. He didn't believe it
at the time, but he says he does now. He says many subtleties are
picked up by experience.    Likewise, he says, acupuncture will never
create a great racehorse.    ``There's nothing I can do to make a horse
run faster than its capacity. It's never been my intent to make any creatures
outperform its ability. It's simply to put them in a state of balance so
they can perform at their optimum, to perform without drugs.''    The
American Veterinary Medical Association, representing more than 45,000
veterinarians, recognized acupuncture as a valid form of veterinary medicine
in July 1988, but still the only courses taught at the nation's 27 schools
of veterinary medicine are electives.    The IVAS offers an extensive
course somewhere in the United States every other year, with the next one
in Tampa, Fla. On odd years, it is offered on foreign soil. The 120-hour
course costs about $2,000 and at the end, trainees must pass both written
and practical exams.    ``Veterinarians in Europe had accepted acupuncture
far more widely than the Americans,'' Cain says. ``They are not so
rigidly governed by their medical associations.''    Schoen says about
200 vets in the United States have been certified by the IVAS, but that
far more vets have learned a little bit of acupuncture and are using it
in smaller ways.    Acupuncture has also been reported to be successful
in treating prize livestock with fertility problems.    Dr. Sheldon Altman
of Burbank, Calif., who has a small-animal practice, feels there is a growing
demand for acupuncture within the profession.    ``I'm the garbage dump
of southern California,'' Altman says. ``It's becoming 80 percent of my
practice, but by the time they get to me, things are sometimes pretty bad.
I don't get that many miracles. Usually, I work on chronic pain problems,
such as arthritis, degenerative joint diseases, slipped disks.''    Altman
himself has landed in the emergency ward twice when dogs in severe pain
did not think that needles were a particularly good idea. Now, he says,
he will not treat a dog that is too nervous.    ``There's too much
adrenalin and the acupuncture probably won't be very effective,'' he says.
   All of the vets agree that the father of veterinary acupuncture in
the United States was the late H. Grady Young of Thomasville, Ga. He started
using acupuncture nearly 50 years ago, at a time when most Americans had
never even heard of it.    In fact, he couldn't even find a book about
it. He found a primer on acupuncture in a used-book store in London and
began experimenting. His first animal patient was a black Labrador retriever
scheduled to be destroyed due to a severe reaction to an immunization shot.
   Altman couldn't believe his eyes when the dog seemed to recover instantly.
In fact, he was so sure the cure was temporary that he did not tell the
owner for six weeks. Then he called the owner to say his pet was alive
and well.    ``Grady just learned by reading books and practicing,'' Cain
says. ``I'm desperately trying to fulfill Grady's dream of spreading the
use of acupuncture.''  
</TEXT>
