<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--LouisBellson ADV10   08-28 1110</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Louis Bellson, ADV 10,1165</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   For years he has been the musician's musician.
Now at 65 he recalls all the big bands and the stellar names that
have passed his way. Mild-mannered and modest, Louis Bellson recalls
the one time he really got mad _ at Benny Goodman.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Bellson, drummer extraordinaire, is not one
to beat his own drum.
   When he turned 65 in July, his offstage modesty matched his
flamboyance on stage.
   He chooses to praise other musicians.
   But the most sincere form of flattery in the music business is
when musicians ask you to sit in with them. And Bellson is much in
demand.
   When trumpeter Clark Terry put together ``Clark Terry and
Friends'' for this year's JVC Jazz Festival here, Bellson and
pianist Oscar Peterson were the friends he chose for his final set.
Bellson's wife since 1952, Pearl Bailey, was in the audience.
   In 1946, Bellson got the idea of using twin bass drums. His
simultaneous manipulation of two bass drums at incredible speed is
one of the most exciting and popular features of his drumming _ used
both for spectacular effect and musical validity.
   But, characteristically, he'd rather talk about other drummers.
   ``It's an honor to be put in a class with Gene Krupa and Buddy
Rich,'' he says. ``But I'm not the only one left. My teachers are
living today. I learned to play listening to Max Roach and Art
Blakey.
   ``I listen to Max today. I smile. I'll pick out something I never
heard before. He's the first drummer to teach all of us to play
melodically. Before him, drummers played rhythmically.
   ``Jo Jones taught me how to play wonderful brush things. He was
the king with the high hat (cymbal). Buddy Rich and I _ we remained
friends until he died _ used to say, if we had to pick just one
drummer it would be Jo when he came out with the Basie Band. He was
the first to play with that fluid drive.
   ``How can you not talk about Chick Webb, Big Sid Catlett, Jimmie
Crawford with the Lunceford Band? People said, `You finally swung
the Ellington Band.' I'd say, `Listen to those records Sonny Greer
did.' There was so much magic there.''
   Louis Bellson, pronounced Louie, was born in Rock Falls, Ill.,
one of four boys and four girls whose Italian father had a music
store. Frank played clarinet. Tony and Henry still play drums. Ede
teaches music in Las Vegas.
   ``We had to learn the rudiments of almost every instrument in the
music store so we could give lessons,'' he says. ``By the time we
were 13, we knew every aria from every opera. It gave us a wonderful
basic structure of music. We were lucky to have our father.
   ``I can go to an opera and enjoy that as well as go to a good
jazz concert. It is wonderful to be able to do that. Music is such a
big thing in our lives.''
   As he sold Dorsey, Miller, Ellington and Basie records in the
store, Bellson says, ``I was always thinking how I'd like to go on
the road and play with those bands.'' He went to ballrooms to hear
traveling bands. Sometimes he sat in.
   Ted Fio Rito hired Bellson when he graduated from high school and
asked if he knew a girl singer. Bellson recommended a fellow
cheerleader, June Haver.
   ``I stayed with him three months, at the Florentine Gardens in
Los Angeles. The Mills Brothers were the main attraction. I learned
so much from that great quartet. One night Freddy Goodman came in.
He was managing his brother. He sent me a note to come to his table
and said, `How would you like to audition for Benny Goodman?'
   ``Benny was doing a picture at Paramount Studios. I went down the
next day. I heard Benny say, `Where's the kid?' I started to sweat.
Benny said, `Put makeup and a gray jacket on him.' My audition was
being in the movie. Benny said, `You got the job. We leave
Thursday.'''
   After Goodman, and Army service, Bellson was with Tommy Dorsey
from 1947 to '49, had a sextet, then played with Harry James until
spending 1951 to '53 with Duke Ellington.
   He left Ellington shortly after he married Pearl Bailey to form
his own bands and combos, often backing his wife. And his former
employers often hired him for special gigs.
   One career highlight was playing in Las Vegas for a bill
combining Pearl Bailey and Louis Armstrong.
   Another highlight was playing for Ellington.
   ``With Ellington,'' Bellson says, ``you never knew exactly what
you were in for. When you joined Ellington, there was no drum book.
He wanted to get the ultimate from you.''
   Bellson's latest album is ``East Side Suite,'' a 53-minute piece
composed with Tommy Newsom, plus six other tracks. Earlier this
year, Musicmasters Records also released ``Hot.'
   ``I've got a big band in Los Angeles and in New York,'' Bellson
says. ``Both are superb. Pearl requires a quartet when she performs.
I'm part of that and I still work with a quintet and do clinics at
high schools and colleges.''
   Miss Bailey and Bellson haven't let their traveling, her Broadway
stint in ``Hello, Dolly!'' or her Georgetown University attendance _
she was graduated in 1985 _ keep them apart for more than a month at
a time.
   Most musicians say Bellson never shows anger, but he once got
furious with Benny Goodman.
   Goodman had asked if Bellson's band would play the first half of
programs in San Francisco and Phoenix. ``I was delighted.''
   But gradually during rehearsals, Goodman started to stare down
some of Bellson's musicians and tell them what to do.
   On a break, Bellson found Goodman sunning himself on the hood of
Bellson's brand new car, his heels scratching the paint.
   ``We went back and he started picking on me and the rhythm
section. I put the sticks down and said, `I don't know what you
want. Get yourself another drummer.' I was so mad at Benny I wanted
to kill him.''
   Goodman apologized later by phone.
   Bellson tried movie music in the 1960s for the likes of Henry
Mancini, but found it unfulfilling. ``I had to go out on the road
and play.
   ``If it were all to end tomorrow I'd still smile _ Ellington,
Basie, Goodman, Dorsey, James _ what more can you ask for?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
