<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Jenkins Adv8-10   08-28 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Jenkins, Adv 8-10,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08-10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept 8-10, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: A Man for All Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tomi Jenkins likes a ballad jazzy and light, the
way his hero Stevie Wonder might write it. But the singer's earliest
musical inspiration was heavy and loud: the Kinks' ``You Really ot
Me.''
   ``That was the song for me,' said Jenkins, a member of the funk
trio Cameo. He recently issued his debut solo album ``Tomi.''
   ``I couldn't stop singing that. It was so different. Before that,
I was listening to R&amp;B and Motown. But then I had friends who
listened to nothing but Traffic, Yes and artists like that. Man,
this was a whole other world. That started my appreciation for whole
different types of music.''
   He brought that same approach to Cameo, which prided itself on
its appeal to diverse audiences, and combines rock, pop, jazz and
funk on his own record.
   ``There's a lot of songs on my album that can be played on AOR
(album-oriented rock) as well as the R&amp;B charts,'' he said. ``It's
not like I consciously set out to write a song for across the board.
I just write that kind of music.''
   While solo albums are often signs of trouble for rock bands,
Jenkins insists that he just wants a change of pace, a chance to
have listeners get to know him better.
   Proving there are no hard feelings, Jenkins has fellow Cameo
member Larry Blackmon producing ``Tomi'' and is recording again with
the group for their new record.
   ``I had written a lot of songs,'' he said. ``A couple of them we
tried to work into Cameo but it just didn't come off.
   ``My voice was really never prominently heard in Cameo even
though I knew I could sing. I didn't beef about it. Cameo is a
concept and I can only do so much within that format. Sooner or
later I had to break out and get my own musical ideas.''
   Jenkins grew up in Rahway, N.J., remembering it as a nice, small
town, but his entertainment days began at Cape Cod in Massachusetts.
   ``My parents would take us there and we'd stay in cabins. They
had entertainment in the house where everybody ate so I would sing,
with no accompaniment. I would sing the same song a hundred times a
day.
   ``The reaction was sheer panic. They ran.''
   He had some stage fright, but speech and drama classes calmed
Jenkins. After graduating from high school, he worked full-time at a
local chemical company until meeting Blackmon in the mid-'70s.
   ``He had just broken up his band and I was looking for a band,''
Jenkins said. ``I got together with Larry and we started New York
City Players. Almost a year later we had a record deal with
Casablanca and were calling ourselves Cameo.''
   Cameo, which also includes Nathan Leftenant, had a rough
beginning, waiting out the disco boom and enduring Casablanca's
legal and financial battles.
   ``Every year they had another president,'' Jenkins said. ``It
affected us greatly, trying to get the music played. When you have
changing regimes, things are just scattered and we suffered greatly
because of it.''
   But they never considered giving up, and finally had their
commercial break in 1979 with ``Secret Omen,'' their first of six
gold albums. Pop success came eight years later with ``Word Up,'' a
Top 10 single and the title track of their platinum album.
   ```Word Up' was slang for `What's happening.' We heard it first
in London. There were some guys going in to do a show at the BBC and
one of them standing outside the gate is saying, `Hey, man, word
up.' We came back to the states and wrote the hit record.''
   ``She's Strange,'' another hit single, was also made possible by
a little eavesdropping.
   ``I remember Larry and I were on an elevator. A woman says,
`That's really strange,' and we just go, `Strange?' That happens a
lot, a one-word catch word, something that stands out.''
   Jenkins is still always on the lookout for a good song, doing his
best to remember any catchy phrase he happens to hear.
   ``I got scraps of paper all over the house. I try to write in a
book but it never works out. I sit down and work out the music.
Usually it's the melody that inspires the lyrics.''
   Jenkins expects most of his audience to initially consist of
Cameo fans, but he's confident he'll have success on his own merits.
   ``As they get into it, they'll definitely recognize the
difference between my music and Cameo's music. They'll see that
here's a guy who can sing and has good songs, different songs from
Cameo. You'd never hear three ballads on a Cameo album.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 8-10</NOTE>
