<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo said he was considering a
sale of Continental Airlines because the ``noise'' at strike-torn
Eastern Airlines was hurting the sister carrier's business.
   In an interview Friday with The Associated Press, Lorenzo said
the sale of part or all of Houston-based Continental was under
discussion partly because of the negative impact from Eastern's
bitter strike and bankruptcy proceeding.
   ``We have to be responsible to our shareholders,'' Lorenzo said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declining mortgage rates boosted sales of
existing homes in July for the first back-to-back monthly increases
this year, a real estate trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Friday that existing
single- family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.40 million units in July, a 1.2 percent increase over revised
figures for June that showed a 4.7 percent increase to 3.36 million
units annually.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world is tightening its economic
boycott of South Africa, but the apartheid state exploits loopholes
such as foreign registration, mislabeling and third-party shipping
to carry on trade, says a new report.
   Among the most vociferous proponents of sanctions are the black
front-line states of southern Africa, which ironically carry on
considerable trade with South Africa.
   The report issued this week from the United Nations Center on
Transnational Corporations notes that the front-line states have
become transshipment points for South African goods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese did it in six months. France did it
in 19 months, and Britain beat us by 20 days.
   While the new record set by the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials was celebrated as a symbolic comeback from the crash of
1987, other stock markets around the world have made faster
recoveries than Wall Street.
   ``It wasn't that the U.S. did poorly,'' Mark Sladkus, a vice
president at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., said Friday. ''It's that the
other markets had special circumstances.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though some first-time investors who were scared
away by the stock market crash two years ago never returned, those
who remained got their reward, market-watchers say.
   The record high of 2,734.64 in the Dow Jones industrials average
Thursday once again pointed out the value of a long-term investment
strategy, these observers said Friday.
   Anyone who held stocks for the past two years has about broken
even, while people who panicked and sold at the bottom took big
losses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of video rental shops have received
promotional kits for a horror movie with live snakes inside the
packages, and outraged animal protection officials called the stunt
``cruel and irresponsible.''
   The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals called
on Cinema International Corp. on Friday to take back the 700
reptiles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two federal agencies and the financial
exchanges they regulate are squaring off over a new product for
investors known as a ``stock basket.''
   On one side are the stock exchanges and their overseer, the
Securities and Exchange Commission. On the other is the newer
Commodity Futures Trading Commission and its charges, the boisterous
markets that deal in commodities.
   The product at issue is technically called an ``index
participation,'' but it resembles a basket of stocks because it
allows investors to buy or sell something with a value tied to broad
stock market indexes, such as the Standard &amp; Poors 500.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial bankers who successfully kept their
deposit insurance fund away from failed savings and loans say the
S&amp;Ls are engaged in a ``sneaky scheme'' to appropriate the name of
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which once exclusively belonged
to banks.
   But James H. Grohl, senior vice president of the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions, isn't worried about the complaints over its
letter saying thrift institutions can advertise they are insured by
the FDIC.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve policymakers voted to nudge
interest rates lower in July, but they worried about reigniting
inflation by going too far, according to minutes of the meeting.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, noting fairly consistent
weakness in housing and consumer spending, voted 10-1 at the end of
its July 5-6 meeting to lower short-term interest rates, according
to the minutes released Friday.
   Subsequently, the benchmark federal funds rate _ the rate banks
charge each other for overnight loans _ fell twice, in quarter-point
increments, to 9 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted a small loss Friday, hesitating after the
yearlong rally that carried the market to record highs Thursday. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped back 2.28 to 2,732.36.
   The dollar finished higher in domestic dealings after declining
overseas. Bond prices dropped after a selloff in Treasury issues.
   Cocoa futures prices plunged as traders looked ahead to next
month's meeting of the International Cocoa Organization with an
expectation of failure. Copper prices reached new contract highs,
grain and soybean futures plunged, precious metals declined, oil
futures were down and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
