<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-28 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0229</SECOND>
<UNK>Dollar Up, Gold Down</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in early European trading
today, thinned by the closure of London financial markets for a bank
holiday.
   Foreign currency dealers said that in the absence of London
trading, little movement was expected until after the opening of the
U.S. business day.
   Dealers were reluctant to predict the dollar's near-term trend.
   ``In the short-term, everything and nothing can happen to the
dollar,'' said one trader in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose to a two-month high against the Japanese yen,
closing up 0.75 yen at 144.28 yen. Later, in Europe, it was quoted
at 144.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at midmorning compared with late
Friday's London rates, included: 1.9643 West German marks, up from
1.9540; 1.6933 Swiss francs, up from 1.6840; 6.6125 French francs,
up from 6.5895; 2.2143 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2055; 1,408.50
Italian lire, up from 1,405.05; and 1.1750 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1732.
   The dollar rose against the British pound. It cost $1.5642 to buy
one pound in Europe early today compared with $1.5725 in London late
Friday.
   In Zurich, the bid was $359.75, down from $360.25 late Friday.
   Financial institutions were also closed in Hong Kong today for
the Liberation Day holiday.
</TEXT>
