<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-28 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits Two-Month High, Stocks Off Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose to a two-month high against the
Japanese yen today while stock prices fell for the fifth consecutive
day on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 144.28 yen, up 0.75 yen from last Friday's
close of 143.53 yen. It opened at 144.20 yen and moved in a narrow
range of 144.15-144.45 yen.
   It was the dollar's highest close in Tokyo since June 21, when it
closed at 144.95 yen.
   Currency dealers said that while the market in general
anticipated the dollar remaining strong, profit-taking and anxiety
about possible central banks intervention kept the currency in a
narrow range.
   ``There was not really one outstanding incentive behind the
bullish dollar,'' said a dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank.
   A dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, also requesting anonymity, said
the dollar's relative firmness was due to expectations that an
upward revision of U.S. gross national product figures for the
second quarter would be announced Tuesday in Washington.
   He said the Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, stepped
into the market on a small scale to stem the dollar's rise in early
trading. The central bank customarily does not comment on its market
intervention.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed 46.62 points Friday, lost another 132.52 points,
or 0.38 percent, closing at 34,607.41.
   Securities dealers said the yen's weakness against the dollar was
discouraging investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
