<FIRST>r f PM-SpottedOwl     08-28 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spotted Owl,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service Says Proposed Timber Limits Threaten Owl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Forest Service is objecting to a
bill in Congress that would determine how much government-owned
timber can be sold in the Northwest.
   Forest Service officials say the bill would cause further
destruction of the old growth forest habitat of the northern spotted
owl. The bird has been the center of disputes between the timber
industry and preservationists who want to stop logging in the owl's
areas.
   Bills passed by both houses of Congress call for sales of 8
billion board feet of timber by Oct. 1, 1990. That much logging
could undo most of the legal and environmental safeguards put into
place this year to help ensure the survival of the owl, the
officials told The Sunday Oregonian.
   Conservation groups hoping to reduce the timber sales plan a
last-ditch effort when the bills are considered by a joint
conference committee.
   Under the bills, Forest Service officials said, the government
would have to sell nearly all the old-growth timber currently locked
up by a federal court order, violate U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
guidelines on the owl's protection and exceed its own long-term
timber production capacity.
   Loggers say that if more timber isn't cut, they will run out of
logs before the end of the year and have to shut down their mills.
   The sales target measures, pushed by Sen. Mark O. Hatfield,
R-Ore., and Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., call for lifting injunctions
that have halted most old growth sales on national forests in
western Oregon and Washington this year.
   ``To make the 8 billion board feet, we're definitely going to
have to sell a very high percentage of that volume that is
enjoined,'' Deputy Regional Forester John Lowe said.
   The Sunday Oregonian said the agency's concerns have prompted a
re-evaluation of the target sales level by congressional staff
members, who were briefed Thursday by Forest Service officials in
Portland.
   ``We have been receiving a lot of conflicting information from
the Forest Service about whether they can do this,'' an unidentified
Hatfield aide told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
