<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-28 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0314</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting widespread rainfall in the western Grain Belt during the
weekend.
   The showers were spreading eastward this morning and were
expected to douse a good portion of the nation's corn and soybean
crop with beneficial moisture.
   The weather's influence on the grain markets is decreasing,
though, as the soybean crop advances beyond its critical flowering
and pod-setting stage. The corn pollination period is also over, so
the threat of dry-weather damage to either crop is greatly reduced.
   Experts said the market's subdued reaction to the weekend
rainfall illustrated the declining importance of weather as a market
factor.
   ``We're lower but the roof hasn't caved in here,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 1\ cents lower with September at $2.31{ a bushel; oats were
1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with September at $1.33 a bushel;
soybeans were 7{ cents lower to 4 cents higher with September at
$5.74{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .42 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in September at 73.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.32 cent to 1.20 cents lower with August at 83.35 cents a pound;
live hogs were .10 cent to .50 cent lower with October at 40.92
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to .20 cent lower
with February at 41.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
