<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Disney-Henson 2ndLd-Writethru   08-28 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disney-Henson, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Muppets Joining Mickey and Friends</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes, new information from news conference;
ADDs byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kermit, Miss Piggy and many of the
other Muppets will be joining ranks with Mickey Mouse and his
friends in an agreement announced today by Walt Disney World and
Muppet creator Jim Henson.
   Henson and Michael D. Eisner, chairman and chief executive of the
Walt Disney Co., said they have signed an agreement-in-principle for
Disney to acquire Henson Associates Inc., including its film and
television library.
   Both Henson and Eisner, announcing the agreement at a morning
news conference, would not disclose the price of the transaction.
   The proposal includes long-term consulting and exclusive
production agreements, with Henson producing motion pictures,
network and off-network television shows, Disney Channel specials
and series and made-for-home video programming, the release said.
   Also included are special Muppet attractions and rides for Disney
theme parks.
   ``I've loved Disney for many years,'' Henson told reporters. ``I
grew up on its movies... and I love the Disney parks, so we're happy
to have our characters at the parks now.''
   Work is already under way for the first project, a Muppet film
attraction using 3-D technology. The attraction, to open next spring
at the Disney-MGM Studios Theme Park here, will be a collaboration
between Henson and Walt Disney Imagineering.
   Disney will also have the merchandising, publishing and other
rights to Kermit, Miss Piggy, Animal, Fozzie Bear, Gonzo and other
Muppets.
   Although Eisner refused to discuss the cost of the agreement, he
said ``we will have a good return on our investment with just the
material that is there already. This is not to mention what's
coming, what is yet to be created.''
   In a news release earlier, he hailed the proposal as ``a business
association made in family entertainment heaven.''
   Henson, winner of several Emmy awards, introduced Kermit the Frog
and other Muppets to television in the 1950s. His library includes
the television shows ``The Muppet Show,'' ``Fraggle Rock,'' and
``Muppet Babies'' and the films ``The Muppet Movie,'' ``The Great
Muppet Caper'' and ``The Dark Crystal.''
   Henson's puppet segments and characters created for the
children's show ``Sesame Street,'' including ``Big Bird'' and
``Oscar the Grouch,'' aren't included in the agreement.
   Eisner said the ``non-profit continuing involvement'' between
Henson and the children's show would continue unchanged.
   Although Kermit appears on Sesame Street, the character is not
considered exclusive to that show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890828-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-France-ClubMed     08-28 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-France-Club Med,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Efforts To Form Big Tourism Company Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts to form Europe's third-largest tourism
company broke down Monday when officials of the two firms involved,
Club Med and the air charter group, Nouvelles Frontieres, backed
away from a preliminary agreement reached in April.
   Under that accord, Club Mediterranee SA, France's largest tourism
and leisure company, had agreed to acquire a 34 percent stake in the
French travel group Nouvelles Frontieres SA.
   The pact would have moved the combined operations into third
place in Europe behind West Germany's Touristik Union International,
known as TUI, and Britain's Thomson Holidays.
   Nouvelles Frontieres Chairman Jacques Maillot said merger talks
with Club Med President Gilbert Trigano would continue. He said the
personalities of the two company leaders were not a problem in the
talks.
   Trigano told a French radio station the break was not final and
said time for reflection might lead to a new approach.
   According to both sides there was disagreement on two points _ a
sale agreement Club Med has with the travel unit of the French media
group Havas and establishment of a joint airline unit.
   Maillot said Nouvelles Frontieres wanted to establish its own
sales unit as the West German and British companies have done while
Trigano wanted to expand operations with Havas.
   Maillot said he also wanted to take over an existing airline
company, Corsica Air, and develop it while Trigano preferred setting
up a separate airline unit while maintaining Club Med's close
relations with Air France's charter company.
   Trigano was quoted in the business daily La Tribune de
L'Expansion as saying Club Med would continue to look for partners
in the field both inside and outside France. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890828-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-RigCount     08-28 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Increases by Six to 935</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs in the
country improved slightly last week, climbing by six to total 909,
Baker Hughes Inc. reported.
   The increase was marginal compared with the 45 rigs added to the
count the previous week. That increase was due partly to areas
drying out from the heavy rains brought on by Hurricane Chantal
several weeks ago, Baker Hughes officials said.
   A year ago, the count stood at 935, the company said Monday.
   Ike Kerridge, vice president of stockholder relations and
economist for Baker Hughes, said more drilling has been predicted
for the second half of the year.
   Baker Hughes' rig count _ the widely watched industry index of
drilling activity _ reflects the number of rigs actively exploring
for oil as of last Friday, not the number of rigs actively producing
oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   Texas, which accounted for more than half of the 45-rig increase,
was the big loser this time, with its count dropping by 14.
   Among other major oil producing states, Oklahoma's count
increased by six and Wyoming's was up by three. California, New
Mexico, North Dakota and Michigan each gained two more rigs.
   Kansas lost three rigs, Louisiana lost two and Ohio's count was
down one.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
