<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-28 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower On Weekend Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mostly
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by rainfall in
the Midwest, where corn and soybeans are approaching maturity.
   But experts said the weather's influence on grain futures prices
is decreasing daily as the soybean crop follows the corn crop in
growing beyond its pollination phase, when moisture is most
critical, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Three weeks ago, if we had had the kind of rain we had over the
weekend and today, we would have been limit down,'' he said,
referring to the exchange's permitted limits on daily price
fluctuation.
   The day's action also demonstrated strong support in the soybean
market at prices around $5.70 a bushel for September delivery. The
September contract's price fell as low as $5.70{ during the session,
but enough buying interest surfaced there to lift it back above
$5.75.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 2} cents lower to { cent
higher with the contract for delivery in September at $3.88\ a
bushel; corn was } cent to 2\ cents lower with September at $2.32 a
bushel; oats were { cent lower to \ cent higher with September at
$1.34} a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with
September at $5.77 a bushel.
</TEXT>
