<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1757EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-28 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cattle Futures Slide On Signs Of Week Beef Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle futures prices fell sharply Monday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, reflecting a seasonal slump in beef consumption
during the dog days of summer.
   On other markets, coffee futures rebounded; sugar futures
declined; grains and soybeans were mostly lower; oil futures were
mostly higher; and precious metals retreated.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent to .70 cent lower with the contract
for delivery in September at 73.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.30 cent to 1.03 cents lower with August at 83.37 cents a pound.
   The decline extended a two-week-old trend that analysts
attributed largely to consumers' reduced appetite for heavy beef
products during the hottest part of the summer.
   ``People don't fix many pot roasts in August _ they don't want to
heat up the house,'' said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling
Research Corp. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Gordon Linn, president of Chicago-based Linnco Futures Inc., said
the cattle markets typically slow late in August after retailers
have completed their buying of beef destined for Labor Day weekend
cookouts.
   ``We have a seasonal down in the markets through next week,''
Linn said. ``But we kind of think that once we get around Labor Day,
we should pick up some demand.''
   Also at the Merc, hog futures settled .70 cent lower to .02 cent
higher with October at 40.62 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.50 cent to .90 cent lower with February at 41.10 cents a pound.
   Coffee futures rallied on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange in a largely technical rebound from recent 14-year lows.
   Coffee settled 1.6 cents to 3.19 cents higher with September at
82.25 cents a pound.
   Sugar futures fell sharply in New York, also in technically
inspired selling.
   ``There was no specific news item we could specifically point
to,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   Sugar settled .35 cent to .70 cent lower with October at 13.14
cents a pound.
   Most grain and soybean futures finished lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade in reaction to rainfall in the Midwest, where corn
and soybeans are approaching maturity.
   But the weather's influence on grain futures prices is decreasing
daily as the soybean crop follows the corn crop in advancing beyond
its pollination phase, when moisture is most critical, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Three weeks ago, if we had had the kind of rain we had over the
weekend and today, we would have been limit down,'' he said,
referring to the exchange's permitted limits on daily price
fluctuation.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at
$3.88{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2 cents lower with September at
$2.32\ a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher with
September at $1.34} a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 2\
cents higher with September at $5.78 a bushel.
   Most crude oil futures advanced on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, where contracts for delivery of West Texas Intermediate
crude settled 8 cents lower to 11 cents higher with October at
$18.64 a barrel; heating oil was .16 cent to .39 cent higher with
September at 51.72 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to
.60 cent higher with September at 53.50 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures slipped lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar strengthened in value against other major
currencies.
   Gold settled 70 cents to 90 cents lower with August at $360 a
troy ounce; silver was 2 cents to 2.9 cents lower with September at
$5.095 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
