<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise Slightly in Thin Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices crept higher in extremely
light activity Monday with no news to influence trading.
   The closing of markets in London for a bank holiday also slowed
U.S. dealings.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose
13 cents to close at $18.64 a barrel.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also posted slight gains.
The September contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up
0.35 cent to close at 53.65 cents a gallon, and home heating oil for
September delivery rose 0.29 cent to settle at 51.72 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said there was little interest in energy futures despite
a surge of buying late in the day. With markets in Britain closed
and no news developments, the market lacked direction, they said.
   Many U.S. traders also were on vacation, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
