<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 1944EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChannelOne     08-28 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Names TV Program Advisers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications has named a
committee of 12 educators and public figures to advise the company
on its proposed classroom television network.
   American Federation of Teachers President Albert Shanker and
former Education Secretary T.H. Bell were among the members of the
panel, Whittle chairman Christopher Whittle said Sunday.
   Whittle Communications has undertaken a $200 million project to
supply television equipment and classroom programming to 6 million
students around the country by the end of 1990.
   Education groups, including the National Parent-Teacher
Association, and state officials in New York and California have
opposed Whittle's proposed 12-minute daily news programs, called
Channel One, because the broadcasts will contain two minutes of
commercials.
   Whittle said the group would help his company's classroom
programming to fit in with the needs of teachers and students.
   Shanker, who heads the nation's second-largest teachers' union,
told Whittle in an Aug. 24 letter he had ``strong reservations both
about the propriety of advertising in schools and the educational
effectiveness of the shows.''
   But he said he would join the panel on a two-year trial basis
because ``I believe it's important for my organization that I be
involved in shaping the program.''
   ``If this were a perfect world, all of America's classrooms would
be equipped with the latest technologies funded by school boards and
other government agencies,'' he wrote. ``Unfortunately, such is not
the case, and it's unlikely we will get the needed technologies
without the participation of companies like Whittle in such
initiatives.''
   Bell served under presidents Reagan, Ford and Nixon.
   Whittle spokesman David Jarrard said Bell will be the only member
paid for his work on the panel. He did not disclose how much Bell
would be paid.
   Other members of the panel included industrialist Ross Perot,
Time-Warner Chairman J. Richard Munro, author Alex Haley; and former
Tennessee governor and current University of Tennessee president
Lamar Alexander.
   The panel also included James Harvey, a staff writer for the
education report, ``A Nation at Risk;'' Matina Horner, retiring
president of Radcliff College; Janelle Leonard, director of
technology training in the Washington, D.C., public schools;
Frederick W. Smith, chairman of Federal Express; Kenneth Rossano,
chairman of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's education subcommittee;
and Joseph Scherer, education director of the National School Public
Relations Association.
</TEXT>
