<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasAir-Continental 1stLd-Writethru f01derstorm.Highsaround80.Lightwinds.
08-28 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Air-Continental, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0164,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>SAS Reportedly Interested in Buying Continental</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 10 grafs to UPDATE with analyst, union comment on possible
Continental sale.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp., which is considering a sale of
part or all of its Continental Airlines subsidiary, reportedly is
involved in advanced talks about such a transaction with
Scandinavian Airlines System and an unidentified partner.
   Talks about the form of a possible sale and the terms have been
going on for some time, and the parties have reached the point of
trying to draft a letter of intent, the Wall Street Journal reported
in Monday's editions.
   A Texas Air spokesman, however, would not confirm that any such
talks have taken place.
   ``I can't confirm or deny anything,'' spokesman Art Kent told The
Associated Press. ``It's inappropriate to comment on anything like
this.''
   Kent said if discussions with an interested party ``reach a
serious point and a letter of intent is appropriate, there will be
an appropriate disclosure.''
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo announced last Thursday that the
Houston-based airline company _ the largest in the nation _ may
consider selling a minority or controlling interest in Continental.
Strikebound Eastern Airlines is Texas Air's other airline
subsidiary, but it would not be involved in any Continental
transaction.
   Lorenzo said Texas Air officials have spoken to parties
interested in Continental, but he has not provided any details about
the talks.
   SAS already has a 9.9 percent stake in Texas Air as part of a
marketing agreement.
   If SAS is interested in buying part of Houston-based Continental,
the transaction would have to be structured in such a way that SAS
would get a minority holding. Department of Transportation rules
prevent foreign companies from having more than a 25 percent stake
in a U.S. carrier.
   Talks that began in June 1988 concerning the Texas Air marketing
agreement apparently turned to SAS possibly buying part of
Continental. That aspect has been pursued with new seriousness in
the past 30 days, an unidentified source told the Journal.
   Signs that Continental could remain profitable after massive
losses in 1987 and 1988, as well as the soaring value of airline
stocks, apparently heated up the discussions.
   Lorenzo's surprise announcement came a week after a Boston
investment firm disclosed that it holds 12 percent of Texas Air.
Loomis, Sayles &amp; Co., a Boston portfolio management company, has
said its 12 percent stake was held for investment because it
believed Texas Air would show a profit in 1990.
   The possible sale of Continental could doom Eastern, according to
securities analysts and labor leaders.
   Miami-based Eastern is in the sixth month of a strike by
Machinists union members, pilots and flight attendants, and is
flying about a third of its pre-strike 1,100 daily flights.
   ``We've always believed that the plan was to shrink Eastern and
roll it into Continental,'' said Louis A. Marchesano, an analyst
with the Philadelphia brokerage Janney Montgomery Scott Inc.
   ``The sale of Continental would mean Eastern would have to make
it on its own,'' Marchesano said Monday, ``and the risk of a
shrunken Eastern not making it is substantial.''
   Eastern, which filed for Chapter 11 protection from bankruptcy
shortly after the walkout began in March, is losing more than $1.5
million a day.
   The sale of Continental, according to Marchesano, would mean
Lorenzo ``might be leaving the airline business.''
   The Miami spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, Ron
Cole, agreed, saying that the Texas Air chairman ``may be cutting
and running.''
   A Texas Air without Continental, Cole said, would have only two
options _ continued liquidation of Eastern assets or the outright
sale of the carrier.
   Striking Eastern employees have repeatedly charged that Lorenzo
has been transferring Eastern assets to Continental, weakening
Eastern and strengthening Continental.
   ``Now that the bankruptcy has thrown a net around Eastern's
assets and stopped the upstreaming of cash,'' Cole said, ``Lorenzo
has to admit that Continental can't go it alone, that it can't
survive without sponging off Eastern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
