<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BoeingOrder     08-28 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Order,0200</SECOND>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southwest Airlines has ordered 20 additional
Boeing 737-500 twinjets, Boeing Co. said Monday.
   The exact price of the order was not announced, but Boeing
spokesman Jack Gamble said the 20 aircraft would be worth about $500
million.
   The first 10 planes, for which Southwest previously had taken
options, will be delivered in 1992, with the remaining 10 to be
delivered the following year.
   The 737-500, the newest and smallest of Boeing's commercial jets,
is undergoing certification for entry into service. The first plane
is to go to Southwest in February.
   The jet can carry 108 passengers in mixed-class seating, and up
to 132 passengers for charter flights.
   Southwest Airlines, based in Dallas, is the nation's
eighth-largest carrier and flies to 29 cities, from California to
Detroit.
   In addition to the orders announced Monday, Southwest has 33 737s
on order and options for 30 more. The orders and options are for a
mixture of the three variations of the 737: the 300, 400 and 500
series.
   Boeing has announced 679 jet aircraft orders worth a total of
$35.37 billion this year, an industry record.
</TEXT>
