<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AladdinBankruptcy     08-28 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Aladdin Bankruptcy,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Las Vegas Hotel Files For Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese businessman Ginji Yasuda filed Monday
to put his ailing Aladdin Hotel under federal bankruptcy protection,
citing debt that outstripped the resort's assets by more than $38
million.
   Yasuda, the first foreigner to be licensed to operate a Nevada
casino, reported in the Chapter 11 filing that his Ginji Corp. owed
$121.2 million to various creditors while having total assets of
$82.9 million.
   The filing, which had been expected, comes on the heels of the
Nevada Gaming Commission's decision last week to pull Yasuda's
license and give the Aladdin until next Tuesday to comply with a
list of conditions to allow its casino to remain open.
   ``This was the first step was to get some breathing room for the
hotel,'' said James Shea, an attorney who worked on the petitition.
   Gaming Commission Chairman John O'Reilly said the bankruptcy
filing did not changed the commission's insistence that the Aladdin
hire several new officers, inject $3 million in cash into the casino
and disclose the source of recent loans to the resort.
   Shea said the hotel has begun to comply with the commission's
conditions, including the hiring Monday of longtime gaming figure
Robert Brooker to be general manager.
   He said hotel officials will hold talks with gaming regulators
this week in an effort to have the $3 million requirement set aside.
   Shea said the bankruptcy filing should mean ``business as
normal'' at the hotel, with employees contuing to get paid and all
casino operations intact.
   The bankruptcy filing staves off a scheduled auction of the
Aladdin by the holder of a $32.5 million mortgage on the resort.
   Yasuda himself took the long-troubled resort out of bankruptcy in
1986 when he bought the club for $54 million and spent another $20
million in improvements.
   Yasuda was given a two-year limited gaming license in 1987 but
casino regulators became increasingly concerned over his failure to
comply with regulatory requirements and the casino's increasing
losses.
   At last week's Gaming Commission meeting, commissioners voted to
strip Yasuda of his license but allow gaming to continue at the
resort while attempts continued to sell it.
   The commission ordered that the 55-year-old Yasuda, who is
reported to be seriously ill at his Los Angeles home, stay out of
the club and remove his name from any accounts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
